Name: Agbami (ITS) Feb 16 '14
Comments:
Agbami crude oil is a light gravity, low sulfur crude (48.3 degrees
API, 0.04 wt percent sulfur) crude that it produced from the
Agbami-Ekoli field, Nigeria's largest deepwater development. The field
is located in the central part of the Niger Delta area, about 70 miles
offshore and covers OML 127 and 128. Recoverable reserves from OML 127
and 128 are 670 million boe and 396 million boe, respectively, of which
395 million boe and 236 million boe, respectively, remain (2014).
Agbami started up on July 29, 2008. Production from OML 127 and OML 128
averages 150,000 b/d and 90,000 b/d, respectively (2014). Output is
tied back to the Agbami FPSO which has a production capacity of 250,000
b/d of oil and can store up to 2.15 million boe. Chevron operates both
fields and holds 32 percent in OML 127 and 46.15 percent in OML 128.
OML 127 partners include Famfa Oil (60 percent) and Petrobras (8
percent) and Statoil holds the remaining 53.85 percent interest in OML
128
*** The GC Analysis Covers  31.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.2  deg. C.

Name: Akpo Exp Bld (Total) '09
Comments:
Akpo project is in Nigerian OML 130. There are 5 discoveries of complex
resevoirs. These include the fields Akpo, Egina, Preowei, Egina and
Kuro. The Akpo FSPO  is located as the hub of the 5 akpo structures
which are some distance from the other fields. While Total is operator,
NNPC is the majority owner. Total began developing the Akpo Field on
the Oil Mining License (OML) 130 in May 2005. Discovered in 2000, the
Akpo gas and condensate field is 200 km offshore Port Harcourt in 1,100
- 1,700 m of water. These data are from the Total (operator) web site
dated Jun 30, 2009. Sulphur below detection limit Hydrogen Sulphide
below detection limit.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  33.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   140.1  deg. C.

Name: Al Shaheen Exp Bld (ITS)Oct  '11
Comments:
Al Shaheen is a light gravity (30.5 degrees API), sour crude (2.2 wt
percent). It is produced from an oil and gas field that lies in
production sharing contract area Block 5 located 125 miles northeast of
Doha, offshore Qatar. Block 5 has 2.234 billion boe and 1.531 bcf gas
initial recoverable reserves. At the end of 2010, the remaining
reserves were estimated at 1.188 billion boe and 958 bcf gas.
Development of Al Shaheen took place in three phases. Phase 1 started
up in 1995 with an initial production rate of 100,000 b/d. Phase 2,
which started up in 2004, increased field capacity to 240,000 b/d.
Phase 3, which is an extension of the Al Shaheen field, came on stream
in 2006. Phase 3 was to increase capacity to 540,000 b/d, however due
to OPEC quotas, production will be capped to 300,000 b/d. Al Shaheen
currently produces 298,000 b/d (2010). Maersk owns and operates the
field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  15.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   128.7  deg. C.

Name: Antan (Saybolt) '11
Comments:
Antan blend is produced from several offshore fields (Adanga, Oron
West, North Oron, Ebughu and extensions, Adanga North Horst, Inagha,
Akam, Bogi and Mimbo) in OML 123 and the Abana fields in OML 114
located in Nigeria's Niger Delta. OML 123 started production in 1975
and OML114 started up in 1999. OML123 and OML114 have initial reserves
of 400 million boe and 76 million boe and remaining reserves of 135
million boe and 9 million boe, respectively. In 2011, OML 123
production averaged 48,000 b/d and OML 114 production averaged 6,000
b/d. Production from both areas are piped to the FPSO Knock Adoon
located over the nearby Antan field. The Knock Adoon has a production
capacity of 60,000 b/d and storage capacity of 1.7 million boe crude.
Sinopec owns and operates the OML123 fields and Moni Pulo owns and
operates OML114. Antan crude is a medium gravity, low sulfur crude oil
(28.7 deg API and 0.27 wt percent sulfur). The crude is predicted to
produce a high nitrogen content (10,600 ppm) vacuum residuum.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  10.9 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.6  deg. C.

Name: Arab Lt Exp Bld  HI RSH (CVX)'11
Comments:
Arab Light, also known as Arabian Light, is a light (33.2 degrees API)
and sour (1.9 weight percent sulfur) crude oil that is mainly sourced
from the Ghawar field, the largest complex of oil fields in the world.
Ghawar started up in 1951 and had initial recoverable reserves
estimated at 130 billion boe. By year end 2010, remaining reserves were
about 57.9 billion boe. Ghawar is located onshore Saudi Arabia and
includes the Ain Dar, Shedgum, Uthmaniyah and Haradh fields. Other
contributing fields are Hadriyah, Al Fadhli, Fazran,Ghawar, Khurais,
and Qatif. Output of the Arab Light blend in 2008 and 2009 was 4.9
million b/d. In 2008, the Khursaniyah project, comprising the
Khursaniyah, Al Fadhili and Abu Haydriyah fields, increased the
stream's production capacity by 500,000 b/d. In 2009, the Khurais
project added another 1.2 million boe capacity to stream. Arab Light is
exported out of the Juaymah, King Fahd, and Ras Tanura loadports. Saudi
Aramco is the sole owner and operator of the stream.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  19.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.3  deg. C.

Name: Aasgard (Statoil) Jan '16
Comments:
Asgard blend is a light (53.7 degrees API), low sulfur (0.09 wt
percent) condensate produced from several fields in the Norwegian Sea,
including Asgard, Haltenbank South, Asgard Condensate, and Yttergryta
Condensate) which are blended in the Asgard-A platform of the Asgard
FPSO then stored in the Asgard-C platform. Midgard, Smorbukk, and
Smorbukk South fields all contribute to the Asgard crude while the
Haltenbank South crude is comprised of the Kristin, Trestall, and
Tyrihans field. Asgard Condensate includes production from the Mikkel
and Morvin fields, and Yttergryta is a gas field. The Asgard
development is the largest development on the Norwegian continental
shelf. Asgard initial recoverable reserves were 650 million barrels of
oil, 466 million barrels of LPG, 108 million barrels of condensate and
7.413 tcf gas. Remaining reserves are 80 million barrels of oil, 126
million barrels of LPG, and 2.727 tcf gas (2016). Production averaged
108,000 b/d of liquids (46,000 b/d of oil and 62,000 b/d) of NGL in
2016. Each field has different owners, however Statoil operates all the
fields and has a 34.57 percent average weighted holding. Other partners
are Norway State DFI (35.69 percent), Eni (14.82 percent), Total (7.68
percent) and Exxon (7.24 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  52.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.9  deg. C.

Agbami crude oil is a light gravity, low sulfur crude (47-48 degrees

Name: Al Jurf Exp Bld (Total) '11
Comments:
Al Jurf, a medium gravity, sour crude with an API of 30.5 degrees and
sulfur content of 1.84 weight percent, is produced from an offshore oil
field located in Block 137-B in the Sabratha Basin about 62 miles off
the coast of Libya. Al Jurf came online on September 2003 and has an
estimated 1 billion boe of initial oil in place, of which 280 million
boe is recoverable. As of 2011, about 207 million boe remain. Al Jurf
has a production capacity of 45,000 b/d, however due to drilling
problems, production in 2009-2010 was held to 38,000 b/d. Production
was halted in March 2011 due to the turmoil in the country and came
back online in September 2011. By December 2011, production reached
40,000 b/d. Output is tied back to the Farwah FPSO which has a
processing capacity of 50,000 b/d and can store 912,000 boe. Total
holds 37.5 percent stake, Wintershall has 12.5 percent interest and the
Libya National Oil Corporation holds 50 percent interest. Mabruk Oil
Operations took over as operator of the field when the conflict in the
country ended in September 2011.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  12.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   130.9  deg. C.

Name: Al Rayyan Fld (ITS) '07
Comments:
Al Rayyan is a heavy (23.9 deg API), high sulfur (3.46 wt percent
sulfur) crude oil that is produced in Block 12 located offshore about
100 miles north of Doha, the capital of Qatar, in water depths of 21-41
m. Al Rayyan came on stream in November 1996 and reached a production
rate of 38,000 b/d shortly after. With the installation of the Al
Morjan platform, production capacity increased to 45,000 b/d.
Production fell from 2008 to 2010 because of water cuts but it has been
holding steady at 10,200 b/d. Initial recoverable reserves are at 92
million boe, of which 19 million boe remain. The field is declining and
is expected to expire by May 2016, but the field could potentially
produce for an additional five years. Output is tied to the Pacific
Jewel, a permanently moored FSO that has a storage capacity of 1.3
million boe. Occidental, the operator holds 92.5 percent stake and
Marubeni holds the remaining 7.5 percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  10.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.9  deg. C.

form.

Name: Access Western Blend (CVX) Feb 9
Comments:
Access Western Blend (AWB) is a medium gravity (22.2 degrees ), high
sulfur (3.71 wt percent) dilbit (diluted bitumen) with a high As
concentration (122 ppb). It is produced from MEG Energy's Christina
Lake Project and Devon's Jackfish Project, two steam assisted gravity
drainage (SAGD) heavy oil producing facilities located in Alberta,
Canada. The Christina Lake area holds an estimated 6 billion barrels of
bitumen in place, of which 1.124 billion barrels are recoverable and
about 1.026 million barrels remain. The MEG Energy operated Christina
Lake consists of three phases. Phase 1 and 2A began in 2008 and
produces 47,000 b/d (2016). Phase 2B began production in 2013 and is
expected to produce 45,000 b/d (2016). Phase 3 is in various stages of
regulatory approval, however once completed, total production capacity
is expected to reach 253,000 b/d. Devon Energy owns and operates the
Jackfish project located 10 miles SE of Conklin, Alberta. Jackfish is
also a three phase project, each with a production capacity of 35,000
b/d, in various stages of development. Phase 1 started up in 2007 and
Phases 2 and 3 started up in 2015. Total production from all three
phases is 97,000 b/d (2016). Jackfish holds 881 million barrels of
recoverable reserves, of which 827 million boe remains. Bitumen is
recovered from the oil sands using the SAGD process then diluent is
added so that it can be transported through the Access Pipeline, a two
pipeline systems that consists of a 345 km diluent pipeline (Diluent)
and a 295 kilometer blended bitumen (dilbit) pipeline. The Diluent
system originates at Edmonton and supplies diluent to the SAGD
facilities and the Blend system originates at the north end of the
Access System and delivers the AWB to Enbridge tankage at Edmonton,
Canada. Access Pipeline is a joint venture between Devon Energy (50
percent) and MEG Energy (50 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  22.8 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.1  deg. C.

Name: Access Western Blend (MAX) '11
Comments:
Access Western Blend (AWB) is a medium gravity (22.7 deg API), high
sulfur (4 wt percent) and high acid (1.7 mg KOH/g) dilbit (diluted
bitumen) produced from MEG Energy's Christina Lake Project and Devon's
Jackfish Project. Both are Steam Assisted Gravity Drainage (SAGD) heavy
oil producing facilities located in Alberta, Canada. MEG Energy s
operated Christina Lake Prospect is located next to Cenovus Energy's
operated Christina Lake project however, they are independent projects.
The entire Christina Lake area holds an estimated 6 billion barrels of
bitumen in place, of which 2.8 billion barrels are recoverable. MEG s
Christina Lake project is developing in three phases. Phase 1 began in
2008 and produces 3,000 b/d. Phase 2 initiated in 2009 and produces
22,000 b/d. Phase 2B, an expansion of Phase 2, and Phase 3 are in
various stages of regulatory approval. Once completed, total production
capacity is expected to reach 210,000 b/d. Devon Energy owns and
operates the Jackfish project located 10 miles SE of Conklin, Alberta.
Jackfish is also a three phase project in various stages of
development. Each phase will have a 35,000 b/d production capacity and
each have est-imated recoverable reserves of 300 million (900 million
boe total). Phase 1 started up in 2007 and produced 27,000-28,000 b/d
in 2010. Phase 2 is expected to reach full production in 2012 and Phase
3 planned startup is targeted for 2015. The SAGD process recovers
bitumen from oil sands by injecting steam through an injection well
into the oil sands formation to liquify the bitumen. The liquefied
bitumen flows down to the production well which is located below the
steam injection well. The bitumen and condensed water from the steam
flows to the surface wellhead and is transported to a processing
facility where the water and other impurities are removed. Diluent is
then added to the bitumen to keep it in liquid form so that it can be
transported through the Access Pipeline, a two pipeline systems that
consists of a 345 km diluent pipeline (Diluent) and a 295 km blended
bitumen (Blend) pipeline. The Diluent system originates at Edmonton and
supplies diluent to the SAGD facilities while the Blend system delivers
SAGD dilbit to Enbridge tankage at Edmonton, Canada where it is
available for upgrading in the Edmonton area and for export on the
Enbridge and KinderMorgan systems. Access Pipeline is a joint venture
between Devon Energy (50 percent) and MEG Energy (50 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  27.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   148.3  deg. C.

Name: Access Western Blend (MAX) Oct '
Comments:
Access Western Blend (AWB) is a heavy (20.9 degrees ), high sulfur
(4.08 wt percent) and high acid (1.8 mg KOH/g) crude oil produced from
MEG Energy's Christina Lake Project and Devon's Jackfish Project, two
steam assisted gravity drainage (SAGD) heavy oil producing facilities
located in Alberta, Canada. The Christina Lake area holds an estimated
6 billion barrels of bitumen in place, of which 2.46 billion barrels
are recoverable and about 2.417 million barrels remain. The MEG Energy
operated Christina Lake consists of three phases. Phase 1 and 2A began
in 2008 and produces 38,000 b/d (2014). Phase 2B began production in
2013 and is expected to produce 27,000 b/d (2014). Phase 3 is in
various stages of regulatory approval, however once completed, total
production capacity is expected to reach 253,000 b/d. Devon Energy owns
and operates the Jackfish project located 10 miles SE of Conklin,
Alberta. Jackfish is also a three phase project, each with a production
capacity of 35,000 b/d, in various stages of development. Phase 1
started up in 2007 and is currently at full production capacity. Phase
2 is expected to reach full production capacity in 2015 and Phase 3
planned startup is targeted for 2014 and will reach full capacity by
2017. Jackfish holds recoverable reserves of 900 million boe, of which
827 million boe remains. Bitumen is recovered from the oil sands using
the SAGD process then diluent is added so that it can be transported
through the Access Pipeline, a two pipeline systems that consists of a
345 km diluent pipeline (Diluent) and a 295 km blended bitumen (dilbit)
pipeline. The Diluent system originates at Edmonton and supplies
diluent to the SAGD facilities and the Blend system originates at the
north end of the Access System and delivers the AWB to Enbridge tankage
at Edmonton, Canada. Access Pipeline is a joint venture between Devon
Energy (50 percent) and MEG Energy (50 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  26.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   143.9  deg. C.

Name: Agar Dilbit (Core) '11
Comments:
Algar is part of The Great Divide project - an oil sands steam assisted
gravity drainage project located in the Athabasca oil sands region of
northeastern Alberta that is operated and owned by Connacher Oil and
Gas. The Great Divide area covers 140 square km that is split into two
development areas, Pod One and Pod Two which has been renamed Algar.
Pod One development began in 2006 and started commercial production in
2007. Algar development started in 2008 and production started up in
2010. Pod One and Algar have initial reserves of 90 million and 91
million recoverable barrels of bitumen, respectively. Remaining
reserves are 80 million and 88 million recoverable reserves,
respectively. In 2011, production at Pod One averaged 6,600 barrels of
bitumen and Algar averaged 6,600 barrels of bitumen. The Great Divide
is a heavy gravity (16.9? API), high sulfur (4.1 wt percent), viscous
(1200 cSt at 20? C) bitumen with a high total acid number (3.2 mg
KOH/g).

Name: Agbami (CVX) '16
Comments:
Agbami crude oil is a light gravity (47.2 degrees API), low sulfur
(0.04 wt percent) crude produced from the Agbami-Ekoli field, Nigeria's
largest deepwater development. The field is located in the central part
of the Niger Delta area, about 70 miles offshore and covers OML 127 and
128. Recoverable reserves from OML 127 and 128 are 714 million boe and
420 million boe, respectively, of which 276 million boe and 166 million
boe, respectively, remain (2016). Agbami started up on July 29, 2008.
Production from OML 127 and OML 128 averaged 147,000 b/d and 88,000
b/d, respectively (2016). Output is tied back to the Agbami FPSO, which
has a production capacity of 250,000 b/d of oil and can store up to
2.15 million boe. Chevron operates both fields and holds 32 percent in
OML 127 and 46.15 percent in OML 128. OML 127 partners include Famfa
Oil (60 percent) and Petrobras (8 percent) and Statoil holds the
remaining 53.85 percent interest in OML 128.

Name: Akpo Exp Bld (CVX) '11
Comments:
Akpo is a light, low sulfur condensate with an API of 45.6 deg and
sulfur content of 0.07 wt percent. The Akpo field lies in Block OM 130
which is located about 125 miles south of Port Harcourt in water depths
of 1,000 - 1,700 m in the Niger Delta, offshore Nigeria. OM 130 covers
over 500 sq miles and includes the Egina and Preowei fields, which are
separate developments. Akpo was discovered in 2000 and holds reserves
of 620 million barrels of condensate and more than 1 Tcf of gas. The
field came on stream in March 2009 and in 2010 production averaged
175,000 b/d. Production in 2011 is expected to fall by at least 10
percent because of a fire onboard the drillship GSF Jack Ryan which
delayed development drilling in early 2011. Drilling is expected to
recommence by late 2011 and production should rebound back to 175,000
b/d by 2012. The Akpo development consists of 22 producing wells, 20
water and two gas injections wells. Output is tied back to the Akpo
FPSO which has a production capacity of 225,000 b/d and a storage
capacity of 2 million boe. Total has a 24 percent stake and operates
the field on behalf of Petrobras (15 percent). China National Offshore
Oil Corp. holds a 45 percent stake and Nigerian National South Atlantic
Petroleum (Sapetro) of Nigeria holds the remaining 15 percent stake.

Name: Al Shaheen Exp Bld (ITS) '04
Comments:
Laboratory report no. Fuj/22595a/04 summary & comments general: the Al
Shaheen crude oil samples were received from Intertek Caleb Brett Qatar
branch on 13th September 2004. The samples were in 2 x 25 ltrs iata
cans. The labels indicated that the samples  were drawn during a crude
transfer on 1st September 2004. Appearance & initial examination: the
sample observed to be liquid at room temperature with good flow
properties. After cooling (to zero degree centigrade) and
homogenization of the sample. H2S c ontent on the vapour phase of the
samples within the original containers were measured and noted to be 80
ppm and 40 ppm respectively. A representative portion of the sample was
drawn and tested for API which observed to be 26.51 API. Distillation
and an alysis: the distillation of the sample was carried out in two
major steps as per ASTM D 2892 (15 theoretical plate column) & ASTM D
5236 (vacuum potstill) methods. The yield pattern of each fraction
collected are tabulated in percentage weight and percen tage volume and
in graphical form. Results of the analysis carried on the various
fractions are shown in pages 8-17. Some of the properties are also
presented in chart form in pages 18-21. Please do not hesitate to
contact us for any additional informati on or clarifications that you
may require on this analysis.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  11.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   131.0  deg. C.

gas of initial recoverable reserves. At the end of 2010, the remaining
reserves were estimated at 1.188 billion boe and 958 bcf gas.
Development of Al Shaheen took place in three phases. Phase 1 started
up in 1995 and had an initial production rate of 100,000 b/d. Phase 2,
which started up in 2004, increased field capacity to 240,000 b/d.
Phase 3, an extension of the Al Shaheen field, came on stream in 2006.
Phase 3 was to increase capacity to 540,000 b/s, however due to OPEC
quotas, production will be capped to 300,000 b/d. Al Shaheen currently
produces 298,000 b/d (2010). Maersk owns and operates the field.

Name: Alaskan North Slope (PTI) Oct '1
Comments:
Alaskan North Slope (ANS) crude is transported through the 800 mile
Trans Alaskan Pipeline System (TAPS) to the port of Valdez. The
pipeline, which transport all the oil produced in the Alaskan North
Slope, gathers oil from three main facilities, the BP-operated Prudhoe
Bay, which supplies about 325,000 b/d and ConocoPhillips operated
Kuparuk River, which contributes about 150,000 b/d, and Alpine, which
accounts for approximately 80,000 b/d, as well as 21 secondary
processing facilities or in-field satellites. TAPS (ANS) began
production in 1977 and has a capacity of 2,100,000 b/d. TAPS
transported about 503,417 b/d of crude oil in 2015. ANS holds about
32.8 billion boe and 137 Tcf of natural gas. ANS quality is seasonal
and the API can range from 30 degrees during the summer months to 32
degrees during the winter months. Sulfur content is typically 1 wt
percent. TAPS (ANS) is operated by Aleyska Pipeline Company and joint
venture participants are BP (48.44 percent), ConocoPhillips (29.21
percent), ExxonMobil (20.99 percent), and Chevron (1.36 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  22.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.9  deg. C.

Name: Alaskan NSlope PL Mix (CVX)'09
Comments:
The 800-mile-long Trans Alaska Pipeline System (TAPS) is one of the
world's largest pipeline systems. Starting in Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's
North Slope, TAPS stretches through rugged and beautiful terrain to
Valdez, the northernmost ice-free port in North America.  The oil that
is shipped from Valdez is called ANS,   It is medium gravity although
it is getting lighter of late. Is it medium is Sulfur and has a
tendency toward naphthenicity.  In general, it makes suitable high
value products and is usable for the manufacture of high VI automotive
lube oil if hydrocracking technology is used. SILVER below detection

Name: Alba (CVX) Feb 11 '15
Comments:
Alba has been in production since January 1994. It is heavy crude that
is an economically attractive option in complex refineries already
running, or contemplating running, heavy crude oils. alba is a
biodegraded crude: biodegradation by microorganisms from an anoxic
aquifer previously contaminated by natural gas condensate, results in
entire n-alkanes of this oil (C13-C34) were consumed-- as evident in GC
analyses. Alba crude oil, which is naturally depleted in n-alkanes,
resulted in a relatively modest stimulation of methanogenesis and
sulfate reduction
*** The GC Analysis Covers   1.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   128.2  deg. C.

Name: Alba (Total) '11
Comments:
The Alba oil field is located 125 mile NE of Aberdeen, Scotland in
Block 16/26 areas A and C in the UK North Sea. Alba, which began
producing in 1994, had initial reserves at 446 million boe and by year
end 2011, about 56 million boe remain. Production in 2011 averaged
27,000 b/d. Alba is heavy gravity crude (19.6 degrees API) with a
sulfur content of 1.23 wt percent and a high crude acid number
(TANequal to 1.5 mg KOH/g). Production is stored in an 825,000 bbl
storage capacity Alba FSU and exported through shuttle tankers mainly
to refineries in North West Europe. Some cargoes are exported to the
Mediterranean and the US. Chevron, the operator, holds 23.37 percent
interest. Other partners are ConocoPhillips with 23.43 percent, Statoil
with 17 percent, BP with 13.3 percent, Total with 12.65 percent, Itochu
with 8 percent, and Endeavour Energy with 2.25 percent. In December
2011, it was announced that Endeavor will acquire ConocoPhillips share
bringing Endeavor's equity to 25.68 percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   1.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   129.0  deg. C.

Name: Albacora Leste (Saybolt) '10
Comments:
Albacora Leste, also known as Albacora East, is a heavy gravity (19.5
degrees API), low sulfur crude oil (0.5 wt percent) with a high total
acid number (1.98 mg KOH/g). The deepwater field lies in water depths
of 800-2000 m and is located east of the separate Albacora field in the
Campos Basin, offshore Rio de Janeiro. Although production began in
1998, full field production did not start until 2006. Albacora Leste
has initial recoverable reserves of 467 million boe, of which 262
million boe (2011) remain. In 2011, production averaged 82,000 b/d and
has been steadily declining since reaching its peak production rate of
156,000 b/d in 2007. Output from the field is tied back to the P-50
FPSO which has a production capacity of 180,000 b/d and a storage
capacity of 1.7 million boe. Petrobras operates the field and has a 90
percent share. Repsol Brasil holds 10 percent share.

Name: Alberta Syncrude (CVX) '10
Comments:
Syncrude Synthetic (SSB), a light (30.8 degree API) gravity sweet
(0.187 weight percent sulfur) synthetic crude oil, is produced from the
Syncrude Canada Project. The project, which began producing in 1978,
upgrades bitumen, a black and asphalt like oil, into lighter
hydrocarbon streams, such as naphtha, Light Gas Oil (LGO) and Heavy Gas
Oil (HGO), and blends them to create a light, low sulfur synthetic
crude oil. The bitumen is from the Athabasca Oil Sands Deposit located
north of Fort McMurray, Alberta, Canada. The reserves hold
approximately 1.7 trillion barrels of bitumen and are considered the
largest petroleum resource in the world. With current available
technologies, over 175 billion barrels is recoverable. The project
produces about 350,000 barrels of synthetic crude oil each day.
Syncrude Canada Ltd, a joint venture company comprised of Canadian Oil
Sands Trust (36.74 percent), Sinopec (9.03 percent), Imperial Oil (25
percent), Nippon Oil (5 percent), Murphy Oil Co. Ltd. (5 percent),
Nexen Inc. (7.23 percent), and Petro-Canada (12 percent) owns and
operates the project.

Name: Albian Muskeg River Heavy 12-308
Comments:
Albian Muskeg River Heavy crude oil is produced from bitumen extracted
from the Muskeg River Mine which is situated on OSL 13, north of Fort
McMurray in Northern Alberta, Canada. OSL 13 contains more than 5
billion barrels of mineable bitumen. In its current design, the Muskeg
River Mine will recover 1.8 billion bbls of bitumen over 36 years and
has a production capacity of 155,000 b/d. As part of the Athabasca Oil
Sands Project (ASOP), the bitumen recovered from the mine is
transported to the Scotford Upgrader, located near Saskatchewan,
Alberta, where hydrogen-addition technology will be used to upgrade the
high viscosity bitumen into synthetic crude oils. Albian Muskeg River
Heavy is medium gravity, high sulfur crude (22 degrees API and 3.4 wt
percent sulfur) with a high arsenic content (70 ppb). ASOP is currently
undergoing expansion and debottlenecking projects that will increase
capacity by about 100,000 b/d and 85,000 b/d, respectively. Shell
Canada operates the ASOP and has a 60 percent interest. Other joint
venture partners are Chevron Canada Limited (20 percent) and Marathon
Oil Sands LP (20 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  22.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.2  deg. C.

Comments:

started producing in 1926 and has since ceased production. Poza Rica
and Lobina started up in 1930 and 2006, respectively, and had initial
recoverable reserves of 1.432 billion and 11 million boe, respectively,

respectively. Altamira is a heavy (15 degrees API), high sulfur (5 wt

atmospheric and vacuum residuum yields as well as high amounts of

operator and owner of the blend.

Name: Alvheim Exp Bld (CVX) '08
Comments:
Sample of Alvheim blend with the addition of production from Vilje
field which came onstream in 2008. Alvheim was discovered in North Sea
in 1998 and brought online in  2007 by operator Marathon. The Alvheim
blends production from  Kneler, Boa, Kameleon fields and now Vilje is
estimated to contain resources of approximately 180 mmboe. Kneler is
eight miles west of the Heimdal platform and was drilled into the
prolific Heimdal formation to a total depth of 7,425 feet below sea
level, encountering a net oil column of 115 feet. Boa was drilled to a
total depth of 7,531 feet below sea level and encountered a 174-foot
gross hydrocarbon column, with 82 gross feet of gas on top of 92 gross
feet of oil in high-quality sands. There will be 10 producing wells and
two water disposal wells in the Phase 1 drilling program, which will
continue through the fourth quarter of 2008. A Phase 2 drilling program
is planned in 2010/2011 for further production wells.The development

Name: Alvheim Exp Bld (CVX) '11
Comments:
The Alvheim field is located on the Norwegian Continental Shelf, west
of Haugesund and close to the UK border in 125 meters (410 feet) water
depth. Light, low sulfur crude oil with an API of 34 degrees and 0.15
weight percent sulfur, is produced from the field. Alvheim was
discovered in 1998 and after a series of delays, was finally brought
online in 2008. In 2009, the production rate ranged from
125,000-135,000 b/d. Most of the recoverable oil is from three main
reservoirs: Kneler, Kameleon and Boa. Combined initial reserves from
these three reservoirs were estimated at 255.4 million bbl, of which
171.1 million bbl remain (2009). Vilje, also known as Klegg, and Volund
fields holds 39 million bbl and 45.3 million bbl, respectively. Phase 2
of the Alvheim field is expected to bring three additional development
wells from the Marihone and Viper exploration discoveries online in
2011. Alvheim s output is loaded into the Alvheim FPSO and is then
transported via shuttle tankers. Marathon oil is the operator and holds
a 65 percent stake in the Kneler, Kameleon, and Boa reservoirs.
ConocoPhillips (20 percent) and Lundin Petroleum (15 percent) own the
remaining interests. Marathon also operates the Volund and has a 65
percent equity stake, with Lundin holding the 35 percent. Vilje is
operated by Statoil who holds a 28.6 percent interest with joint
venture partners Marathon (46.9 percent) and Total (24.24 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  17.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.1  deg. C.

Name: Amukpe Exp Bld (CVX) '11
Comments:
The Amukpe field is an onshore oil field located in the northwestern
part of the Niger Delta on license OML 38. It was first discovered in
1970 and began production in 1972. Amukpe is a light gravity (43 deg
API), low sulfur (0.09 weight percent) crude oil that contains high
amounts of mercury (greater than 200 ppb). Crude is produced through a
45,000 b/d capacity flowstation and then transported through the
Amukpe-Rapele pipeline to the Forcados terminal where it is blended
into the Forcados grade. The Amukpe field had initial recoverable
reserves of 60 million boe, of which 42 million remain (2010). In 2010,
production averaged at 5,000 b/d. The Nigerian Petroleum Development
Corporation (NPDC) operates the field and holds 24.75 percent interest.
Septa Energy holds 30.25 percent and SEPLAT Petroleum Development, a
consortium with two Nigerian companies, Platform Petroleum and Shebah
Petroleum and Maurel and Prom, holds 45 percent interest.

Name: ANS Exp Bld (CVX) Mar' 12
Comments:
Alaskan North Slope (ANS) crude is transported through the 800 mile
Trans Alaskan Pipeline System (TAPS) to the port of Valdez. The
pipeline, which transports all the oil produced in the Alaskan North
Slope, gathers oil from three main facilities, the BP-operated Prudhoe
Bay, which supplies about 325,000 b/d and ConocoPhillips operated
Kuparuk River, which contributes about 150,000 b/d, and Alpine, which
accounts for approximately 80,000 b/d, as well as 21 secondary
processing facilities or in-field satellites. TAPS (ANS) began
production in 1977 and is currently transporting about 660,000 b/d,
less than half of its peak throughput of 2,055,000 b/d achieved in 1998
and one third of the pipeline's total capacity. It is estimated that
TAPS total throughput through 2009 is about 16 billion boe and that ANS
holds about 36 billion boe and 137 Tcf of natural gas. ANS quality is
seasonal and the API can range from 30 degrees during the summer months
to 32 degrees during the winter months. Sulfur content is typically 1
wt percent. TAPS (ANS) is operated by Aleyska Pipeline Company and
joint venture participants are BP (46.93 percent), ConocoPhillips
(28.29), ExxonMobil (20.34 percent), Koch (3.08 percent) and Chevron
(1.36 percent).

Name: Arab Extra Light  (CVX) '11
Comments:
Arab Extra Light is a light gravity, medium-sulfur (API 38.1 degree and
sulfur content of 1.2 weight percent) crude oil that is produced from
four different fields located onshore in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia
(Abqaiq, Berri, Shaybah, and Qatif). Qatif, situated in the Gulf Coast
of eastern Saudi Arabia, started up in 1946 and is the oldest
contributor to the blend. Abqaiq and Berri, located in the Kingdom's
Eastern Province, came onstream on 1948 and 1968, respectively.
Shaybah, the newest stream to come on line, came onstream 1998 and is
located in the Rub al-Khali desert. Due to OPEC quotas, production in
2009 was held to about 1.1 million b/d. Qatif produces 100,000 b/d
(2004). Output for the Abqaiq and Berri fields are 400,000 and 300,000
b/d respectively (2009). Shaybah production capacity is 1.45 million
b/d, however it has yet to be reached. Quatif reserves are 8.4 billion
boe, Abqaiq reserves are estimated at 17 billion boe, Berri reserves
are 10 billion boe, and Shaybah has an estimated 18-19 billion boe.
Saudi Arabian Oil Co (Saudi Aramco) owns and operates the fields.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  24.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   138.9  deg. C.

Name: Arab Heavy (ITS) Jan 30 '14
Comments:
Arabian Heavy, also known as Safaniyah, is a medium gravity, high
sulfur crude (API 27.3 degrees and 3 wt percent). The supergiant
Safaniyah field, which has 15.983 billion boe remaining reserves
(2010), is the main contributor to the grade. The Zuluf Heavy and
Manifa fields, which have remaining recoverable reserves of 12.966
billion and 9.499 billion boe, respectively, also contributes to the
blend. Output from the Safaniyah and Zuluf fields, which came onstream
on 1957 and 1973, respectively, is transported through eight offshore
pipelines to three onshore trunk lines to Ras Tanura and Juaymah
loading ports. The redevelopment of the Manifa field restarted
production in 2013 and will increase Arab Heavy s production capacity
from 1.5 million b/d to 2 million b/d once it reaches full capacity. In
2012, production averaged 1 million b/d. Saudi Aramco is both the owner
and operator of this grade.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  14.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.4  deg. C.

Name: Arab Medium (CVX) Jan '14
Comments:
Arab Medium, also known as Arabian Medium, is produced from the Abu
Sa'fah, Marjan, Qatif, and Zuluf fields. Abu S'afah, a super-giant
offshore field located along the Saudi and Bahrain border, came on
stream in 1966 and had initial reserves of 20.181 billion boe.
Production and reserves are split between Bahrain and Saudi, however
Saudi Aramco operates the field. Marjan, also a super-giant offshore
field, is located on the Saudi side of the Iran-Saudi Border. Marjan
came onstream in 1973 and initial reserves were 8.963 billion boe. The
Qatif field was brought onstream in 1946 and reserve estimates were
8.553 billion boe. Qatif is an onshore oil field that is located in
north-east Saudi Arabia and extends into the shallow offshore of the
Arabian Gulf. Zuluf, with initial reserves of 20.181 billion boe, is
the largest of all contributing fields. Zuluf, which came onstream in
1973, is adjacent to the Marjan field in northern Saudi Arabia. Saudi
Aramco, the owner and operator of the grade, exports Arab Medium grade
though the Ras Tanura and Juaymah loadports. Arab Medium is a light
gravity (31.3 degrees API) crude oil with a sulfur concentration of
2.44 wt percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  17.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.7  deg. C.

Name: Arab X Lt Exp Bld (CVX) '09
Comments:
2009 sample  Arab Extra Light, other names Berri, Shaybah Blend
Arab
Extra Light is a Light , medium-sulfur Mideast Crude oil similar to
top quality Abu Dhabi grades, It is suitable for making Kerosene and
Petrochemical naphtha, but , unlike west African and North sea crude
oil grades, it is not especially good for gasoline manufacturing.
Arab Extra Light is sourced from the Berri and Abqaiq Fields and since
1998 from the Shaybah field in the Rub al-Khali desert near the border
with Abu Dhabi. Shaybah, which contains 15 bbl of reserves contributes
roughly 500,000 barrels per day to Arab Extra Light Flows, the second
phase of the Shaybah development, which is due to be completed by
2008, will boost production by further 300,000-400,000 b/d from the
mid 2006 levels of 1.4 million b/d. the field also produces 880
million cubic feet per day of associated gas. The Shaybah  complex
includes three separation plants and a 636 km pipeline to connect the
field to Abqaiq, the closest gathering center, for  blending with Arab
light crude (Berri and Abqaiq streams).  The Crude is produced
entirely by Saudi Arabian Oil Co (Saudi Aramco). 100% State owned
descendant of the Aramco consortium of Chevron, Texaco, Exxon, and
Mobil.

Name: Arab XL Exp Bld (CVX) Apr 19'11
Comments:
Arab Extra Light is a light gravity, medium-sulfur (39-40? API and
sulfur content of 1 wt percent) crude oil that is produced from four
different fields located onshore in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia
(Abqaiq, Berri, Shaybah, and Qatif). Qatif, situated in the Gulf Coast
of eastern Saudi Arabia, started up in 1946 and is the oldest
contributor to the blend. Abqaiq and Berri, located in the Kingdom's
Eastern Province, came onstream on 1948 and 1968, respectively.
Shaybah, the newest stream to come on line, came onstream 1998 and is
located in the Rub al-Khali desert. Due to OPEC quotas, production in
2009 and 2010 was held to about 1.1 million b/d. Qatif produces 100,000
b/d (2004). Production capacity for the Abqaiq and Berri fields are
400,000 and 300,000 b/d, respectively (2011). Shaybah production
capacity is 1.45 million b/d, however it has yet to be reached. Quatif
reserves are 8.4 billion boe, Abqaiq reserves are estimated at 17
billion boe, Berri reserves are 10 billion boe, and Shaybah has an
estimated 18-19 billion boe. Saudi Arabian Oil Co (Saudi Aramco) owns
and operates the fields.

Name: Argonauta (Shell) '07
Comments:
Argonauta is largest of four fields that comprise the Parque das
Conchas project, also known as the BC-10 development, located offshore
Brazil in the Campos Basin. Argonauta is a heavy (15.5 degrees ), low
sulfur (0.5 wt percent), viscous (5880 cSt at 20 degrees C) and acidic
(3.6 mg KOH/G) crude oil that is expected to produce a vacuum gas oil
and vacuum residuum with high nitrogen concentrations (3330 ppm and
10900 ppm, respectively). It is also expected to have a high
atmospheric residuum yield (79 vol percent). The field started
production in 2010. Phase 2 of the development started in Oct 2013
increasing production from 13,000 b/d to 36,000 b/d. Initial
recoverable reserves were estimated at 132 million boe and remaining
reserves are at 122 million boe. Output is tied back to the Espirito
Santo FPSO which can process up to 100,000 b/d of heavy crude.
Participants of the field are Shell (operator, 50 percent), Petrobras
(35 percent), and ONGC (15 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers    .9 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   131.9  deg. C.

Name: Aseng Exp Bld (ITS) '11
Comments:
The Noble Energy operated Aseng field, formerly known as Benita, is
located in Block I offshore Equatorial Guinea and covers part of the
Douala Basin. In addition to the Aseng field, Block I also holds the
Diega and Yolanda field. Adjacent to Block I is the Alen field,
formerly known as Belinda, in Block O. As a result of Block I and O
unitization, Alen will be developed and production will be tied to the
Aseng faciliies. Aseng produces a medium gravity (29.3 degrees API) low
sulfur (0.25 wt percent) crude oil with a high crude pour point
temperature (97 degrees F, 36 degrees C) and high measured lead
concentration (119 ppb). Aseng was discovered in June 2007 and had
initial recoverable reserves of 136 million boe, 15 million bbl of
condensate, and 500 bcf of gas. First oil was achieved on November
2011. Total liquids production in 2012 is expected to reach 50,000 b/d
(45,000 b/d oil and 5,000 b/d condensate). Peak oil production of
47,510 b/d is anticipated for 2015. Output is tied back to the Aseng

Comments:

was 200,000 b/d. Each field has different owners, however Statoil
operates all the fields and has a 46.45 percent average weighted
holding. Average holdings for Norwegian owned Petro is 19.12 percent,
Eni is 12.77 percent, Total is 11.68 percent and Exxon is 9.98 percent.

technology. The AOSP started up in 2003 and bitumen production averaged

percent interest.

Name: Athabasca UTF Bitumn(Shell)'07
Comments:
The Ells River oil sands leases are located some 12 miles (20
kilometers) west of Fort McKay and 26 miles (42 kilometers) southwest
of our joint venture Athabasca Oil Sands Project (AOSP). As opposed to
AOSP, which is an oil sands mining operation, the Ells River leases
have potential for recovery using Steam Assisted Gravity Drainage
(SAGD). This process uses steam and horizontal wells to extract the
bitumen in situ - meaning in place and without excavating the land.
this heavy tar sand bitumen was distilled with conventional protocols.
 Data on chemistry is sparse.  We used the distillation data to better
estimate the cutpt of the vac resid since these materials tend to
crack as the operators push to the desired endpt.  The results is an
under-reporting of the achieved endpt.  The difference in endpt was
75*F higher than the reported nominal D5236 cutpt.  no fluidity,
smoke, aniline data; sparse vis data.  Estimates from ATARS107 were
used as needed for guidance.

Comments:

Chirag, and Guneshli fields came on stream in 2005, 1997, and 2008,
respectively. The ACG fields have recoverable reserves estimated at
6.054 billion boe. Remaining reserves are at 3.909 billion boe (2014).
Production averaged 639,000 b/d in 2013. The ACG fields are owned by
the Azerbaijan International Operating Co. (AIOC), a consortium led by
BP, the operator with 37.43 percent interest, and includes Chevron
Corporation (11.27 percent), Inpex Corporation (10.96 percent), SOCAR
(Azeri State Oil Co, 10 percent), Statoil (8.56 percent), ExxonMobil (8

Name: Azeri Light Suspa (XOM) APR '14
Comments:
Azeri Light Supsa, also known as Azeri Light, is a light gravity (35.6
degrees API) low sulfur (0.15 wt percent) crude oil that is loaded from
the Supsa or Batumi ports, both located on the Black Sea coast of
Georgia. Azeri is produced from the Azeri, Chirag, and Guneshli (ACG)
located in the Caspian Sea, offshore Azerbaijan. Most of the crude is
transported to the Mediterranean via the Baku-Tbilisi-Ceyhan (BTC) and
sold as Azeri BTC. The remaining volumes are sent to Supsa or Batumi
and sold as Azeri Light Suspa. During the first half of 2013, ACG
production averaged 672,000 b/d and included 73,000 b/d from Chirag and
135,000 b/d of Guneshli fields as well as 152,000 b/d of Azeri, 52,000
b/d from Central Azeri, 194,000 b/d from West Axeri, and 118,000 b/d
from East Azeri. Chirag was the first field to go online in 1997,
followed by Azeri in 2005 and Guneshli in 2008. Initial recoverable
reserves were estimated at 6 billion boe and remaining recoverable
reserves (2014) is currently estimated at 3.909 billion boe. The ACG
fields are owned by the Azerbaijan International Operating Co. (AIOC),
a consortium consisting of BP, the operator with 37.43 percent share,
Chevron Corporation with 11.27 percent share, Inpex Corporation with
10.96 percent share, Socar (Azeri State Oil Co.) with 11.65 percent
share, Statoil with 8.56 percent, ExxonMobil with 8 percent, Turkish
Petroleum (TPAO) with 6.75 percent, Itochu Corp. with 4.3 percent, and
Hess with 2.72 percent.

Name: Azurite Exp Bld (Murphy) '09
Reference: Crude Brochure set by Clare Smit
Comments:
Azurite Crude Oil is a medium heavy, low-sulphur crude oil produced in
the territorial waters of the Republic of Congo. The gravity is 25.0
degree API, sulphur content averages 0.56% with a 0.85 TAN. Refiners
with hydrocracking capabilities will find the high gas oil content
particularly attractive. Production began in August 2009 and the
facility has a design capacity of 40,000 Barrels per day. The Azurite
Terminal is located offshore Congo, 130 km from Pointe Noire in 1400
meters of water, at approximately 05 deg 38 min S, 10 deg 59 min E. The
terminal, operated by Murphy West Africa Ltd., utilizes the industry's
first FDPSO (Floating Drilling Production Storage and Offloading)
vessel. During the drilling phase, vessels up to Suezmax size are
acceptable to load part cargoes of approx. 500,000 Barrels. After the
drilling phase is completed, the terminal will be able to accommodate
VLCC's as a first or second load port to lift up to 1,000,000 Barrel
cargoes. Sulphur below detection limit Hydrogen Sulphide below
detection limit
*** The GC Analysis Covers   6.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.7  deg. C.

Comments:

Sud) block offshore Republic of Congo. Quality of the crude is
unknown.  The Azurite development is located in about 4,500 feet of
water and utilizes the industry's first Floating Production Storage
and Offloading facility with drilling capability (FDPSO). The FDPSO
has storage capacity of 1.3 million barrels of oil and the capability
to process 40,000 barrels of oil per day. Murphy Oil Corporation
serves as operator and has a 50 per cent working interest in the
Azurite field and the MPS block. Partners are PA Resources (35 per
cent) and Societe Nationale Petroles du Congo (15 per cent).The future
will include production from Tourquise. The Turquoise Marine-1
discovery is approximately 17 miles from Azurite.  This is a HAC with
high nitrogen and may be a competitor to Alba.

Name: Bach Ho (ITS) May 11 '14
Comments:
Bach Ho, also known as the White Tiger, is Vietnam's largest oil field
and includes the Bach Ho, Bach Ho Northeast, Rong, and Nam Rong-Doi Moi
fields. It is located off the southeast coast of Vietnam in the
southern Cuu Long Basin in Blocks 09-1 and 09-3. Bach Ho was discovered
in 1975 and began producing in 1986. Rong came on stream in 1994 and
Bach Ho Northeast as well as Nam Rong-Doi Moi came onstream in 2010.
Initial recoverable reserves were 1.718 billion boe and 907 bcf of gas,
of which about 188 million boe and 108 bcf of gas remain (2014).
Despite the addition of the Bach Ho Northeast and Nam Rong-Doi Moi
fields, output has been in decline. Average output was 118,000 b/d in
2013 and 106,000 b/d in 2014. Bach Ho is a light (39.1 degrees API),
waxy, low sulfur crude (0.04 wt percent) crude oil with a high measured
pour point (90 degrees F). The field is owned and operated by
Vietsovpetro, a 50:50 joint venture between Petrovietnam and Russia's
Zarubezhneft.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  14.8 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.8  deg. C.

Name: Bach Ho (ITS) Nov '12
Comments:
Bach Ho Heavy, also known as the White Tiger, includes the Bach Ho,
Bach Ho Northeast, Rong, and Nam Rong-Doi Moi fields. It is located
offshore the southeast coast of Vietnam in the southern Cuu Long Basin.
The Bach Ho field was discovered in 1975 and began producing in 1986.
Rong came on stream in 1994 and Bach Ho Northeast as well as Nam
Rong-Doi Moi came onstream in 2010. Initial recoverable reserves were
1.577 billion boe and 673 bcf of gas. As of January 1, 2011 about 150
million boe and 57 bcf of gas remain. In 2010, ouput averaged 140,000
b/d. All of Bach Ho production is processed at a local refinery
however, due to increased production from heavier fields and decreased
production from lighter fields, the grade is now a lower gravity ( 35
degrees API) crude than it had been previously (40 degrees API) and is
no longer suitable feedstock for that refinery. The heavier Bach Ho
grade is still a low sulfur (0.07 wt percent sulfur) crude oil that has
a high crude pour point ( 71 degrees F). The field is owned and
operated by Vietsovpetro, a joint venture between Petrovietnam (51
percent) and Russia's Zarubezhneft (49 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  12.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.6  deg. C.

Name: Bachaquero (CVX) Mar '13
Comments:
The Bachaquero field is located in the PDVSA operated Maracaibo Basin
in the western region of Venezuela. Bachaquero, which also produces the
BC-22, BC-17, and BC-24 grades, was discovered in 1930 and had initial
reserves of 8.4 billion boe, of which 149 million boe remain (2012).
Current total production at Bachaquero is 55,000 b/d (2012). Bachaquero
is a heavy gravity (11.4 degrees API), high sulfur (2.7 wt percent),
acidic (3.6 mg KOH/g) and viscous (30,300 CSt at 20 degrees C) crude
with a high measured arsenic content (238 ppb). The crude is expected
to produce a high atmospheric residuum (ARES) yield (80 vol percent)
and vacuum residuum (VRES) yield (42 vol percent). The VRES is expected
to have high Nickel  Vanadium content (1070 ppm). PDVSA (60 percent)
and Shell (40 percent) own the grade through a joint venture called
Petroregional del Lago.

Name: Badak (Total) '09
Comments:
The Badak oil field is located on the east coast of Kalimantan,
Indonesia. Most of the field lies in the onshore Sanga Sanga PSC,
however a small portion of the field extends to into the Offshore
Mahakam contract area. Badak came onstream in 1974 and was estimated to
have initial reserves of 26 million barrels of condensate and 17
million barrels of oil. Remaining reserves are 5 million barrels
condensate and 2 million barrels oil (2010). Production from Badak is
mixed with other producing fields in the Sanga Sanga PSC, including
Nilam, Pamaguan, Wailawi, Lampake, Semberah, and Mutiara, and then
piped to the Santan Terminal where it is blended with the Attaka grade.
Total liquids production from the Sanga Sanga PSC averaged 21,000 b/d
in 2011. The Sanga Sanga PSC is operated by Virginia Indonesia Company
(VICO), and owners include BP and Eni with 37.8125 percent interest
each, Chinese Petroleum Corp with 20 percent interest and Universe Gas
and Oil with 4.375 percent interest.

Name: Bakken - North Dakota Sweet
Comments:
The Bakken Formation is a large rock unit from the Late Devonian to
Early Mississippian age occupying about 200,000 square miles (520,000
km2) of the subsurface of the Williston Basin, covering northwestern
South Dakota, and southern Saskatchewan and Manitoba, Canada. Bakken
contains 3 to 4.3 billion barrels of technically recoverable oil.
Production began in 1953 and cumulative production through 2008 was 135
million boe. The development and application of horizontal drilling and
horizontal fracturing have boosted production rates for 2010 to 350,000
b/d. Oil is transported through the North Dakota Pipeline System, a
161,000 bpd pipeline operated by Enbridge Energy Partners, LP. The
330-mile crude oil gathering and 620-mile interstate transportation
system gathers crude oil from points near producing wells to
Clearbrook, Minn. From there, it is either connected to the Lakehead
System, a 1,900 mile pipeline system that transports crude oil from
Western Canada to the Gulf Coast, or to a third-party pipeline that
transports crude oil to refineries in the Minneapolis/St. Paul area.
Several companies are operating in the Bakken formation; most notable
are Hess Corporation, Marathon Oil, Continental Resources Inc., and
Whiting Petroleum Corporation.

Name: Bakken Bld (Saybolt) '08
Comments:
The Bakken Formation was named in 1953 from core samples taken by
Amerada Petroleum from the H. O. Bakken No.1 well in Williams County.
The Bakken Formation, initially described by geologist J.W. Nordquist
in 1953, is a rock unit from the Late Devonian to Early Mississippian
age occupying about 200,000 square miles of the subsurface of the
Williston Basin, covering parts of Montana, North Dakota, and
Saskatchewan. The rock formation consists of three members: lower
shale, middle dolomite, and upper shale. The shales were deposited in
relatively deep marine conditions, and the dolomite was deposited as a
coastal carbonate bank during a time of shallower water. The middle
dolomite member is the principal oil reservoir, roughly two miles below
the surface. Both the upper and lower shale members are organic-rich
marine shale. The greatest Bakken oil production comes from Elm Coulee
Oil Field, Richland County, Montana, where production began in 2000 and
is expected to ultimately total 270 million barrels. In 2007,
production from Elm Coulee averaged 53,000 barrels per day. However, N
Dakota is where current production is focused. New interest developed
in 2007 when EOG Resources out of Houston, Texas reported that a single
well it had drilled into an oil-rich layer of shale below Parshall,
North Dakota was anticipated to produce 700,000 barrels (111,000 m3) of
oilThis, combined with other factors, including an oil-drilling tax
break enacted by the state of North Dakota in 2007, shifted attention
in the Bakken from Montana to the North Dakota side. The number of
wells drilled in the North Dakota Bakken jumped from 300 in 2006 to 457
in 2007.  Crude from  Mountrail County wells generally has API gravity
between 40-45. this sample is crude aggregated at Truck stations in
N.DAKOTA and MONTANA and loaded on to railroad cars. Data are very
limited and provide no molecules.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  25.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.5  deg. C.

WHILE THE FREEZE ON ONE OF THE LIGHT FRACTIONS

Name: Basra (XOM) '16
Comments:
Basra, formerly known as Basra Light, is a light (29.9 degrees API),
high sulfur (2.9 wt percent) crude, produced from several southern
Iraqi fields. The blend consists of production from the Rumalia (34
degrees API), West Qurna 1 (19.6 - 37.3 degrees API), Ahdab (33 - 36
degrees API), and Halfaya (28 degrees API) fields. Rumalia, the main
component, started up in 1956 and has remaining recoverable reserves of
15.48 billion boe (2014). Current remaining reserves (2014) for West
Qurna One, which began production in 1976, is 15.7 billion, Ahdab,
started in 2011, is 1.06 billion boe, and Halfaya, which has been in
production since 2005, is 4.87 billion boe. Rumalia partners are BP
(Operator with 38 percent), CPNC (37 percent), and state owned State
Oil Marketing Organisation (25 percent). West Qurna One is operated by
ExxonMobil (25 percent). State owned Iraqi Oil Exploration Company and
PetroChina each holds 25 percent, Shell holds 15 percent and Pertamina
holds 10 percent. Ahdab is operated by CNPC (37.5 percent) and partners
are ZhenHua Oil (37.5 percent), Midland Oil (25 percent), and Midland
Oil (25 percent). Halfaya is operated by PetroOil (37.5 percent) and
partners are stateowned South Oil (25 percent), Petronas Carigali
(18.75 percent) and Total (18.75 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  16.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.7  deg. C.

holds 15 percent and State owned Iraqi Oil Exploration Company holds
the remaining 25 percent. Zubair is operated by Eni (32.81 percent).

percent).

Name: BBLT  (ITS) Apr 30 '14
Comments:
The Benguela, Belize, Lobito and Tomboco (BBLT) fields are located
offshore Angola in Block 14. Phase 1, which includes the Belize fields,
started up in January 2006. Phase 2, which includes the Lobito,
Tomboco, and Benguela fields, started up in June 2006, January 2007 and
June 2007, respectively. BBLT is a light (34 degrees API), low sulfur
(0.3 wt percent) crude oil that is expected to produce VRES with a high
N concentration (11,400 ppm). Initial recoverable reserves were 474
million boe and remaining reserves are 198 million boe (2014). BBLT is
developed via a Compliant Piled Tower (CPT), which has a 220,000 b/d
production capacity. Production averages 74,000 b/d in 2014. Benguela
is split into two separate streams. Benguela Light is blended into the
BBLT grade which is transported to the Kokongo field then to the
Malongo terminal, in Cabinda Area A, and sold as part of the Nemba
Blend. Benguela heavy is sent to the Kuito FPSO where it is blended
into the Kuito grade. Chevron operates the BBLT and holds 31 percent
interest. Other partners are Angola Block 14 B.V. (20 percent), Eni (20
percent), Sonagol PandP (20 percent), and Galp Energia (9 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  19.8 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.4  deg. C.

Name: Bekapai (Total) '11
Comments:
The Bekapai oil field is in the Offshore Mahakam PSC located in the
Kutei Basin, offshore Kalimantan, Indonesia. The crude is light gravity
(42.8 degrees API) and low in sulfur (0.06 wt percent). IT is expected
to produce a vacuum residuum with a high MCRT concentration (56.5 wt
percent). Bekapai, the first field in the Offshore Mahakam PSC to come
onstream, started production in 1974 with an initial production rate of
2,000 b/d. The field reached a peak production of over 30,000 b/d once
its three platforms, Platforms A, B, and C, were installed in the
1970's. Bekapai production is in decline and output has been maintained
at 2,000 b/d (2012). Initial recoverable reserves were at 196 million
boe and 422 bcf gas. Remaining reserves are at 2 million boe and 35 bcf
gas (2013). Production from the field is sent to the Senipah terminal
through a 15,000 b/d, 12-inch diameter, 40 km long pipeline then
exported via tanker. Total is the operator and equal ownership is
shared with INPEX Corporation.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  26.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.6  deg. C.

Name: Belayim Land (ENI) '11
Comments:
The Belayim Land field is located along the eastern shore of the Gulf
of Suez onshore Egypt in the Sinai Peninsula. The field was discovered
in 1955 and started production in 1956. Initial recoverable reserves
were 834 million boe, of which 221 million boe remain (2011). Belayim
Land is a medium gravity (21.1 degrees API), mid level sulfur (3.1 wt
percent) crude oil that is blended with Belayim Marine and other nearby
fields at the Petreco Oil Center to produce the Belayim Blend. Total
Belayim Blend output in 2011 averaged 130,000 b/d. Eni has 100 percent
equity in the Belayim Land Field and operates the field through
Petrobel, a 50:50 joint venture with Egyptian Petroleum Corp.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   9.9 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.9  deg. C.

Name: Belayim Marine (ENI) '09
Comments:
The Belayim Marine field is located along the eastern shore of the Gulf
of Suez, offshore Egypt in the Sinai Peninsula. The field was
discovered in 1961 and started production in 1962. Initial recoverable
reserves were 1.884 billion boe. Remaining reserves are estimated at
400 million boe (2011). With an API of 28.8 degrees and sulfur content
of 2.45 wt percent, the Belayim Marine grade is a lighter and sweeter
stream than the nearby Belayim Land stream. Belayim Marine and Belayim
Land make up 80 percent of the Belayim Blend grade. Output from nearby
fields, Abu Rudeis, Ferian, Sinai, Dal and Ras Garra, make up the
remaining 20 percent. The Belayim Blend is blended at the Petreco Oil
Center then transported to the Feiran marine terminal for storage and
export. Belayim Blend output in 2011 averaged 130,000 b/d. Eni has 100
percent equity in the Belayim Land Field and operates the field through
Petrobel, a 50:50 joint venture with Egyptian Petroleum Corp.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  16.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.1  deg. C.

Name: Benguela Field (ITS) Apr 30 '14
Comments:
The Benguela field is in Block 14 of the Lower Congo Basin located
offshore Angola. It is a component of the BBLT grade (Benguela, Belize,
Lobito and Tomboco). Benguela Intermediate is a medium gravity (23.1
degrees ), low sulfur (0.73 wt percent), and high As concentration
(80.7 ppm) crude oil. The field started up in June 2007 and is
producing 12,000 b/d of light Benguela and 12,000 b/d of heavy
Benguela. Initial reserves were 139 million b/d of which, 67 million
boe remains (2013). The lighter stream is blended into the BBLT grade
and sent to the Kokongo field to the Malongo terminal, in Cabinda Area
A, and sold as part of the Nemba Blend. The heavier stream is blended
into the Kuito stream. Chevron operates the field and holds 31 percent
interest. Angola Block 14 B.V., Eni and Sonangol PandP each hold 20
percent interest and Galp Energia holds 9 percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   9.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.0  deg. C.

Benguela, Belize, Lobito and Tomboco (BBLT) oil fields and is located
in 390 m (1,280 feet) of water 70 km (45 miles) offshore Cabinda,
Angola. Cabinda Gulf Oil Company (CABGOC), a wholly owned subsidiary of
Chevron Corporation, is the block operator on behalf of the partner
group consisting of CABGOC. Six main oil pools make up the BBLT complex
with oil in place approaching 1.5 billion barrels (Figure 3). The
reservoirs are composed of high quality turbidite sands deposited in a
middle bathyal slope valley/incised canyon environment with 24deg
-38deg  API gravity oil.  this sample is represetnative of the medium
production that goes into the BBLT PL.

Name: Berantai (ITS) Jun25 '15
Comments:
Berantai is an offshore gas condensate field in the Malay basin located
in the Peninsular Malaysia, south of the Tapis oil field. The field was
discovered in 1978 and production started in Oct 2012. The current
production rate is 4,000 b/d oil (2016). Initial reserves are 19
million barrels of oil, 1 million barrels of condensate and 214 bcf
gas, of which 11 million barrels of oil and 88 bcf gas remains (2016).
Production is tied back to the Berantai FPSO then transported via
shuttle tankers for export. A 12-inch, 30 km pipeline is used to
transport produced gas to the Angsi Central Processing Platform (CPP).
From there, it is sent to the onshore terminal at Kerteh through a
32-inch, 166 km pipeline. Berantai condensate has an API of 53.1
degrees and a low sulfur concentration (0.02 wt percent). Petronas
operates the field and ownership is split between Petrofac Energy
Developments (50 percent) and SapuraKencana Petroleum (50 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  40.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   130.8  deg. C.

production rate is 9,000 b/d oil, 1,000 b/d condensate and 120 mm cf/d
sales gas (2013). Initial reserves were 20 million barrels of oil, 1
million barrels of condensate and 212 bcf gas, of which 19 million
barrels of oil, 1 million barrels condensate and 205 bcf gas remain.
Produced oil is tied back to the Berantai FPSO then transported via
shuttle tankers for export. A 12-inch, 30 km pipeline is used to
transport produced gas to the Angsi Central Processing Platform (CPP).
From there, it is sent to the onshore terminal at Kerteh through a
32-inch, 166 km pipeline. Berantai condensate (BERCND697) has an API of
69.7 degrees . It has a low sulfur content (0.003 wt percent) and a low
acid number (0.05 mg KOH/g). Berantai condensate has an API of 69.7
degrees . It has a low sulfur content (0.003 wt percent) and a low acid

Name: Blake Fld  (CVX) '10
Comments:
2010 Sample and CVX assay. The Blake oil field (Blake 'Channel') is a
North Sea oil field about 64 miles from Aberdeen (in the Outer Moray
Firth). The field began oil production in 2001. The field is operated
by Talisman Energy (UK) Ltd, a wholly owned subsidiary of Canadian
company Talisman Energy Inc, and owned by Talisman (51.99 percent),
Intrepid Energy North Sea Ltd. (13 percent), Kerr-McGee Resources (UK)
Limited (14.49 percent), Lasmo (ULX) Ltd. (16.33 percent) and Nippon
Oil Expro UK Ltd. (4.19 percent). The field, located in blocks 13/24
and 13/29b. The hydrocarbons produced from the Blake field are
transported via flow lines to a subsea production manifold for onward
transportation to the Bleo Holm FPSO (9.5km away) via 10in and 12in
production lines. On the FPSO, the Blake fluids are processed with
those from the Ross field. Additionally, Blake contains Blank Flank
production. The Blake Flank development is a smaller developed oil
field directly adjacent to the original Blake Channel . The first
production from Blake Flank was brought online in September 2003 with
an estimated flow rate of 5,200 barrels a day. The field is operated by
BG Group with a 44 percent interest and the remainder being held by
Talisman Energy (53.6 percent) and Paladin Resources (2.4 percent). The
Blake Flank field is tied into the current Blake production pipeline
infrastructure thus extending the economic life of the original Blake
Channel. Quality of the blend is typical NSea crude of its gravity
which is heavier than avg. this is a very unusual crude and peculiar
for its region.

Name: Bonga (CVX) Dec '12
Comments:
The Bonga field lies in OML 118 in the deepwater Niger Delta, 60-70
miles off the southern coast of Nigeria. The field was discovered in
1996 and started production in November 2005. Bonga is light (30.7
degrees API) and low sulfur (0.24 wt percent) crude oil with a high
measured arsenic content (134 ppb). Bonga Northwest, Bonga North, and
Bonga Southwest, discovered in 2003, 2004, and 2005, respectively, are
expected to come onstream on 2014, 2016, and 2018, respectively, and
will be tied back to the Bonga FPSO which has a production capacity of
225,000 bbl of oil and 170 mmcfd gas and a storage capacity of 2
million boe. In 2012, output averaged 135,000 b/d. Bonga holds
recoverable reserves of 1.666 billion boe and 1.182 bcf gas, of which
1.287 billion boe and 922 bcf gas remains (2012). Bonga is operated by
Shell (55 percent). Partners include ExxonMobil (20 percent), Eni (12.5
percent), and Total (12.5 percent).

Name: Bongor Field (XOM) '11
Comments:
Bongor crude oil is produced in Block H in the onshore Bangor Basin of
western Chad. According to China National Petroleum Corp (CNPC), the
owner and operator, Block H, which includes the Baobab, Mimosa, Ronier
and Prosopis, holds 700 million barrels of oil in place, of which 126
million boe (Baobab with 12 million boe, Mimosa with 33 million boe,
and Ronier with 81 million boe) are recoverable. Production from Ronier
and Mimosa began in May 2011 with a total production rate of 3,000 b/d
(2,000 b/d from Ronier and 1,000 b/d from Mimosa). Peak production is
expected to reach 18,000 b/d by 2014. Output from the Bangor fields are
transported through a 311 km, 16-inch pipeline to the 50,000 b/d
Djarmaya refinery located 40 km north of the capital Ndjamena. Bongor
crude is a light gravity (32.5 degrees API), low sulfur (0.05 weight
percent), waxy crude oil with a high crude pour point (86 degrees F).

Name: Bonny Light (CVX) Jan '13
Comments:
Bonny Light, also known as Nigerian Bonny Light, is a West African
benchmark crude. It is a light gravity, sweet crude (35.6 API and 0.15
wt percent Sulfur) with high As (140 ppb), Se (144 ppb), and Ti (128
ppb) levels measured in the whole crude and high Nitrogen in the VGO
and VRES cuts. Bonny Light is produced from several different fields
(Adibawa, Cawthorn Channel, Ekulama, Etelebou, Imo River, Jiseke, Kolo
Creek, Nembe) in the Niger Delta basin and exported via the Shell
operated Bonny Light export terminal. Shell has been operating the
terminal in 1961. Sabotage and thefts due to political unrest and poor
security conditions in the Niger Delta has led production to sharply
decline from a peak of 475,000 b/d in 2005 to an estimated 185,000 b/d
in November 2013. Approximately 85 percent of Bonny Light is owned by a
joint venture operated by Shell (30 percent) and partners Nigerian
National Petroleum Corp. (55 percent), Total (10 percent) and Eni (5
percent). The remaining 15 percent is from a joint venture operated by
Chevron (40 percent) with partner Nigerian National Petroleum Corp. (60
percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  17.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.2  deg. C.

Name: Boscan (CVX) Aug 27 '13
Comments:
Boscan is a large, heavy crude oil field located on the western side of
Lake Maracaibo in the Zulia state of Venezuela. The field holds 1.9
billion barrels of recoverable reserves, of which about 420 million
remain (2013). Boscan was discovered in 1946 and started production in
1948. Production currently averages 112,000 b/d (2013). Output from the
field is sent to the PDVSA-operated Bajo Grande Terminal 45 miles from
Lake Maracaibo via pipeline. Although the crude is very heavy it does
not require heating in the pipeline. Boscan is a viscous (109,000 cSt
at 20 degrees C) extra heavy crude (10.5 degrees API), with a high
sulfur content (5.5 wt percent) and high measured As content (312 ppb).
It is expected to have high VRES (50.3 wt percent) and ARES (82 wt
percent) yields and produce a VRES with a high nitrogen concentration
(10,400 ppm). Boscan is operated by PetroBoscan, a consortium
consisting of PDVSA (60 percent), Chevron (39.2 percent), and Inepetrol
(0.8 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers   2.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.4  deg. C.

Name: Bouri (LPI) '09
Comments:
Bouri is an offshore oil field located in Block NC-41, about 75 miles
off the coast of Libya. The field, discovered in 1976 and came on
stream in 1988, had initial recoverable reserves of 921 million, of
which 435 million remain. Production peaked at 83,900 b/d in 1991. Due
to the Libyan war, all production was shut-in in February 2011.
Production restarted in November 2011 with an initial production rate
of 10,000 b/d, far below its prewar levels of 40,000-45,000 b/d. Bouri
output is transported from the DP4 platform to the Sloug, a permanently
moored tanker that can store up to 1.5 million boe, through a 2.3 km,
16 inch pipeline. The field is operated and owned by Mellitah Oil and
Gas, a 50-50 joint venture between Eni and Libya's National Oil
Company. Bouri crude oil is a medium gravity, high sulfur crude oil
(26.0 deg API, 1.66 wt. percent sulfur).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  11.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   144.4  deg. C.

Name: Brent (XOM) '14
Comments:
Brent is light (37.6 degrees API), low sulfur (0.4 wt percent)
benchmark crude produced from fields located in the East Shetland
Basin, on the UK Continental Shelf. Most of the field lies in block
211/29 and a small extension is in block 3/4a. Production started in
1976 and has produced about 1.856 billion barrels of oil. Due to
falling production, Shell, the operator, has begun dismantling the
Brent Delta platform which was mothballed in 2011. Brent Alpha and
Brent Bravo were closed in Oct 2014. Of the four platforms, Brent
Charlie is the only one still producing and is expected to continue
production for the next few years. Brent is a declining oil field that
is producing less than 1,000 b/d. Ninian crude is blended into Brent to
stabilize quality fluctuations and boost production volume. Output is
transported through the 36-inch diameter Brent Pipeline System (BPS) to
the Sullom Voe Terminal (SVT) in the Shetland Islands. Brent owners are
Shell (50 percent) and ExxonMobil (50 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  23.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.2  deg. C.

  VOLS OF BOTH NINIAN & BRENT ARGUED FOR COMMINGLING.

  THISTLE, AND OSPREY GOING INTO DUNLIN, MURCHISON, EIDER,

Comments:
This assay is on the web. Brent blend is a light, medium sulfur, low
acidity crude oil with a low crude oil pour point.  The H2S content
measured at 160 C was <5 ppm wt. The selenium content measured on crude
was 40 ppb wt. The sulfur recovery from the d istillation was 99% of
crude value, ie 0.438%  kerosene (149-232) density, sulphur and freeze
are suitiable for jet A1.  Gasoil / diesel (232-342) density and cetane
index indicate suitability for  gas oil and diesel production although
desulphurisation may be necessary vacuum gasoil (369-550) medium
density with low sulphur and low basic nitrogen indicating suitability
as FCC feed.  Dewaxed oil data indicates good lube potential.
Atmospheric residue (>369) medium density with low sulphur. High
vanadium  content indicates that product should be processed in a
vacuum distillation stage to separate wax distillate as FCC feed. High
sodium content may cause an increase in coke formation in heaters and
reactors. Vacuum residue (>509,>550, >585) medium densit y with medium
sulphur. Typical fuel oil blend stock.

Name: Brent Exp Bld (CVX) '08
Comments:
11/2008 sample,  CVX assay.  Brent Blend is a medium density, medium
sulphur,low acidity crude oil with a low crude oil pour point. BRENT IS
A STRATEGICALLY IMPORTANT CRUDE BECAUSE IT SERVES AS THE MARKER FOR N.
SEA OILS AND BRENT IS A KEY INTERNATIONAL SPOT MARKET BENCHMARK GRADE
USED AS AN INTERNATIONAL MARKER FOR SPOT AND FUTURE SALES. IT IS THE
SECOND LARGEST UK CRUDE OIL STREAM AFTER FORTIES. THE CRUDE OIL IS
PRIMARILY REFINED IN NORTHWEST EUROPE, BUT DEPENDING ON ARBITRAGE
OPPORTUNITIES, SIGNIFICANT VOLUMES OFTEN MOVE TO THE US GULF AND EAST
COAST, AS WELL AS TO THE MEDITERRANEAN. BRENT BLEND IS TYPICAL HIGH
QUALITY, LIGHT, LOW-SULFUR NORTH SEA CRUDE OIL (I.E., apprx.38 API, 0.2
WT% S). BECAUSE THE SEGREGATION COMMINGLES CRUDE AND NGL FROM BOTH THE
NINIAN SYSTEM AND THE BRENT SYSTEM TO BECOME THE BRENT BLEND-EACH OF
WHICH IS A COMPOSITE OF MANY FIELDS NVOLVING MANY PRODUCERS THAT IS
THEN LOADED FROM THE SULLOM VOE TERMINAL IN THE SHETLAND ISLANDS -THERE
IS GREAT INTEREST AND INVOLVEMENT IN IT. PRODUCTION IS DIVIDED AMONG
SEVERAL INTERNATIONAL OIL COMPANIES. EXXONMOBIL AND ROYAL DUTCH/SHELL
LEAD THE PACK OF BRENT SYSTEM PRODUCERS, FOLLOWED BY BP, ORYX, AMERADA
HESS, EXXONMOBIL, AND OTHERS. TOTAL IS THE NINIAN SYSTEM'S LEAD
PRODUCER, FOLLOWED BY CHEVRONTEXACO, ORYX, ROYAL DUTCH/SHELL, ENI/AGIP,
AND OTHERS. BRENT BLEND IS A COMPILATION OF CRUDE OIL, AND NATURAL GAS
LIQUIDS. THE MAIN FIELDS OF THE BRENT SYSTEM ARE BRENT, CORMORANT,
HUTTON, THISTLE, MURCHISON (22% NORWEGIAN), AND DUNLIN. THE MAIN FIELDS
OF THE NINIAN SYSTEM ARE NINIAN, ALWYN NORTH, AND MAGNUS.  PASCAGOULA
RAN 1 CARGO OF BRENT IN 2001. BRENT IS THE LARGEST FIELD IN THE NORTH
SEA; IT IS ALSO THE WORLD'S SECOND LARGEST OFFSHORE FIELD. ACID, WHOLE
CRUDE <0.05 SILVER below detection limit ARSENIC below detection limit
BORON below detection limit BERYLLIUM below detection limit CALCIUM

Name: Brunei Light (ITS) '08
Comments:
Brunei Light, a light gravity (44.1 deg API), low sulfur (0.04 wt

and Gannet fields, all located in the Baram Delta basin offshore
Brunei. Ampa SW, Brunei's oldest offshore field, started up in 1964.
Fairley and Fairley Baram started up in 1970 and Gannet came onstream
in 1988. Output from Fairley and Fairley Baram is blended with SW Ampa
crude then delivered to Seria for export or for blending into Champion
crude. Initial recoverable reserves were 1.574 billion boe. By the end
of 2010, about 141 million boe remain. Production in 2010 averaged
32,000 b/d. Brunei Shell Petroleum, a 50:50 joint venture between Shell
and the Brunei government, owns and operates the field.

Name: BRWA-14 Berantai Field (ITS) Mar
Comments:
BRWA-14 is a well in the Barantai Field offshore Malaysia. Berantai is
an offshore gas condensate field in the Malay basin located in the
Peninsular Malaysia, south of the Tapis oil field. The field was
discovered in 1978 and started production in Oct 2012. The current
production rate is 9,000 b/d oil, 1,000 b/d condensate and 120 mm cf/d
sales gas (2013). Initial reserves were 20 million barrels of oil, 1
million barrels of condensate and 212 bcf gas, of which 19 million
barrels of oil, 1 million barrels condensate and 205 bcf gas remain.
Produced oil is tied back to the Berantai FPSO then transported via
shuttle tankers for export. A 12-inch, 30 km pipeline is used to
transport produced gas to the Angsi Central Processing Platform (CPP).
From there, it is sent to the onshore terminal at Kerteh through a
32-inch, 166 km pipeline. Petronas operates the field and ownership is
split between Petrofac Energy Developments (50 percent) and
SapuraKencana Petroleum (50 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  23.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.7  deg. C.
