Name: BU ATTIFEL (ENI) '06
Comments:
Bu Attifel, also known as Abutiffel or Abu Atiffel, is light sweet
crude with an API of 43 degrees and 0.02 weight percent sulfur. It is
produced in Libya's eastern central desert in the Sirte Basin, which
holds 90 percent of Libya's 41.5 billion bbls of reserves. Bu Attifel,
the country's second largest field, began production in 1972. In 2009,
the production rate was 88,000 b/d, down 15,000 b/d from the year
before. Eni is the operator and has a 50 percent interest, while
Libya's National Oil Corp. (NOC) holds the remaining 50 percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  12.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   145.3  deg. C.

Name: Bu Attifel Exp Bld (AGIP)'08
Reference: Paper assay sent by Singapore Co
Comments:
Bu Attifel: Operated by Agip, Bu Attifel was discovered in 1968 at a
depth of 14,300 feet in the eastern side of the Sirte basin. One of the
deepest fields in the country, Bu Attifel produces oil of 41 deg. API
gravity. It has a total of 39 wells, of which 30 are said to be
producing. Bu Attifel has been producing since the early 1970s and
several discoveries since then have added to its reserve base. Of the
five discoveries made in 1990-1994, two were oil-rich structures near
Bu ttifel discovered by Agip. This is one of the waxiest crudes.  The
crude is a light yellow brown and resid is pale. Heteroatoms are very
low an 650*F+ can be fed directly to FCC. Being rich in paraffins and
in n-paraffins specifically, crude is excellent for manufacture of
petrochemicals.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  10.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.1  deg. C.

Name: Bu Attifel Exp Bld (CVX) Aug '12
Comments:
Bu Attifel, also known as Abutiffel or Abu Atiffel, is a waxy, light,
sweet crude (API of 43 degrees and 0.03 wt percent sulfur) with a high
crude pour point (97.8 degrees F) and high mercury content (90 ppb). It
is produced in Libya's eastern central desert in the Sirte Basin, which
holds 90 percent of Libya's 41.5 billion barrels of reserves. Bu
Attifel, the country's second largest field, began production in 1972.
In 2012, production averaged 53,000 b/d. Prior to being shut-in due to
the Libyan uprising, Bu Attifel was producing 88,000 b/d. Initial
recoverable reserves were 2.126 billion barrels of oil and 101 million
barrels of condensate. In 2012, 326 million barrels oil and 21 million
barrels of condensate remain. Production of the field is transported
through a 132 km, 30 inch pipeline to the Zueitina Intisar A (103A)
facilities then sent via a 220 km, 40-inch pipeline to the Zueitina oil
terminal. Bu Attifiel is owned and operated by Mellitah Oil and Gas, a
50-50 joint venture that includes Eni and Libya's National Oil Corp.
(NOC).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  11.8 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.2  deg. C.

the field.

Name: Burun/Keimir Fld (SGS) '07
Comments:
sample of Burun Crude oil  from the Kiemir block received on the
08/11/2007 by  SGS distillation apparatus at atmospheric pressure to
180C then at 10mm Hg pressure to an overhead temperature of 365C AET.
The 365+ C residue was then distilled in the Kontes Martin Hivac
Distillation unit at pressures between .01 and .25 mmHg. data are
poor-- sparse, missing dha. the Keimir block is located on the
south-western coast of the Caspian near the border with Iran in western
Turkmenistan. the fields are rich in gas as well. TurkmenNeft is
operator for the  JV's 120,000 b/d production in of light and sweet oil
under the export crude grade Okarem. The Burun Field is located within
the West Turkmenistan Basin, on the continental margin of the
southeastern Caspian Basin, onshore Turkmenistan. Late Tertiary
sediments of western Turkmenistan contain significant reserves of oil
and gas in fluvial and deltaic reservoirs. Oil has been produced from
the area commercially for over 100 years, initially from shallow
hand-dug wells targeting oil seeps. The Burun Field was discovered in
1967 and currently produces 1550 m3 of oil per day (9750 bopd) of 33
API sweet crude and 1 MMm3 of gas per day (35 MMscf/d) from 88 wells
(as of Jan. 2003). The field is approximately 10 km by 3 km and
comprises stacked reservoirs of Neogene age, with an overall anticlinal
structure developed as a result of dextral shear. Over 200 wells have
been drilled on the structure, with 50 currently on production.
Reservoirs are stacked channel to delta front sandstones at a depth of
1000 m to 4400 m. The Pliocene to Quaternary Red Series, Akchagylian
and Apsheronian suites form the main reservoirs, deposited in a variety
of fluvio-deltaic to shallow marine environments. ACID, WHOLE CRUDE
value calculated VIS104 value calculated VIS122 value calculated VIS212
value calculated WAX CVX value calculated IRON value calculated SOLVENT
POWER value calculated SOLVENT REQUIREMENT value calculated REID VAPOUR

Name: Cabinda (CVX) '16
Comments:
Cabinda crude oil is a light gravity (32.3 degrees API), low sulfur
(0.152 wt percent) crude oil with a high measured As concentration
(73.2 wt ppm). It is produced in Cabinda Area A Block 0, located
offshore Angola. Cabinda crude, which accounts for almost 60 percent of
Angola's oil production, came onstream in 1968. Cabinda Area A Block 0
is comprised of the Takula, Malongo, Mafumeria, and Kambala complex
which hold 2.154 billion boe, 1.373 billion boe, 379 million boe and 85
million boe, respectively, of initial recoverable reserves. Remaining
reserves are 180 million boe, 91 million boe, 287 million boe, and 22
million boe, respectively (2017). Output from each complex is sent via
pipeline to the Malongo Terminal where it is blended and marketed as
the Cabinda Blend. In 2013, production averaged 176,370 b/d. The
Cabinda Area A concession is operated by Chevron (39.20 percent).
Sonagol EP (41 percent), Total (10 percent), and Eni (9.8 percent) are
joint venture partners.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  15.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.7  deg. C.

Name: Cabinda Exp Bld (CVX) '11
Comments:
Cabinda crude oil is a light gravity, low sulfur crude (32.2 degrees
API and 0.15 wt percent sulfur) that is produced in Cabinda Area A
Block 0 located offshore Angola. Cabinda crude, which accounts for
almost 60 percent of Angola's oil production, came onstream in 1968.
The field has initial recoverable reserves of 4.236 billion barrels of
oil and 83 million barrels equivalent of LPG, of which 1.131 billion
barrels of oil and 4 million barrels equivalent of LPG remains. Cabinda
consists of several complexes including the Malongo complex which
includes the Malongo North, West, and South fields as well as the
Limba, Kali, Kungulo and Mafumiera Norte development, the declining
Kambala/Livuite complex, and the Takula complex which also includes the
Takula, Wamba, Banzala, N'Sano, Numbi South East and Numbi North East
satellite fields. Crude from Area A is transported to Malongo terminal
where it is commingled with output from the Takula, Lucula and Lago
streams and the resulting blend is marketed as Cabinda Blend. In 2010,
production averaged 230,000 b/d. The Cabinda Area A concession is
operated by Chevron (39.20 percent). Sonagol EP (41 percent), Total (10
percent), and Eni (9.8 percent) are joint venture partners.

Name: Calypso Exp Bld (CVX) Feb '12
Comments:
Calypso crude oil, also known as Angostura, is produced from an
offshore oil and gas field located 40 km off Trinidad and Tobago's
coast. The crude is light gravity (31.9 degrees API), low in sulfur
(0.6 wt percent) and is expected to produce vacuum residuum with high
nickel and vanadium content (708 ppm). Calypso was developed in two
phases with Phase 1 starting oil production in 2005 and Phase 2
starting gas production in 2011. The fields have recoverable reserves
of 70 million boe and 974 bcf gas with remaining reserves of 17 million
boe and 974 bcf gas (2011). In 2011, production averaged 10,100 b/d and
111 mmbcf gas/d. BHP Hilton operates the field and holds 45 percent
interest. Other partners are Total (30 percent), Sinopec (12.5 percent)
and CNOOC ltd (12.5 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  12.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.4  deg. C.

Name: Calypso Exp/Angostura(Core) '04
Comments:
First oil from the greater Angostura oil and gas field was achieved in
December 2004 with first production in January 2005, representing the
first oil production from the northeast coast of Trinidad. Initial oil
production is expected to be around 60,000  barrels of oil per day. The
bulk of the produced gas is being re-injected into the Angostura
reservoirs to support oil production from the field.  The crude is 1.5
mg KOH/g acid, 165 ppm mercaptans, 6.9% wax, 0.61% S, 1170 ppm total N,
360 ppm basic N, 78 ppm V, 15 ppm Ni, 4 ppm Fe, 11.8 k, 2.6% MCR, 0.98%
asphaltenes, 1.o psi RVP, 490 lb salt/k bbl.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   5.8 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.3  deg. C.

Comments:

ppm V, 5 ppm Fe,   99 ppb Se, 37 ppb Hg, 195 ppb As, 190 ppb Cu, 55 ppb
Pb,    1.48 mg KOH/g acid, 10.3 cst viscosity @104F, 7.8   cst
viscosity @122F, 11 wt% n-paraffins/wax,   1.5 p si RVP. Compatability
parameters of 63.3 vol% ct,   0.30 PO, 0.11 RA.  Block 2(c) is located
approximately 24 miles (38.5 km) east of the island of Trinidad. Crude
is from a large faulted structure known as the Greater Angostura
Structure.  Fields includ e: Angostura-1, drilled in 1999, was the
discovery well for the field, intersecting some 950 feet (gross) of gas
pay within early oligocene sands. The hydrocarbon potential of the
structure was confirmed by drilling Aripo-1, Kairi-1, Canteen-1,
Kairi-2, Ang ostura-2, and Canteen-2. Each of these
exploration/appraisal wells intersected oil and gas in oligocene sands.
The Kairi and canteen fault blocks contain most of the oil thus far.
CVX SCA assay based on poor its data.

Name: Cano Limon (CVX) Oct '12
Comments:
Cano Limon, one of Columbia's largest oil fields, is in the Cravo Norte
license in the eastern Llanos Basin located in the eastern province of
Arauca near the Colombian-Venzuelan border. The field was discovered in
1983 and came on stream in 1985. Cano Limon includes the Cravo Norte,
Cosecha, and Rondon areas. The produced crude oil is medium gravity
(29.6 degrees API) and low sulfur (0.51 wt percent). Total initial
recoverable reserves were 1.609 billion boe. Most of the reserves lie
in the Cravo Norte Block (1.524 billion boe). Smaller volumes reside in
the Cosecha and Rondon fields (33 million and 47 million boe,
respectively). In 2013, remaining reserves were 107 million, with 77
million boe in the Cravo Norte Block, 7 million in the Cosecha Area and
23 million boe in the Rondon Area. Production has been steadily
declining since reaching 100,000 b/d in 2007. Production in 2012
averages 60,000 b/d (43,000 b/d from the Cravo Norte Block and 7,000
b/d from Cosecha and 10,000 b/d from Rondon). Ouput from Cano Limon is
exported to Covenas via a 490 mile Ecopetrol operated pipeline.
Occidental operates the fields and holds a 43.75 percent interest.
Other partners are Ecopetrol (50 percent) and Repsol-YPF SA (6.25
percent). Neat Cano Limon has not been available since October 2012
because Ecopetrol, the operator, has been blending the crude with
Vasconia.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   9.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.4  deg. C.

Name: Cascade (CVX) Feb '13
Comments:
Cascade crude consist of production from the Cascade field, located in
the Walker Ridge Blocks 205, 206, 249, 250 and 425 in the Gulf of
Mexico, about 300km (180 miles) south of the Louisiana coast and the
nearby Chinook field, located in WR 206. Phase 1 of the Cascade
development came on stream with Cascade coming onstream on February 25,
2012 and Chinook starting up in September 2012. Output from the
Cascade/Chinook is tied back to the BW Pioneer FPSO, the first oil and
gas producing FPSO in the US portion of the Gulf of Mexico. The Cascade
field has recoverable reserves of 200 million boe and 40 bcf gases and
Chinook holds 195 million boe and 29 bcf sales gases. Production from
the Cascade and Chinook fields are expected to peak at 34,780 b/d and
36,250 b/d, respectively, in 2025. Cascade is a medium gravity crude
oil (25 degrees API) with a sulfur content of 2.97 wt percent.
Petrobras operates both field and holds 100 percent of Cascade and
66.67 percent of Chinook. Total holds 33.33 percent of Chinook.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  11.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.9  deg. C.

Name: Cascade (INSP) May 14 '12
Comments:
The Cascade field is located in the Walker Ridge Blocks 205, 206, 249,
250 and 425 in the Gulf of Mexico, about 300km (180 miles) south of the
Louisiana coast and 15 miles away from the nearby Chinook field.
Cascade came on stream in February 25, 2012 with an initial production
rate of 8,000 b/d. The field was discovered in 2002 and was developed
with the nearby Chinook field which is expected to start production
this year. Output from the Cascade field, as well as Chinook, will be
tied back to the BW Pioneer FPSO, the first oil and gas producing FPSO
in the US portion of the Gulf of Mexico. The Cascade field has
recoverable reserves of 211 million boe and 53 bcf gas. Peak production
of 40,000 b/d is expected to be reached in 2020. Cascade is a medium
gravity crude oil (23-24 degrees API) with a sulfur content of 3 wt
percent and high measured crude As (less than 50 ppb) content. It is
also expected to produce a vacuum residuum with high microcarbon
content (greater than 30 wt percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  11.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   144.0  deg. C.

Name: Cascade Fld  Well 1 DST (W.Port)
Comments:
Cascade and Chinook are located in the Walker Ridge block, around 300km
(180 miles) south of the Louisiana coast. Petrobras is the operator of
both the Cascade and Chinook units, owning 50% and 66.67% of the fields
respectively. The remaining 50% of Cascade is owned by Devon Energy
Corporation, while Total E&P owns the remaining 33.33% of Chinook. The
fields will be developed two subsea wells in Cascade and one subsea
well in Chinook, approximately 30km south of Cascade. Each well will be
drilled to an approximate depth of 27,000ft, and based on reservoir
performance. Petrobras may expand production to additional subsea wells
on each field. Due to be put onstream mid 2010. The lab reported
viscosity @ 60F of 283 ct was not used in workup because it was too
close to pour pt of 30F and could contain solids Organic Chloride below
detection limit Hydrogen Sulphide below detection limit

Comments:
2010 discharge sample and a CVX TFA assay. The Castilla Blend is
produced in the Magdalena Valley of Colombia by state owned Ecopetrol,

comprised of Castilla crude and other heavy crudes produced in the
plains region and are blended to a target API gravity of 18.8 deg and 2
weight percent Sulfur. To facilitate the transport of crude oil through
the pipeline system to Cove as, the viscosity is reduced by adding
virgin naphtha. The Castilla field was first developed in 1975. In
2010, it was reported that the production of the Castilla field
exceeded 100,000 b/d.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  11.9 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.7  deg. C.

Name: Castilla Exp Bld (CVX)'10
Comments:
2010 sample of discharge.  CVX assay update.  Castilla Blend is a heavy
crude currently advertised by Ecopetrol as being 18.8  and 2.0% S.  it
results from mixing 13*Castilla crude with other heavy crude fields in
the plains region, to which virgin naphtha is added as diluent. Diluent
is in short supply and they may use condensate as well, to transport
this stuff using the oil pipeline system to Coveñas.  You can expect
variation.  I would contract both gravity and sulfur.  Mcr is a good
indicator of what is what.  The resid tends to produce a brittle
asphalt.  Castilla is an immature crude and so mcr and asphaltenes will
be high.  you can also expect suspended water in the oil phase. Many of
the producer now have tools that tell them how to blend to hit the
targets in contracts.  So this may be an opportunity but only if
properly framed to accommodate what is the reality.Ecopetrol and
Pacific Rubiales have been saying is they blend to pipeline viscosity.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   9.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.7  deg. C.

Name: Champion (SGS) '12
Comments:
The Champion oil fields are located about 40 km offshore Brunei in the
Baram Delta Basin. The field, which includes the main Champion oil
field, the Champion West Field, and the Peragam field, was discovered
in 1970 and began producing in 1972. The Peragam field, located under
the Champion fields, was abandoned due to bad hole conditions.
Champion, Champion West, and the Peragam fields have initial
recoverable reserves of 1.049 billion boe, 117 million boe, and 8
million boe, respectively. Total production in 2012 was 48,000 b/d.
Champion is a component of Seria. Output from Champion is sent to the
Seria terminal for export. The Champion field is owned and operated by
Brunei Shell Petroleum, a 50:50 joint venture between the Brunei
Government and Shell. Champion is a light gravity, low sulfur crude oil
(33.1 degrees API, 0.08 wt percent sulfur) with high arsenic content
(460 ppb).

Name: Cheecham (Statoil) '11
Comments:
Cheecham Heavy Blend, also known as Leismer, is produced from the
Leismer oil sands project, one of the four core development areas of
the Kai Kos Dehseh project (KKD) located in the Athabasca region of
Alberta, NE of Edmonton, Canada. Construction started in 2008 and first
oil was achieved on January 2011 with an initial production rate of
10,000 b/d. Production is expected to increase and reach peak
production rate of 40,000 b/d by 2019. The Leismer area, the first area
in the KKD project to be developed, utilizes Steam Assisted Gravity
Drainage (SAGD) process to extract bitumen which is then diluted prior
to transport from Alberta to Edmonton through Enbridge s 350,000 b/d
Waupisoo Pipeline where it is sold as Cheecham Heavy Blend. Future
plans includes building a 280 km, 225,000 b/d capacity pipeline that
will transport all production from the KKD. Leismer has initial
recoverable reserves of 500 million barrels of bitumen, of which 496
million barrels remain. Cheecham is medium gravity (21.5 deg API), high
sulfur (3.6 wt percent) diluted bitumen (dilbit) that has a high total
acid number (2 mg KOH/g). It is expected to produce a vacuum residuum
with a high MCRT (30.8 wt percent) and high nickel and vanadium (676
ppm). Statoil is the operator with 60 percent interest. PTT Exploration
and Production (PTTEP) of Thailand owns 40 percent interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  20.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.5  deg. C.

Comments:
Chim Sao, formerly known as Blackbird, is an oil and gas field that
also includes the Dua field. Both fields are located in Block 12W of

Name: Christina Lake Dilbit (MAX) '03
Comments:
Christina Lake dilbit (CRSTN199) has an API of 19.9 degrees API, a high
sulfur content of 2.61 wt percent and a high MCRT content of 30 wt
percent. It is produced from the Cenovus Energy operated Christina Lake
project located in the Athabasca region of Alberta about 120 km south
of Fort McMurray. The 9 degrees API bitumen is recovered via SAGD then
diluted with Synthetic Crude Oil (SCO) so that every barrel of dilbit
is comprised of 45 percent SCO and 55 percent bitumen. Christina Lake
started production in 2002 and is now producing 99,000 barrels of
bitumen per day. Initial recoverable reserves are estimated at 1.849
billion barrels of bitumen and about 1.794 billion barrels of bitumen
remain (2013). Christina Lake Dilbit is transported through the
Athabasca to Hardisty where it is sold to Canadian and US refineries.
Cenovus Energy and ConocoPhillips each have a 50 percent equity share.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   8.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   143.1  deg. C.

Name: Coco Exp Bld (ENI) '09
Comments:
Congo Export Blend, also known as Congo Composite Crude (COCO) or Zaire
Blend, is a light gravity, low sulfur crude with an API of 30.6 degrees
, 0.14 wt percent sulfur and high crude pour point of 80 degrees F. It
is a blend produced from the output of the East Mibale, Tshiende,
Liawenda, Kinkasi, Makelekese, Muanda and Kifuku fields. Crude oil from
all the fields, except the Tshiende field and the shut in East Mibale
field, are sent to the Kinkasi gathering station via pipeline or truck
then transported with Thiende output to the Mibale processing station
for water and salt separation. Once processed, the crude is piped via a
4-km, 16-in pipeline to the Parenco operated offshore Mibale platform
where the crude undergoes further desalination as well as co-mingling.
COCO is stored in the Kalamu FSO which has a 1.1 million boe storage
capacity. Kinkasi and East Mibale, the first streams to come on stream,
started up in 1980. COCO's initial recoverable reserves were 107
million boe, of which 24 million boe remain (2011). The field currently
produces about 9,600 b/d (2010). Parenco is the sole operator and owner
of the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  10.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.5  deg. C.

Name: Cold Lake (CVX) '13
Comments:
Cold Lake Blend is diluted bitumen (dilbit) that is mainly produced
from Imperial Oil Resources' in Situ Cold Lake project located in
Northeastern Alberta, Canada. The blend also includes bitumen from
other sources such as the Cenovus-ConocoPhillips Foster Creek project,
which is located north of the Cold Lake area and uses SAGD for bitumen
extraction, as well as bitumen from Canadian Natural Resources' (CNR)
CSS-based Primrose/Wolf Lake operations and Royal Dutch Shell's Orion
project. Imperial Oil Resources' in Situ Cold Lake project s bitumen
(11 degrees API and sulfur content of 5.5 wt percent) is extracted
primarily using the Cyclic Steam Stimulation (CSS) extraction technique
where bitumen is heated to flow using a series of steam injections into
the oil sands reservoir followed by a 'soak' period that allows the
steam to rise through the reservoir and heat the viscous oil. The
heated oil and water are then pumped to the surface and extracted. The
length of each steaming and extraction cycles can vary from three to 12
months. The extracted bitumen is then diluted with condensate so that
it can be transported through the Cold Lake pipeline to Edmonton and
Hardisty where it enters the Enbridge system to eastern Canada and the
US market. Imperial's Cold Lake bitumen production averaged 154,000 b/d
in 2012. The entire Cold Lake area had initial recoverable reserves of
1.98 billion barrels of bitumen. Remaining recoverable reserves are 964
million barrels of bitumen (2013). Production from Imperial Oil
Resources Cold Lake project began in 1986. Cold Lake Blend has an API
of 22.8 degrees and sulfur content of 3.6 wt percent. The crude also is
predicted to have high Ni  V content in the vacuum residuum (595 ppm).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  20.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.7  deg. C.

Name: Congo Export Blend COCO (SAY) Au
Comments:
Congo Export Blend, also known as Congo Composite Crude (COCO) or Zaire
Blend, is a light gravity, low sulfur crude with an API of 30.6?, 0.14
wt percent sulfur and high crude pour point of 80? F. It is a blend
produced from the output of the East Mibale, Tshiende, Liawenda,
Kinkasi, Makelekese, Muanda and Kifuku fields. Crude oil from all the
fields, except the Tshiende field and the shut in East Mibale field,
are sent to the Kinkasi gathering station via pipeline or truck then
transported with Thiende output to the Mibale processing station for
water and salt separation. Once processed, the crude is piped via a
4-km, 16-in pipeline to the Parenco operated offshore Mibale platform
where the crude undergoes further desalination as well as co-mingling.
COCO is stored in the Kalamu FSO which has a 1.1 million boe storage
capacity. Kinkasi and East Mibale, the first streams to come on stream,
started up in 1980. COCO's initial recoverable reserves were 107
million boe, of which 24 million boe remain (2011). The field currently
produces about 9,600 b/d (2010). Parenco is the sole operator and owner
of the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  10.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   138.2  deg. C.

Name: Connacher 14 Dilbit (SGS) '13
Comments:
The Great Divide project is an oil sands steam assisted gravity
drainage project operated and owned by Connacher Oil and Gas. The Great
Divide area is split into two development areas, Pod One and Algar,
formerly known as Pod Two. Algar is located about eight km east of Pod
One, 80 km south of Fort McMurray and 370 km north of Edmonton and
covers approximately 5,120 acres. The Algar development started in 2008
and production began in 2010. Initial reserves are estimated at 82
million recoverable barrels of bitumen and about 77 million remain
(2013). In 2011, production averaged 6,900 barrels of bitumen.
Connacher 14 Dilbit is a viscous (3560 cSt at 20 degrees C), heavy
(16.8 degrees API) and high sulfur (4.4 wt percent) diluted bitumen
with a high total acid number (2.6 mg KOH/g). The vacuum residuum is
expected to have high VRES Ni (830 ppm) and MCRT (37.7 wt percent)
concentrations.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  15.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.6  deg. C.

Name: Connacher POD 1 DilBit (CVX) '14
Comments:

Divide project operated and owned by Connacher Oil and Gas. The Great
Divide which also includes the Algar area, formerly known as Pod Two,
is a SAGD project located 80 km south of Fort McMurray and 370 km north
of Edmonton and covers approximately 5,120 acres. Dilbit is created
from the produced bitumen is diluted with condensate. Initial
recoverable reserves are estimated at 79 million recoverable barrels of
bitumen and about 67 million barrels of bitumen remain (2014). In 2013,
production averaged 6,300 barrels of bitumen. Connacher POD 1 dilbit is
a viscous (2260 cSt at 20 degrees C), heavy (15.3 degrees API) and high
sulfur (4.3 wt percent) diluted bitumen with a high total acid number
(2.6 mg KOH/g) and high As (100 ppb) concentration. It is also expected
to have a high ARES yield (70 vol percent) and a high VRES Ni (632
ppm) concentration.

Name: Cook Inlet/SwansonRvr/CIPL(CVX)'
Comments:
7/2009 sample, CVX assay of Swanson River.  The Cook Inlet Pipeline
provides crude oil transportation services to producers in and around
Alaska's prominent Cook Inlet. Crude is gathered from fields on the
west side of the Cook Inlet and carried through the pipeline to the
nearby Drift River Marine Terminal. The pipeline was designed with a
flow rate of 225,000 BOPD, traveling through 42 miles of 20 inch pipe.
The Drift River Marine Terminal, which has crude oil storage
capacity in excess of 1 million barrels, receives crude from the
pipeline into storage for subsequent delivery to tankers berthed at
the Christy Lee Platform. Most of the crude is delivered into the
local refinery market.  Chevron Pipe Line Company operates the
facilities.

Name: CPC Blend (CVX) '09
Comments:
2009 sample, CPC Blend is a light crude oil which was first introduced
to the market at the end of 2001 with the commissioning of a 1,580km
pipeline by the Caspian Pipeline Consortium (CPC). The CPC pipeline
links major oil fields in Western Kazakhstan to a Black Sea export
terminal opened in 2001 at Yuzhnaya Ozereevka, located 40km North-West
of Novorossiysk (Russia). At the end of 2004, CPC Blend consisted of
seven crude oil streams: Tengiz, Aktobe, Kumkol, Martyshi, Arman,
Karachaganak and Siberian Light. The most significant developments in
2004 were the introduction of Karachaganak in June, and the beginning
of Russian crude injection, principally Siberian Light, in November.
Despite new streams being injected to the pipeline, Tengiz remains the
single largest component of CPC Blend. CPC blend is a very light, low
sulfur (mistaken taken as sweet), somewhat waxy crude oil.  This crude
contains a lot of mercaptans and may have H2S although H2S is stripped
from the crude as part of the stabilization process. Aluminium below

Name: CPC Blend (CVX) Dec '11
Comments:
CPC Blend started up in 2001 when the Caspian Pipeline Consortium
pipeline, which runs from Kazakhstan's Tengiz field and other western
oil fields with the Yuzhnaya Ozereevka terminal near the Russian Black
Sea port of Novorossiysk, was completed. Tengiz accounts for about 45
percent of the blend making it the largest contributor. Other main
contributors are the Aktobe (41.6 degrees API gravity), Kumkol (41.2
degrees ), Martyshi (31.8 degrees ), Arman (28.8 degrees ),
Karachaganak Condensate (44.7 degrees ) and Russian Siberian Light
(35.1 degrees ) as well as several other Russian and Kazakh crudes. The
CPC pipeline capacity of 650,000 b/d has increased by 15 percent with
the addition of drag reducing agents in 2009. Throughput in 2010
averaged 750,000 b/d. CPC Blend is a light gravity (44-45), low sulfur
crude ( 0.6 wt percent) with high measured As (154 ppb). The crude is
also predicted to produce jet/kero that is high in mercaptans. The CPC
pipeline is owned and operated by the CPC consortium which consists of
Russian Federation (24 degrees ), Republic of Kazakhstan (19 percent),
Chevron Caspian Pipeline Consortium Company (15 percent), LUKARCO B.V.
(12.5 percent), Rosneft-Shell Caspian Ventures Limited (7.5 percent),
Mobil Caspian Pipeline Company (7.5 percent), Caspian Pipeline Company
(7 percent), ENI International (N.A.) N.V. S.ar.l. (2 percent), BG
Overseas Holdings Limited (2 percent), Kazakhstan Pipeline Ventures
L.L.C. (1.75 percent), and Oryx Caspian Pipeline L.L.C. (1.75 percent).
Tengiz partners Chevron (operator, 50 percent), Exxon Mobil (25
percent), Kazmunaigas (20 percent) and LukArco (5 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  31.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   144.3  deg. C.

Name: Cusiana Exp Bld (EcoPetrol) '03
Comments:
Cusiana was discovered in 1991. The field covers an area roughly 16
miles x 4 miles in the foothills of the Eastern Andes. Combined with a
neighboring field, reserves of the 36 API, 0.25 wt % sulfur crude are
estimated to be 2 billion bbl. Production began in October 1994,
operated by BPX Colombia. The recently completed early production phase
involved drilling about 14 production wells and connecting them to
Cusiana processing facilities. In addition, this phase entailed
constructing more than 80 miles of pipeline, as well as upgrading
existing pumping stations and constructing new ones. The so-called full
field development stage will be complete by the end of 1997. This phase
comprises further field development and expansion of the existing
pipeline from Cusiana to Coveas. Additional tankage is being built at
Coveas to allow the segregation of Cusiana from other lower-quality
crudes. The existing tanker loading unit (TLU) can handle cargoes of
about 800,000 bbl at a rate of 40,000 bbl/Flash Point below detection
limit

Name: Dai Hung (PVEP) '15
Comments:
Dai Hung, the Vietnamese translation for Big Bear, is an offshore oil
field located in Block 05-1 in Vietnam's Nam Con Basin. It is a waxy,
light gravity (35.9 degrees API), low sulfur (0.07 wt percent), and
high pour point (67 degrees F) crude oil. Dai Hung has initial reserves
of 69 million boe and 16 million barrels of remaining reserves (2016).
The field came on-stream in 1994 and in 2011, production averaged 5,500
b/d. Production averaged 9,000 b/d in 2015. Most of the production is
from the Dai Hung Phase II project which utilizes the WHP-DH2 platform
and is primarily focused on production from the southern area of the
field. Output from the field is tied back to the FSO Kamari.
Petrovietnam is the sole owner and operator of the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  18.8 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.3  deg. C.

sulfur (0.07 wt percent), and waxy with a high pour point (86 degrees
F). Dai Hung has initial reserves of 69 million boe. By year end 2011,
about 31 million boe remain. The field came onstream in 1994 and in
2011, production averaged 5,500 b/d. Production is expected to increase
to a peak of 15,400 b/d in 2012 due to the newly installed WHP-DH2
platform that is primarily focused on production from the southern area

Name: Dai Hung Exp Bld(PVEP)'05
Comments:
2005 PVEP (VietsovPetro --a 50/50 venture with the Russians) assay.
crude has increased in gravity by 2*API from historical data.  this

re-blended fractions on which data were produced that are not the best.
 DHA is missing. The Dai Hung Oil field, offshore Vietnam, is comprised
of a complex subsurface structure containing stacked reservoir
sequences typically found in many other Southeast Asian fields.
Combined with areal fault compartmentalisation, this situation has led
to the observed, large variations in oil properties. It is sweet,
medium gravity and moderately waxy. in 2004, a new field was brough to
onstream and added to the segregation.

Name: Dalia Fld (TOTAL) '98
Comments:
Pre-production sample.  The crude is low sulphur & naphthenic, with
high yields in distillates (gasoil and vacuum gasoil). It is
particularly suitable for refineries with thermal and catalytic
conversion capabilities. Synergies might be obtained by proce ssing
Dalia in a blend with a light, low TAN, paraffinic crude. Naphtha
yields are low, but with an N+2A above 80 the naphtha is an excellent
feedstock for gasoline production kerosene suitable for jet fuel
production after hydrotreatment rather than swe etening, with giveaways
on aromatics content and freezing point in a wide range of boiling
points. Gasoil high yields of gasoil with very good cold properties.
Due to the giveaway on cold properties, it is an attractive endstock
with other more paraffini c gasoils having giveaways on cetane.
Cracking feedstock high yields of vacuum gasoil with a modest sulphur
content and acceptable K factor. Suitable to increase cracker yields of
transportation fuels. Residue bottoms are a good visbreaking feedstock.
Th e residue of visbreaking is suitable as a component in low to
medium-sulphur fuel oil
*** The GC Analysis Covers   4.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.4  deg. C.

Name: Dar Blend (ITS) '05
Comments:
Dar blend is a heavy high acid crude oil (peak production 200Mbpd
reached in 2006, 26API, 0.11%S, 2.4TAN) produced in Sudan (Adar Yeild,
tale fields). The field is developed by a consortium consisting of Cnpc
(41%), Malaysia's Petronas (40%), Sudapet (8% ), Sinopec (6%) and
Dubai's Al-Thami (5%). Channoil gave us oil marketing summary and crude
oil assay. The crude is paraffinic, has very high pour point, high wax
content, high Ni and N content. Middle distillates have good burning
properties. Main issue  is poor cold flow properties, Ni and high N (if
sold in direct burning market). Odd yield profile, reported assay data
indicates the blend is spiked with both condensate and a heavy
component (such as topped crude).  Also, reported yields have not been
normalized nor does the start-350F balance. Even so, the gas yields are
absurd. They were ignored because expansion is negative and balance is
poor.

Name: Das Blend (CVX) Oct 14 '14
Comments:
Das Blend is a light gravity, mid-level sulfur crude oil (39.6 degrees

is sent, processed and blended at Das Island. Das crude is expected to
produce sour naphtha (greater than 300 ppm RSH). The Abu Dhabi Marine
Operating Company consortium owns and operates the lower Zakum and Umm
Shaif fields as well as the DAS facilities. Participants of the
consortium are state owned ADNOC (60 percent), BP (14.7 percent),
Japan's Jodco (12 percent), and Total SA (13.3 percent). Bunduq is
operated by the Bunduq Oil Company which includes Cosmo Oil (43.65
percent), JX Nippon Oil and Energy Corp (43.65 percent), MOECO (9.7
percent) and BP (3 percent). Total operates the Abu Al Bukhoosh field
and holds 75 percent interest and INPEX holds the remaining 25 percent.

Name: DIANA HOOVER/HOOPS PL (BP) '01
Comments:
The constituent fields Diana (East Breaks 945, 946, 988 & 989), South

(East Breaks 949), and Madison (Alaminos Canyon 24 & 25) are located

Caisson Vessel (DDCV) in 4,800 ft. of water at the Hoover site. Diana,

then flows over to the Hoover DDCV where it is commingled with
theHoover. XOM is operator and the production goes into HOOPS Blend.
Kerr-McGees' production from their Boomvang and Nansen fields is
commingled offshore with the Diana/Hoover/Marshall/Madison fields via
the Williams operated Banjo Pipeline.   It is then called HOOPS Blend.
HOOPS Blend is delivered mainly into the Cushing, OK and Texas Gulf
Coast markets. HOOPS Blend is a medium sulfur domestic crude oil with a
naphthenic acid content of approximately 0.93 MG/GM. H2S DISSOLVED
below detection limit POUR POINT <-76

Name: Diluted Crude Oil DCO (CVX) '17
Comments:
DCO is typically produced whenever upgrader production issues occur. It
is a blended crude oil consisting of Hamaca Petropriar (Ayacucho), an
extra heavy crude oil (6-8 degrees API) produced in the Venezuela s
Orinoco Oil Tar Belt, and either Naphtha (47-50 degrees API), Mesa (30
degrees API) or Santa Barbara (39 degrees API) to produce a Diluted
Crude Oil of 16-18 degrees API. The Hamaca concession, which includes
the Boyaca (Machete), Junin (Zuata), Ayacucho (Hamaca), and Carabobo
(Cerro Negro) fields, covers 160,000 acres, has a reserve estimate of
235 billion boe, and is expected to produce approximately 2.1 billion
barrels of extra heavy crude oil over 35 years. Petroleos Venezuela,
the operator, holds a 70 percent interest and Chevron holds the
remaining 30 percent. DCO is a heavy (16.8 degrees API), high sulfur
(3.08 wt percent), acidic (2.35 mg KOH/g) diluted crude with high As
concentration (94.7 ppb). The vacuum residuum is predicted to have high
Nitrogen (11,100 ppm) and Ni+V (1,080 ppm) concentrations.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  12.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.7  deg. C.

assayreports an exceptionaly high level of olefins.

Name: Djeno (ITS) Nov 26 '13
Comments:
Djeno is a low sulfur, medium gravity crude oil (API 30.2 degrees and
0.27 wt percent sulfur) produced from several offshore fields in the
Pointe Noire Grand Fonde and Pex permit area in the Congo Basin which
includes the Total operated Yanga, Sendji, Tchibouela, Tchendo,
Likalala, Emeraude, Likouala fields, and the Eni operated Zatchi and
Loango fields. In 2008, Total's offshore Moho-Bilondo field, located in
the Haute Mer Block, came on stream and was added to the blend. Djeno
blend production averaged 175,680 b/d in 2012. Output from all of the
Congo's fields are transported to the Total operated terminal where
they are mixed into either the Djeno or N'Kossa blends. Total holds a
65 percent share in the Pointe Noire Grand Fonde and Pex permit area
with Eni holding the remaining 35 percent. The Moho-Bilondo is held by
Total (53.5 percent), Chevron (31.5 percent) and state Societe
Nationale des Petroles du Congo (15 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  12.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.2  deg. C.

Name: Djeno (Total) '10
Comments:
Djeno is a low sulfur, medium gravity crude oil (API 27.3 deg and 0.42
wt percent sulfur) that is produced from several offshore fields in the
Pointe Noire Grand Fonde and Pex permit area in the Congo Basin.
Contributing fields includes the Total operated Yanga, Sendji,
Tchibouela, Tchendo, Likalala, Emeraude, Likouala fields, and the Eni
operated Zatchi and Loango fields. In 2008, Total's offshore
Moho-Bilondo field, located in the Haute Mer Block in water depths from
600 - 900 m, came on stream and was added to the blend. Output from all
Djeno contributing, as well as all of the Congo s other fields, are
transported to the Total operated terminal where they are mixed into
either the Djeno or N'Kossa blends. Due to the addition of the
Moho-Bilondo field, 2008 production of the Djeno blend rose to around
190,000 b/d. Total holds a 65 percent share in the Pointe Noire Grand
Fonde and Pex permit area with Eni holding the remaining 35 percent.
The Moho-Bilondo is held by Total (53.5 percent), Chevron (31.5
percent) and state Societe Nationale des Petroles du Congo (15 percent).

GULF RAN A CARGO OF DJENO IN PHILADELPHIA IN APRIL 1983.

Name: Doba Blend (XOM) '15
Comments:
Doba blend is comprised of the output from several fields located in
southern Chad's Doba Basin. Bolobo, Miandoum, and Kome were the first
to startup in 2003-2004. Nya, Moundouli, and Maikeri were brought on
stream from 2005-2007 and Timbre was the last stream startup in 2009.
In April 2014, a portion of Badila oil was added to the stream.
Together, initial recoverable reserves were 739 million boe of which,
174 million boe remains (2016). Production in 2016 averaged 66,000 b/d.
Output is transported to an offshore export terminal at Kribi on
Cameroon's Atlantic coast via the Chad-Cameroon Pipeline. Doba is a
medium gravity (25.1 degrees API), low sulfur (0.08 wt percent), acidic
(2.16 mg KOH/g) crude oil with a high calcium concentration (160 ppm).
It is expected to have a high ARES yield (74.8 vol percent). ExxonMobil
operates the field and holds 40 percent interest. Other partners are
SHT (25 percent) and Petronas (35 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers   3.9 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   131.7  deg. C.

In April 2014, a portion of Badila oil was added to the stream.
Together, initial recoverable reserves were 739 million boe of which,

Name: Doba Exp Bld (CVX) '10
Comments:
The Doba blend of crude oil comes from Bolobo, Miandoum, and Kome oil
fields located in southern Chad's Doba Basin. From 2005-2007, three
more satellite fields (Nya, Moundouli, and Maikeri) were brought on
stream. Doba is heavy crude (21.1 deg API) with low sulfur content (0.1
weight percent Sulfur), has an acidic nature, and high calcium content.
The Bolobo, Miandoum, and Kome fields have estimated reserves of 135
million, 227 million, and 588 million boe, respectively. Production in
2009 averaged 120,000 b/d, down from its peak production rate of
215,000 b/d in 2004. Although new fields were introduced, production
has steadily declined because of the field s geographical complexity,
effects of early water breakthrough, and lack of reservoir pressure.
Extensive use of injector wells are used throughout the fields because
of the low reservoir pressure. Chevron has a 25 percent interest along
with ExxonMobil (operator, with 40 percent) and Petronas (35 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers   1.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.5  deg. C.

Comments:
2009 standardized report from Shell.  This segregation is not related

the Shetland Islands and 7.5 miles north of the Thistle Field, in a
water depth of about 500 feet. The Don field was discovered in July
1976 and started producing in Oct 1989. Output was commingled into
Brent Bld and peaked in 1991 but the field ceased production in 2001.
Don West and Don SW (in License P236 (Block 211/18a)) were bought from
BP and COP and brought onstream by operator Petrofac and its partners
(First Oil, Nippon, Valiant and Stratic) 1H 2009 and called Don Blend.
 Production is expected  to peak at 50 kBD.
Exports from the Don West
and Don Southwest fields will be from the FPSO Northern Producer.

South-West.

Name: Dubai (ITS) Aug 4 '14
Reference: CVX sample with lab tests by ITS
Comments:
Dubai, a light (30.8 degrees API) sour (1.95 wt percent sulfur) crude
oil, is composed of the output of four fields, Fateh, Fateh South West,
Rashid, and Falah, in the DPE contract area located offshore Dubai in
the Eastern Gulf Basin. The fields came on stream between 1969 (Fateh)
to 1978 (Falah) and had an initial reserves of 3.9 billion boe, 288
million bbl LPG, and 79 million bbl condensate. Fateh, Fateh South
West, Rashid, and Falah have about 3 billion boe, 2.65 billion boe, 500
million boe and 110 million boe oil in place, respectively. The DPE
contract area is in decline and has remaining recoverable reserves of
155 million boe, 14 million bbl LPG, and 9 million bbl condensate
(2014). Despite increased drilling, Dubai's oil output has fallen from
66,000 b/d in 2008 to 44,000 b/d in 2014. Output from Rashid, Fateh
South West and Falah are piped to the Fateh loading terminal which
consists of two offshore loading facilities located 96 km
north-northwest offshore Dubai. Al Jalia field came onstream in 2011
and is tied to the Rashid field. Dubai Petroleum Establishment (DPE)

Dubai, a light (31 API) sour (2 wt percent sulfur) crude oil, is

Basin. The fields came on stream between 1969 (Fateh) to 1978 (Falah)

and 79 million bbl condensate. Fateh, Fateh South West, Rashid, and

decline and has remaining recoverable reserves of 165 million boe, 20
million bbl LPG, and 13 million bbl condensate (2011). Despite
increased drilling, Dubai's output has been falling, from 66,000 b/d in
2008 to 44,600 b/d in 2010. Output from Rashid, Fateh South West and
Falah are piped to the Fateh loading terminal which consists of two
offshore loading facilities located 96 km north-northwest offshore
Dubai. Al Jalia field had just come onstream in 2011 and is tied to the

field.

Comments:
The Dumbarton field, located in Blocks 15/20a and 15/20b offshore UK

barrels of oil over a period of five years. Dumbarton crude oil is

70 percent equity. Noble Energy holds the remaining 30 percent equity.

Comments:
The Eagle Ford Shale play extends from the Mexican border into East
Texas. It covers an area that is 400 miles long, 50 miles wide, and is
4000-12,000 ft deep. It is estimated that Eagle Ford holds 4 tcf of
shale gas and 3 billion boe shale oil. The condensate produced in Eagle
Ford has an API range of 47-56 degrees and sulfur of up to 0.2 wt
percent. Several companies, including Anadarko Petroleum, Chesapeake
Energy,CNOOC-China Nat l Offshore Oil Co, ConocoPhillips, Hess
Corporation, Koch Oil, Korea National Oil Corporation, Marathon Oil,
Mitsui Oil Exploration, Murphy Exploration and Production, Newfield
Exploration, Petrohawk, Pioneer Natural Resources, Reliance Industries,
SM Energy Company, Statoil, and Talisman Energy, are operating in the
play. Current Production (2011) is estimated at 750 MM cf/d of gas and
80 kBD of crude oil and condensate. Production is expected to
drastically increase from its current level to 750,000-800,000 b/d in
the near future. As a result, crude oil facilities as well as several
pipelines in the area are either being upgraded or built to increase
Eagle Ford export and storage capacity.

Name: Eagle Ford Condensate (SPL) '11
Comments:
The Eagle Ford Shale is a hydrocarbon producing formation of
significant importance due to its capability of producing both gas and
more oil than other traditional shale plays. It contains a much higher
carbonate shale percentage, upwards to 70 percent in south Texas, and
becomes shallower and the shale content increases as it moves to the
northwest. The high percentage of carbonate makes it more brittle and
fracable . The shale play trends across Texas from the Mexican border
up into East Texas, roughly 50 miles wide and 400 miles long with an
average thickness of 250 feet. It is Cretaceous in age resting between
the Austin Chalk and the Buda Lime at a depth of approximately 4,000 to
12,000 feet. It is the source rock for the Austin Chalk and the giant
East Texas Field
*** The GC Analysis Covers  45.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   140.8  deg. C.

Name: Ebok (Core) JUN '11
Comments:
Ebok is a medium gravity, low sulfur crude oil (21.1 degree API and
0.34 wt percent sulfur). The field is located in OML 67 in Nigeria's
south eastern producing area, about 50 km offshore in 135 ft water
depths. Ebok holds 102 million boe of proved and probable reserves. The
field was discovered by an ExxonMobil/NNPC Joint Venture in 1968 and
was awarded to Oriental Energy Resources in 2007. Production began in
February 2011 with an initial rate of 15,000b/d. Production is expected
to ramp up to 35,000 by the end of 2011 then peak to 50,000 b/d by
2012. Output is processed at the Ebok Mobile Offshore Processing Unit
(MOPU) then sent to the 1.2 million boe capacity Virini Prem FSO.
Afren, the operator, holds a 100 percent pre cost recovery working
interest. Post cost recovery interest will be split equally with joint
venture partner Oriental Energy Resources.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   2.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   131.9  deg. C.

Name: Ebok (CSA) Jun 2011
Comments:
Ebok is a medium gravity, low sulfur, naphthenic crude oil (21.2 deg
API, 0.3 wt percent Sulfur). The Ebok field is located in OML 67
approximately 50 km offshore in 135 ft water depths in Nigeria's south
eastern producing area. It contains certified reserves of 106.2 million
boe. The field was discovered by the ExxonMobil/ NNPC Joint Venture in
1968 then awarded to Oriental Energy Resources in 2007. Initial
production will take place in two phases that will access 60 percent of
the certified reserves. Phase 1 will target the Central Area of the
field and Phase 2 will cover the West Fault Block area of the field.
Together, production capacity is expected to reach 35,000 b/d. In
February 2011 the 50,000 b/d production capacity Mobile Offshore
Production Unit (MOPU) started up. Output will be sent to the 1.2
million boe capacity Virini Prem Floating, Storage Offloading Vessel
(FSO). Afren is the operator and holds a 100 percent pre-cost recovery
working interest. Post-cost recovery interest will be split equally
with joint venture partner Oriental Energy Resources.

The Chevron operated Escravos Gas Plant (EGP-3A) processes gas and
liquids produced from the Meji, Okan, Mefam and Delta South fields
located in OML 90, offshore Nigeria in the Niger Delta. EGP-3A started
up in June 2010 and has an onshore production capacity of 395 mmcfd of
gas, 34,000 b/d of LPG and 9,000 b/d of condensate and a total plant
capacity of 680 mmcfd of gas and 58,000 b/d of LPG and condensate. The
plant produces product condensate streams A and B from two separate
processing trains which are blended then injected into the Escravos
crude blend. The EGP 80 percent A/ 20 percent B condensate blend will
be exported as its own clean product once construction of the pipeline
and related infrastructure to export is complete. Joint venture
partners of OML 90 are Chevron (40 percent) and state owned Nigerian
National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) (60 percent). The EGP 80 percent
A/ 20 percent B condensate blend is light gravity and sweet (60.8
degrees API and 0.005 wt percent sulfur).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  72.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   141.7  deg. C.

Name: Ekofisk  Blend (Statoil) '11
Comments:
Ekofisk blend is a light, paraffinic, low sulfur crude (38.4 deg API
and 0.2 weight percent sulfur). The blend is mainly composed of the
output from four fields (Ekofisk, Eldfisk, Embla, and Tor) that are
combined into a single stream at the Ekofisk hub and is then
transported by the 700,000 b/d Norpipe pipeline to Teesside, UK for
tanker loading and export. Other crudes from the UK fields in the
J-Block of the Fulmar area of the UK central North Sea are tied into
the Ekofisk-Teeside pipeline to the UK's east coast. The field, which
came online in 1971, is located 320 km off of the coast of Norway. The
initial reserve estimate was 3.5 billion boe. By year end 2009, 769
million boe remain, however 10 other Norwegian fields that contribute
to the blend contain 808 million boe. The average production rate for
2009 was 387,000 b/d, down 38,000 b/d from the previous year. The
decline in production is expected to continue through 2010. Conoco,
Talisman and BP operate both the Norwegian and UK fields while Shell
and Maersk operate solely in the UK fields. Ekofisk blend has 21 joint
venture partners.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  25.5 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   143.0  deg. C.

Name: Eocene (CVX) '14
Comments:
Eocene is a low gravity, high sulfur crude (17.9 degrees API and 4.0 wt
percent sulfur) that is expected to produce sour naphtha (323 wt ppm).
Eocene is produced from three shallow, yet large formations (First
Eocene, Second Eocene, and Maestritchian) in the Wafra, Fuwaris, South
Umm Gudair, and Humma fields in the Partitioned Neutral Zone (PNZ)
located between Kuwait and the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia. Oil was
discovered in 1953, and first production began in 1956. The production
rate in 2008 reached 80,000 b/d however this is expected to
significantly rise with the 2009 startup of Chevron's Large Scale Pilot
Steamflood Project, the first commercial application of a conventional
steamflood in a carbonate reservoir anywhere in the world. Eocene
reservoir volumes are estimated at 23.0 billion boe in place. Saudi
Arabian Chevron (SAC) operates under a 60 year concession originally
awarded to Getty Oil Co. in 1959 and inherited by Texaco then Chevron.
The concession, which was set to expire in 2009, was extended by 30
years in 2008. SAC and Kuwait Gulf Oil Co. jointly operate the field
and each hold a 50 percent interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   7.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.2  deg. C.

Name: Eocene Exp Bld(Core) '07
Comments:
Eocene, like our Ratawi crude, is produced from the Wafra, South Umm
Gudair and South Fuwaris fields in the Partitioned Neutral Zone (PNZ)
situated between Kuwait and the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.  It is
exported out of Mina Saud terminal in the Kuwait-controlled PNZ. Eocene
is a heavy, high sulfur crude oil, similar in many respects to grades
such as the Egyptian Gisum. It is suitable for asphalt manufacture.
Chevron's assets in the Partitioned Neutral Zone (PNZ) come from
Texaco's acquisition of Getty Oil's interests in the area including the
long-term concession granted by the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia to Getty
Oil in 1949. Production of both Ratawi & Eocene grades of crude oil
were consumed locally until the refining facilities were destroyed in
1993 during the Gulf War and Ratawi crude had to be exported. Ratawi is
produced from the smaller, deeper Ratawi reservoir of the Wafra field
while Eocene is produced from the larger, shallow Eocene reservoir
which overlays the Ratawi accumulation. Production from the two fields
is divided equally between Kuwait and the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   5.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   129.4  deg. C.

Name: Eocene Exp Bld(Core) '09
Comments:
2009 Dec sample sent to Core labs for tfa assay on behalf of CVX as
part of the obligation to assay production.  As of mid-2010, cargoes
are running closer to 18.4 API. The crude is exported out of Mina Saud
terminal in the Kuwait-controlled PNZ. Chevron has been producing oil
on behalf of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia in the onshore Partitioned
Zone (PZ) between Kuwait and Saudi Arabia since 1949. A 30-year amended
extension of the operating agreement governing this arrangement was
granted in early 2009. During 2009, 62 wells were drilled in the PZ,
and 1,025 were producing at the end of 2009. In 2009, Chevron began
steamflooding of the First Eocene reservoir, marking the first
commercial application of a conventional steamflood in a carbonate
reservoir anywhere in the world. A carbonate reservoir is an oil or gas
trap formed in reefs, dolomite or certain types of limestone.

The Erha terminal is located within the Gulf of Guinea off the Nigerian
coast at approximate center point position  5  21 36N  4  21  00 E.
This Terminal is about 85 nautical miles South East of Lagos Port.
The Terminal consists of a spread-moored floating production and
offloading [FPSO] unit that has a design storage capacity of 2.2
million barrels of crude oil. The FPSO is also equipped to take the
same export tanker in tandem moor from the facility's North end as an
emergency offloading regime via a single 16 inch hose string. The
Terminal is operated on a 24-hour schedule seven days a week throughout
the year, operational circumstances permitting.  Ships are berthed only
during daylight hours but ships can unberth any time of the day.

the output of several fields in the region including Bella, Benin
River, Benue River, Dibi, Ejulebe, Ewan, Gilli Gilli, Mefa, Meren,
Okan, Opolo, and Opuekeba. Most of Escravos is used domestically and is
processed at the Warri refinery and a minor amount is blended into the
West Hackberry Sweet grade. Escravos started up in 1968 and production
averaged 166,000 b/d (2015). Escravos is loaded from the
Chevron-operated Escravos Terminal, which can accommodate Very Large
Crude Carrier (VLCC) loading. Chevron, the operator, holds 40 percent

Name: ESPO (CVX) '13
Comments:
ESPO, also known as ESPO blend, is comprised of several different
crudes that feed into the East Siberia-Pacific Ocean (ESPO) pipeline.
The ESPO pipeline system was built in two stages. Stage 1, completed in
December 2009, consists of a 2,694 km, 600,000 b/d capacity pipeline
that runs from T2,694 km pipeline linking Taishet in the Irkutsk Oblast
 to Skovorodino, seven pumping stations, and an oil export terminal at
Kozmino Bay. In September 2010, a spur connecting Skovorodino to Daqing
 in China was completed in September 2010 and began transporting
300,000  b/d in January 2011. Stage 2, completed on December 2012,
increased  capacity to 1.6 million b/d and linked Skovorodino to the
Port of  Kozmino, located on Russia's Pacific coast. The ESPO pipeline
currently  transports just over 300,000 b/d to Skovorodino where it is
then  transported via rail to Kozmino. Crudes from the
Verkhnechonskoye,  Talakanskoye, Dulisminskoye fields and Irkutsk Oil
Company's fields in  East Siberia as well as Vankorneft fields in the
Krasnoyarsk Krai all  contribute the blend. ESPO's total capacity is 1
million b/d and its  current throughput is 715,000 b/d (2013). ESPO is
a light, low sulfur  crude (35.4 degrees API and 0.51 wt percent
sulfur) with a high  measured As content (77 ppm). Transeft operates
the pipeline and  Rosneft, TNK-BP, Surgutneftegas and Gazprom Neft all
contribute to the  blend.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  17.5 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.8  deg. C.

Name: ESPO EXP BLD (Shell) '11
Comments:
ESPO East Siberian crude oil, also known as ESPO blend, is comprised of
several different crudes that feed into the East Siberia-Pacific Ocean
(ESPO) pipeline. The ESPO pipeline system is being built in two stages.
Stage 1, which is complete, has a 600,000 b/d capacity and runs from
Taishet in East Siberia to Skovorodino, located 60 kilometers north of
the Chinese border. Stage 2 will increase capacity to 1.6 million b/d
and link Skovorodino to the Port of Kozmino, located on Russia's
Pacific coast. The ESPO pipeline currently transports just over 300,000
b/d to Skovorodino where it is then transported via rail to Kozmino.
Crudes from several Siberian fields such as Talakan, Verkhnechonsk,
Taishet and Yaraktinskoye all contribute the blend. ESPO, which started
up 2009, has a 36.0 deg API and 0.60 weight percent sulfur. However
since the blend is new to the market and EPSO pipeline has yet to be
completed, the blend's quality is expected change. Transeft operates
the pipeline and Rosneft, TNK-BP, Surgutneftegas and Gazprom Neft all
contribute to the blend.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  20.5 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.3  deg. C.

Name: Etame (CVX) '13
Comments:
The Etame, also known as Etame Marin, is a waxy, light gravity (35.5
degrees API) low sulfur crude oil (0.07 wt percent) with a high pour
point (87.8 degrees F) and high measured lead content (54 ppb). The
field is located in the northern section of the Congo Basin, offshore
southern Gabon, and West Africa. The Etame Marin grade currently
includes the Avouma/Tchibala South, Ebouri, and Etame fields. During
the 2H 2014, the SE Etame and Tchibala North fields, which are part of
the larger Etame Marin concession, are expected to come online. Etame
was discovered in 1998 and started production in 2002. In 2013,
production averaged 17,500 b/d. Initial reserves were estimated at 131
million bbl and remaining reserves are estimated at 53 million boe.
Output from the field is tie back to the Petr leo Nautipa FPSO which
has a production capacity of 30,000 b/d of oil, a gas handling capacity
of 10 mmcfd and a storage capacity of 1.08 million boe. The field is
operated by Vaalco Energy (28.07 percent). Other partners are Addax
(31.36 percent), Sasol (27.75 percent), Tullow Oil (7.5 percent),
Sojitz (2.98 percent), and PetroEnergy Resources (2.34 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers   7.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.8  deg. C.

Comments:
The Forcados Blend is produced from several fields in the Western

capacity of 440,000 b/d, however, production in 2011 was held to
219,000 b/d due to Nigeria's security situation. Forcados is light
gravity (30.4 deg API), low sulfur (0.29 weight percent) crude oil.

with 5 percent equity and Total with 10 percent equity. Nigerian

Name: Forties Blend (Statoil) '11
Comments:
Forties Blend is a composite of over 70 fields that range from
condensate to moderately sour crude and operated by over 40 companies.
Forties came on stream in 1975 and produced about 315,000 b/d in 2009.
The Buzzard field, which came on stream in 2007, contributes 30 percent
making it the main contributor to the blend. Forties is a light gravity
(38.7 degrees API), low sulfur crude oil (0.8 wt percent). Output from
the contributing fields are transported onshore through the BP operated
Forties Pipeline System (FPS) to Cruden Bay in Aberdeenshire then piped
further to Hounds Point. BP is the largest interest holder of the
stream with about 20-25 percent and Nexen, the majority holder of
Buzzard, holds about 15 percent interest. Other owners are BG, Apache
and Suncor with about 10 percent interest each. This assay represents
39 percent Buzzard.

Name: Forties-Buzzard Bld (BP) '06
Comments:
Projected blend for FPS with addition of the Buzzard Field.  Estimated
gravity by 2007 is 41.7:  notes from BP web site: release date: 08
March 2006 BP, the operator of the Forties Pipeline System (Fps), today
issued guidance on the effect that introduct ion of oil from the
Nexen-operated Buzzard Field into the FPS would be expected to have on
Forties Blend crude oil when Buzzard begins production.  Oil from the
Buzzard field will be exported through the Forties Pipeline System and
so become a constituen t of Forties Blend crude, affecting its
hydrocarbon characteristics. Buzzard is expected to begin production
late in 2006 and build up to peak production of approximately 210,000
barrels a day in 2007.  Initial assays on Buzzard crude made by Nexen
indic ate that the oil is a medium gravity, sour crude with an API of
32.6 degrees and whole crude sulphur level of 1.44% wt. Current Forties
Blend crude (sampled in march 2005) has an API of 44.6 degrees and
sulphur level of 0.20% wt.   As a result of the int roduction of
Buzzard crude into the FPS, it is expected that the API of Forties
Blend crude in 2007 will be some 2.9 degrees lower than currently and
3.5 degrees lower in 2010, when it would be expected to have an API of
around 41 degrees, similar to the  gravity the blend had in 1997. Over
the same period to 2010, the sulphur level of Forties Blend would be
expected to rise to around 0.56% wt.  Full details of a projected assay
of Forties Blend in 2007, when it would be expected to contain
approximately  23 per cent Buzzard crude, and further information on
the impact this would have on the properties of the blend are contained
in the information issued today by BP.  The full information note and
assay can be viewed on www.bpcrudes.com or a copy obtaine d from
alex.stacey@bp.com, telephone +44(0)20 7948 3496.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  29.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.5  deg. C.

Name: Frade Exp Bld (CVX) '10
Comments:
May 2010 discharge sample. Most wells are online but a few remain to be
connected.  Final development will be completed by Oct. Frade is a
deepwater oil field located offshore Brazil, 120 kilometers northeast
of Rio de Janeiro. The Frade Field contains an estimated 200 million to
300 million barrels of recoverable oil and is located in the RJ363
Campos Basin in a water depth of 3,500 feet, approximately 75 miles
offshore the state of Rio de Janeiro. It will produce 100K b/d to the
Frade FSPO. The Frade Field is Chevron's first producing, and only
operated, oil field in Brazil. The development project was approved by
Chevron (51.74%) and partners Petrobras (30%) and FJPL (18.26%), a
Japanese consortium, in the second quarter of 2006. It is an "anchor
development" whose reserves, production and revenue will provide cash
flow for the development of the company's other four Brazilian
deepwater projects (Papa Terra, Maromba, Atlanta and Oliva). Aluminium
below detection limit Barium below detection limit Chromium below
detection limit Copper below detection limit Potassium below detection
limit Molybdenum below detection limit Silicon below detection limit

Name: Frade Exp Bld (CVX) Jan '11
Comments:
Chevron operated Frade is located offshore in Brazil's northern Campos
Basin about 230 miles NE of Rio De Janeiro in under 3500-3700 ft of

19.8 degrees and 0.7 wt percent sulfur. The crude also has high arsenic
levels (56 ppb) and is expected to produce a vacuum residuum that is
high in nitrogen (10,300 ppm). Frade's initial recoverable reserves are
estimated at 245 million boe, with 196 million boe remaining (2011).
The field came onstream in June 2009 with an initial production rate of
5,000 b/d. Peak production of 70,000 b/d was reached in 2011. Frade
output is tied back to the Frade FPSO, which has a crude processing
capacity of 100,000 b/d and a storage capacity of 1.5 million boe.
Joint venture partners are Chevron Corporation (51.74 percent), Japao
Petroleo Ltd, a consortium made up of Inpex, Sojitz and Jogmec (18.26
percent), and Petrobras (30 percent).

Name: Galeota Exp Bld (CVX) '09
Comments:
2009 assay update.  The Galeota Block lies in water depths of 12 to 30m
and sporadically saw development from 1970 until 1985, during which
production peaked at some 5,200 b/d of 25-28 API crude. The block
contains several oil fields served by four production platforms that
were installed between 1972 and 1984. Production is currently down to
about 1,400 bo/d, but additional exploration and development
opportunities exist, particularly on the eastern side of the block.
Petrotrin estimates remaining potential reserves of 200 to 500 MMbo.
The East Coast acreage consists of East Galeota, (67 sq km), Galeota
(35 sq km), Manzanilla (145 sq km), Palmiste (37 sq km) and West
Galeota (191 sq km) blocks and is located in the Columbus Sub-basin.

Name: Ghana Light Blend (ITS) '11
Comments:
Ghana Light Blend consists of the output from the Jubilee field and
other smaller fields in the region. Jubilee is a super giant deepwater
oil field that lies in the West Cape Three Points license and the Tano
block located about 37 miles off the coast of Ghana, in the Gulf of
Guinea under 1100-1700 m water depths. Jubilee is a supergiant field
that holds 1.2 - 1.5 billion boe recoverable reserves. Phase 1 of the
project came on stream on December 2010. In May 2011, production
reached 70,000 b/d. By August 2011, Jubilee is expected to reach its
production capacity of 120,000 b/d. Output is tied to the Kwameh
Nkrumah MV21 FPSO which has a storage capacity of 1.6 million boe and
can process 120,000 barrels of crude and 160 million cubic feet of gas
per day. Ghana Light Blend is a light, low sulfur crude oil (37.1 deg
API and 0.09 wt percent sulfur). Tullow Oil operates Jubilee and holds
a 36.46 percent stake. Other participants are Anadarko Petroleum (23.49
percent), GNPC of Ghana (13.75 percent), Kosmos Energy (23.49 percent),

Name: Gippsland Exp Bld (XOM) '08
Comments:
2008 sample and XOM web assay. In 1965 an Esso/BHP Billiton joint
venture drilled Australia's first offshore well and discovered the
Barracouta gas field in Bass Strait.Gippsland shows seasonality with
added condensate.  Two years later Kingfish was discovered, the first
offshore oil field, which to this day remains the largest oil field
ever discovered in Australia..  Gippsland Blend (aka Bass Strait).
There are now 21 offshore platforms and installations in Bass Strait,
which feed a network of 600km of underwater pipelines and keep the oil
and gas flowing, 24 hours a day.  By 2011 that number will increase to
23, with the addition of the new Marlin B platform and Kipper sub-sea
wells.  To date, almost four billion barrels of crude oil and around
seven trillion cubic feet of gas have been produced - with more than 30
years of gas still to be produced.

Name: Girassol (ITS) '14
Comments:
Girassol crude oil is produced from offshore Angolan oil fields located
in Block 17, about 95 miles from the Luanda coast. It includes
production from the Girassol, Jasmim, and Rosa fields which are all
tied back to the Girassol FPSO which has a 270,000 b/d processing
capacity and can store up to 2 million barrels of oil. Girassol, the
first to come online, started up in 2001 and Jasmim started up in 2003.
Together, these two fields had 971 million barrels of recoverable oil
and 193 million barrels of remaining recoverable reserves (2014). Rosa
had 417 million barrels of recoverable oil and about 221 million boe
remain (2014). In 2013, output from Girassol/Jasmim averaged 112,000
b/d and Rosa averaged 102,000 b/d. Girassol is a light (30.2 degrees
API) and low sulfur (0.3 wt percent) crude oil. Block 17 is operated by
Total (40 percent). Other partners include Statoil (23.33 percent),
ExxonMobil (20 percent), and BP (16.67 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  11.9 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.5  deg. C.

Name: Girassol exp bld (BP) '02
Comments:
This assay is in the public domain. Girassol is a low acidity, medium
sulphur, heavy crude oil with high vanadium and nickel content.  The
crude oil sulphur balance from the distillation products was 100%
recovery (0.36 %wt).  Crude oil methanol content by GC (on water
extract) 164ppm.  Kerosene (149-232) density, sulphur and freeze point
fit specification for jet A1. Gasoil / diesel (232-342) may be ok
untreated in some gas oil products, but many markets require 0.05 %wt S
in diesel.   Vacuum gas oil ( 369-550) medium density, sweet.  Low
basic nitrogen content indicates possible FCC feed.   Dewaxed oil data
indicates possible lube potential.  Atmospheric residue (>369) medium
density, low sulphur, metals content and carbon residue content
indicate sho uld process in a vacuum distillation stage to separate wax
distillate as FCC feed.    Vacuum residue (>509, >550) medium, sweet,
indicates suitability for low sulphur fuel oil production.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  13.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.1  deg. C.

Name: Girassol Exp Bld (Total) '07
Comments:
In 1996 when the reserves of Girassol were discovered in deep water on
Block 17, Angola went from being a solid but average oil producing
country to become a hotspot in the global search for major oil
reserves.
When Girassol came on stream in late 2001, the line on
Angola's oil production graph moved upwards exponentially. It is a
trend that is set to continue as more offshore fields are brought into
production.
Thus far, deep water discoveries off Angola's Atlantic
coast have reached success rates of about 80%. On Block 17, commercial
discoveries were found in all drilled wells - Rose, Dahlia, Orchid,
Jasmine, Tulip and Sunflower (Girassol in Portuguese).
The total
oil production for Angola in 2001 was below one million barrels per
day (bpd). By the end of 2005 production of crude in Angola surpassed
1.4 million bpd and that it will reach two million bpd in the first
trimester of 2008.With the fast-paced advance of drilling technology
and the success of Blocks 15 and 17, there are great expectations for
results of ultra-deep water (i.e. drilling at depths greater than
2.000 meters) exploration off Angola's coast.
Angolan ultra deep
water Blocks are numbered 31 to 34. With reserves of blocks 31 and 32
estimated to be at about 800 million barrels within the next 15 years
Angola may become one of the major oil producers in the southern
hemisphere.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   9.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   130.7  deg. C.

Name: Gorgon Condensate (CVX) '16
Comments:
Gorgon is a large gas and condensate field located offshore Western
Australia in the Carnarvon Basin that produces condensate with an API
between 51-53 degrees and a very low sulfur concentration (0.01 wt
percent). The field holds 285 million barrels of condensate and 42.7
tcf gas. In March 2016, the first LNG Gorgon cargo was shipped. The
Gorgon project is expected to produce 2,000 b/d and 310 mcf gas/day in
2016. Peak condensate production is expected to reach 18,630 b/d in
2023. Chevron operates the field and holds 47.33 percent interest.
Other partners are Exxon Mobil (25 percent), Shell (25 percent), Osaka

percent).

Name: Grane (Statoil) Dec '14
Comments:
Grane is a heavy gravity (20.3 degrees API), low sulfur (0.8 wt
percent), acidic (2.5 mg KOH/g) crude oil. The Grane field covers three
licenses, PL169 B1 (block 25/11c), PL169 B2 (block 25/11d), and PL001
(block 25/11a), located offshore in central Norwegian North sea between
the Sleipner and Heimdal developments. The field has 1.39 billion
barrels of oil in place, of which about 828 million boe is recoverable.
Remaining reserves are estimated at 207 million boe (2015). Production
in 2014 averaged 87,000 b/d. Output from the field is transported
through the 29 inch diameter, 204 km Grane Oil Pipline to the Sture
Terminal on the Norwegian coast. In 2014, the nearby Svalin field went
on line and was tied into the Grane platform. Most of Grane is sold as
its own grade, however a small volume is blended into the Oseberg
Export blend. Joint venture partners are Statoil, the operator, with
36.66 percent interest, Norway State DFI with 28.94 percent, ExxonMobil
with 28.22 percent, and Conoco Phillips with 6.17 percent.

Name: Grane Exp Bld (XOM) '09
Comments:
2009 Sample; Total web assay.The field was discovered by Hydro in 1991,
and came on stream on 23 September 2003.  The platform is located
around 185 kilometres west of Haugesund, where sea depth is 127 metres.
The field was discovered by Hydro in 1991, and came on stream on 23
September 2003.  Grane is the first field on the Norwegian continental
shelf to produce heavy crude oil. This oil differs from other types in
that it is found in younger geological formations than what is usual on
the continental shelf, namely in sandstone from the Tertiary period,
deposited around 60 million years ago. The oil is transported by
pipeline to the Sture terminal, where it is stored in large rock
caverns in the mountainside prior to shipment to the world market. The
field receives natural gas from the Heimdal Gas Centre through a 50
kilometre long pipeline. The gas is injected as pressure support into
the reservoir, to ensure high production and extraction rates.

Name: Great Divide (Core) Feb '12
Comments:
The Great Divide project is an oil sands steam assisted gravity
drainage project located in the Athabasca oil sands region of
northeastern Alberta that is operated and owned by Connacher Oil and
Gas. The Great Divide area covers 140 square km that is split into two
development areas, Pod One and Pod Two which has been renamed Algar.
Pod One development began in 2006 and started commercial production in
2007. Algar development started in 2008 and production started up in
2010. Pod One and Algar have initial reserves of 90 million and 91
million recoverable barrels of bitumen, respectively. Remaining
reserves are 80 million and 88 million recoverable reserves,
respectively. In 2011, production at Pod One averaged 6,600 barrels of
bitumen and Algar averaged 6,600 barrels of bitumen. The Great Divide
is a heavy gravity (16.9 degrees API), high sulfur (4.1 wt percent),
viscous (1200 cSt at 20 degrees C) bitumen with a high total acid
number (3.2 mg KOH/g).
