Name: Hamaca Blend (CVX) '16
Comments:
Hamaca Blend is a synthetic crude oil produced by the Venezuela s
Orinoco Oil Tar Belt upgrader project which takes place at the Jose
refinery complex located on the northern coast of Venezuela. Extra
heavy crude from the Petropiar field is piped via a 55-km, 30-inch
pipeline to PDVSA's Patio de Tanques de Oficina then piped through a
175-km, 42-inch line to the Jose refinery complex. The crude then goes
through a process that upgrades extra heavy (6-8 degrees API), sour
crudes from the Orinoco Tar Belt to a lighter, synthetic crude of 25-26
degrees API and Sulfur content of 2 wt percent through a series of
processes that involve dilution with naphtha to facilitate transport to
the upgrading facility, diluent removal and re-cycling, hydrocracking,
high-temperature gasification processes, desulphurization, coking, and
blending. The Hamaca upgrader has the capacity to process 200,000 b/d
of extra heavy crude into 190,000 b/d synthetic crude (95 percent
conversion), 4,000 tons/day of coke, and 600 tons/day of Sulphur. The
Hamaca concession, which includes the Boyaca (Machete), Junin (Zuata),
Ayacucho (Hamaca), and Carabobo (Cerro Negro) fields, covers 160,000
acres, has a oil in place estimate of 235 billion boe, and holds 1.419
billion barrels of bitumen. Remaining reserves are 760 million barrels
of bitumen. Production began in 2002, but the upgrader project did not
begin until 2004. Average production of syncrude is 71,300 b/d and
heavy oil is 55,000 b/s (2016). Hamaca Blend is a viscous (1270 cSt at
20 degrees C), heavy gravity (17.1 degrees ), mid-level sulfur (2.27 wt
percent) crude with a high As concentration (64.6 ppb). It is expected
to produce a vacuum residuum with high Nitrogen (11,700 ppm), Ni
(1060 ppm), and MCRT (31.5 wt percent) concentrations. Petroleos
Venezuela, the operator, holds a 70 percent interest and Chevron holds
the remaining 30 percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   6.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.7  deg. C.

THE HAMACA UPGRADER IS EXPECTED TO BE OPERATIONAL EARLY 2004.

Name: Hamaca DCO (CVX) Oct 17 '13
Comments:
Hamaca DCO is typically produced whenever upgrader production issues
occur. It is a blended crude oil consisting of Hamaca Petropriar
(Ayacucho), an extra heavy crude oil (6-8 degrees API) produced in the
Venezuela s Orinoco Oil Tar Belt, and either Naphtha (47-50 degrees
API), Mesa (30 degrees API) or Santa Barbara (39 degrees API) to
produce a Diluted Crude Oil of 16-18 degrees API. The Hamaca
concession, which includes the Boyaca (Machete), Junin (Zuata),
Ayacucho (Hamaca), and Carabobo (Cerro Negro) fields, covers 160,000
acres, has a reserve estimate of 235 billion boe, and is expected to
produce approximately 2.1 billion barrels of extra heavy crude oil over
35 years. Petroleos Venezuela, the operator, holds a 70 percent
interest and Chevron holds the remaining 30 percent. Hamaca DCO cargo
properties can vary. This cargo is heavy (17.0 degrees API), high
sulfur (3.22 wt percent), and acidic (2.38 mg KOH/g).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  14.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   140.5  deg. C.

Comments:

THE NAPHTHA IS HIGH IN AROMATICS AND IS EXCELLENT REFORMER
  FEED. OCTANE DATA FOR MEDIUM NAPHTHA IS VERY UNUSUAL.
NOTE THAT ST-300 F THE HC DETAIL WAS ONLY PARTLY MEASURED.
THE JET IS UNSUITABLE: LOW IN SMOKE AND HIGH IN NAPHTHALENES:
RESID MAY BE A GOOD CANDIDATE FOR FCC FEED.
  310-375F/375-420/420-520F ARE 1.35/8.63/23.2 VOL%, RESPECTIVELY.
THE BLENDED BACK GRAVITY USING THE GULF C4- DATA IS 33.7 API.
HANDIL IS PRODUCED FROM ABOUT 150 RESERVOIRS. IT IS AN UNUSUAL
  CRUDE, AROMATIC IN THE TOP, PARAFFINIC IN THE MIDDLE AND
  NAPHTHENIC IN THE BOTTOM. COMPATIBILITY DATA FROM '77 SHOWED
  THAT THE 650+ F RESID HAS A #3 SPOT TEST, IS UNSTABLE AND IS
  NOT A GOOD SOLVENT FOR ASPHALTENES. THE 960+ F RESID HAS #1
  SPOT, IS STABLE AND HAS BETTER SOLVENT POWER.

Name: Harding Exp Bld (BP) '02
Comments:
This assay is in the Public Domain on BP's Website. Harding is a highly
Naphthenic, High Acidity, Medium Sulphur, Extra Heavy Crude Oil with
High Vanadium Content, and an extremely Low Pour Point. The sample
showed signs of Cracking at approx 585 C.  The  IBP was 91.5 C by ASTM
D2892 (Mod) The Crude Oil Sulphur balance from the distillation
products was 101% Recovery (0.595%Wt). The H2S Content Measured At 160
C Was < 2 Ppm Wt.  Kerosene (149-232) Sulphur And Freeze Point Fit
Specification For Jet A1, Bu t   Density Is At Upper Limit.  Gasoil /
Diesel (232-342) Cetane Index May Be Too Low And Sulphur And Density
Too High For Many Gas Oil Specifications  Vacuum Gas Oil (369-550)
Heavy, Sweet With Low Basic Nitrogen Content Indicates Good Fcc Feed.
The 369-5 09C Fraction Was Not Dewaxed As This Would Not Improve The
Pour Point (Due To The Extremely Low Wax Content).  The Vi Has Been
Calculated And The Data Included For Indication Only. The Data
Indicates Poor Lube Suitability.  Atmospheric Residue (>369) Med ium
Density, Low Sulphur, High Vanadium Content And Carbon Residue Content
Indicate Should Process In A Vacuum Disillation Stage To Separate Wax
Distillate As Fcc Feed.  High Sodium Content May Increase Coke
Formation I N Heaters/Reactors.  Vacuum Residue ( >509, >550,>585)
Medium Density, Medium Sulphur Indicates Suitability For Low Nickel
Grade Fuel Oil.  Potential Fcc Feed.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   1.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.8  deg. C.

Comments:
Hawkins Blend is a light (33.0 degrees ) gravity crude oil with a
sulfur concentration of 1.9 wt percent. It is produced from the

Hawkins, discovered in 1940, has initial recoverable reserves of 1.3
billion boe. The field has since produced over 800 million barrels of
oil. Production peaked at 115,000 b/d in 1975 and has steadily declined
to less than 7,000 b/d over the years. In 2010, ExxonMobil launched a
redevelopment project that will upgrade facilities and re-inject
nitrogen, carbon, dioxide and other inert gases to recover an
additional 40 million boe and boost production by 1,300 b/d. ExxonMobil
holds 78 percent interest. The remaining interest is held by several
owners.

Comments:

percent interest and Eni holds 5.18 percent interest.

Name: Hibernia (XOM) '11
Comments:
The Hibernia oil field is located in the in the Jean D'Arc Basin in the
North Atlantic Ocean, approximately 315 km east-southeast of St.
John's, Newfoundland, Canada. The field produces light, low sulfur
crude oil with an API of 33.9 deg and a sulfur content of 0.45 weight
percent. Hibernia, Newfoundland's first producing field, was discovered
in 1971 and went onstream on 1997. In 2010, recoverable reserves were
revised from 1.244 billion boe to 1.395 billion boe, which includes 220
million boe from the newly built South Extension which will extend the
project life from 2028 to 2033. First oil from the South Extension was
achieved in June 2011 and total output in July 2011 averaged 160,000
b/d. The Hibernia platform sits in shallow waters (about 79 m depths)
and is susceptible to iceberg damage. To protect from icebergs, the
platform has spiked projections called "teeth" that are designed to
withstand iceberg impacts and there is also a vessel on standby to push
icebergs away. To prevent the base of passing icebergs from damaging
equipment, subsea wellheads are dug into the seabed, called "glory
holes." ExxonMobil (33.125 percent) operates the field. Other owners
are Canada Hibernia Holding Corp. (8.5 percent), Chevron Corporation
(26.875 percent), Murphy Oil Co. Ltd. (6.5 percent), Statoil (5
percent), and Suncor Energy (20 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  19.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   140.9  deg. C.

Name: Hibernia Blend (XOM) '07
Comments:
Hibernia is an oil field in the North Atlantic Ocean, approximately 315
kilometres (196 mi) east-southeast of St. John's, Newfoundland, Canada.
Hibernia crude is produced in the Jean D'Arc Basin and loaded at the
IMTT-operated NTL Terminal in Newfoundland. The production rate of the
field is approximately 150 thousand b/d. Chevron has a 30% interest.
As the Hibernia field was located in an extremely inhospitable
environment consisting of rogue waves, fog, icebergs and sea ice,
hurricanes, and nor'easter winter storms, engineering analyses
determined that the most appropriate drilling platform would be in the
form of a gravity base structure.  Production commenced on November 17,
1997 and Hibernia has proven to be the most prolific oil well in
Canada, with initial production rates in excess of 50,000 barrels of
oil equivalent per day from a single well. A dedicated fleet of shuttle
tankers continuously operates between the platform and an onshore
transshipment facility at Whiffen Head.

Name: HSB/Husky SCO Blend (CVX) '09
Comments:
The Husky Lloydminster upgrader, located Lloydminster, Saskatchewan
(not Alberta), converts heavy oil to high-quality low sulfur synthetic
oil. The upgrader links Husky’s heavy oil assets to conventional
markets. The feedstock for the upgrader are deposits in northeastern
Alberta and western Saskatchewan, and the bitumen from Husky’s Tucker
Oil Sands Project located Northwest of Cold Lake, Alberta. Naturally
occurring salable products are recovered from the feed. The heavier
material is routed to primary upgrading via Hydrocracking which
converts residue to synthetic crude oil.   In addition to synthetic
crude, the upgrader produces sulfur (used in fertilizer and chemical
industries )and fuel grade petroleum coke. Heavy oil history meaning
it contains water, water soluble salt, clay, and sand. The diluent is
recovered for reuse.

Name: Hungo (XOM) Oct '16
Comments:
Hungo is a medium to light gravity (29.4 degrees API), low sulfur (0.59
wt percent) crude oil. The field, which includes both the Chocalho and
the Hungo fields, is in Block 15 Kizomba A located 120 kilometres
offshore Angola in the Lower Congo Basin. Recoverable reserves are
estimated at 787 million boe and remaining reserves is 113 million boe
(2017). Production averaged 60,000 b/d in 2016. Output from the field
is tied back to the Kizomba A FPSO which can process up to 270,000 b/d
and store 2.2 million boe. Partners include ExxonMobil (operator, 40
percent stake), Eni (20 percent), BP (26.67 percent) and Statoil (13.33
percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  16.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.5  deg. C.

Comments:

12.8 tcf gas and 527 million boe condensate. Icyths is expected start
production during 3Q' 2017 at an initial production rate of 3,000 b/d
condensate. Production s expected to peak at around 100,000 b/d by
2020. Output is tied back to an FPSO that can store 1.2 million barrels
of condensate. Inpex, the operator, holds 62.25 percent interest. Other
partners are Total (30 percent), CPC (2.63 percent), Tokyo Gas (1.58
percent), Kansai Electric (1.2 percent), Osaka Gas (1.2 percent), Chubu

Name: Iracema (INS) Apr '15
Comments:
Iracema, also known as Cernambi, is a large pre-salt oil field located
in Brazil's Santos Basin about 240 kilometers off the coast of Rio de
Janeiro state. It is a light (31.4 degrees API), low sulfur (0.275 wt.
percent) crude oil. Cernambi holds 1.456 billion barrels of recoverable
oil and is expected to reach a peak production rate of 292,910 b/d in
2017. Output is tied to the newly installed Cidade de Mangaratiba FPSO,
which can process 150,000 b/d. Output will also be tied back to the
FPSO Cidade de Itaguai which is expected to be completed by 2017.
Petrobras operates the field and holds 65 percent interest. Other
partners are GALP (10 percent) and BG Group (25 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  15.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.5  deg. C.

Name: Jansz Condensate Tank 1 (ITS) Oc
Comments:
Jansz Condensate, a component of Gorgon, is produced from the Jansz/Lo
field located approximately 30 miles NW of Gorgon off the NW coast of
Western Australia in the Carnarvon Basin. It is light gravity (51.4
degrees API) and low sulfur (0.01 wt percent). Janz holds 79 million
barrels of initial condensate reserves and 16,279 bcf gas. Janz gas
production started up in 2015 and it is expected to reach a peak
production rate of 8,000 barrels of condensate/day by 2023. Output from
the field is sent to the Barrow Island LNG Plant via a 180 km pipeline.
Chevron operates the Gorgon Area, which includes the Jansz/Lo fields,
and holds 47.33 percent interest. Other partners are ExxonMobil (25
percent), Shell (25 percent), Osaka Gas (1.25 percent), Tokyo Gas (1
percent) and Chubu Electric (0.42 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  53.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.3  deg. C.

B5/27 concession offshore Thailand on the northern edge of the Pattani
Basin. Initial recoverable reserves are 73 million boe and remaining
reserves are 14 million boe (2016). Production, which started in 2005,
averaged 11,500 b/d in 2016. Output from the fields is tied back to the
Jasmine Venture MV7 FPSO which can process 20,000 b/d and store 800,000
boe. Mubadala Development Co owns and operates the field.

Name: Jubarte Fld DSTP-57(Petrobs) '02
Comments:
DST sample of a single well.  Data from Petrobras. The Jubarte field
was discovered in January 2001, as a result of drilling of the
1-ESS-100 well in Block BC-60, at a water depth of 1,185 to 1,365
meters and at about 77 Km off the shore.  Block BC-60 is located in the
northern portion of the Campos Basin, off the southern coast of the
State of Espírito Santo. The FPSO P-57 will produce 180,000 barrels per
day of crude at a water depth of 1200 meters: the field is 45% owned
and operated by Petrobras. Oil reserves were estimated to be about 600
million barrels. The field is a pre-salt area where oil and gas
deposits are stuck under the layer of salt. The salt layer leads to
difficulty in tapping the potential reserves but technology has
overcome the primary difficulty. Phase one production started in late
2006 with the start of operations of FPSO JK (P-34), which had a
processing capacity of up to 60,000 barrels. Phase one covered four
producing wells. The Jubarte-4 horizontal well produces 15K b/d of h.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   2.9 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.5  deg. C.

Name: Jubarte P-57 (CVX) '11
Comments:
The Jubarte field is a pre-salt and post-salt deepwater oil field
located in the northern Campos Basin, offshore Brazil. Jubarte is a
heavy gravity (17.1 degrees API), high acid number (3.06 mg KOH/g), low
sulfur (0.535 weight percent), high viscosity, and high ARES yield
(less than 80 weight percent) crude oil. The field, which came online
in 2002, holds a total of 4 billion boe, of which 617 million boe in
the post salt reservoir and 157 million in the pre-salt reservoir is
recoverable. By year end 2011, about 502 million and 146 million boe,
respectively remain. Total production in 2010 averaged 55,000 b/d.
Output from the field is tied back to the P-57 FPSO which has a
processing capacity of 180,000 b/d. Future plans include the
installation of the P-58 FPSO in 2013, which is similar in design to
the P-57 FPSO and will focus on the pre-salt reserves and will include
production from the Cachalote and Baleia Franca fields. Petrobras owns
and operates the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   3.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.9  deg. C.

Name: Jubilee Exp Bld (Tullow) '11
Comments:
Jubilee, Ghana's first producing oil field, is an offshore giant oil
field located in the West Cape Three Points Block in the Tano Basin.
The field has recoverable reserves of 849 million boe and 800 bcf gas.
Commercial production began in December 2010 and averaged 66,000 b/d in
2011. Production will take place in three phases. Phases 1 started in
December 2010, involves development of 470 million barrels of reserves
in the Jubilee Unit Area and the installation of the Kwameh Nkrumah
MV21 FPSO which can process 120,000 b/d of crude and 160 million cubic
feet per day of gas and store 1.6 million barrels of crude oil. Peak
production for this phase is expected to reach 70,000 b/d. Phase 1a is
anticipated start up sometime in 2012 and Phase 1b, which will maintain
plateau production of 120,000 b/d, will start up in 2014, depending on
the success of phases 1 and 1a. Jubilee crude oil is light gravity
(36.4 degrees API) and low sulfur (0.2 wt percent). Tullow Oil (47.18
percent) is the operator. Partners are Anadarko and Kosmos Energy, with
17 percent interest each, Ghana National Petroleum Co with 15 percent
interest, and Sabre Oil and Gas with 3.83 percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  22.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.9  deg. C.

Name: Kamelia Condensate (ITS) Feb'14
Comments:
Kamelia Condensate, also known as Bunga Kamelia, is produced from the
first phase of development of an Early Production System (EPS) from the
Kamelia field in the Terengganu Area located offshore Malaysia in the
North Malay Basin. It is a light gravity (51.4 degrees API), low sulfur
(0.005 wt percent) condensate. Production started in Oct 2013 and
output averages 2,000 b/d of condensate (2015). Initial recoverable
reserves were estimated at 4 million barrels condensate and 150 bcf gas
of which, 3 million barrels condensate and 114 bcf gas remains. Output
is tied back to the Perisai Kamelia FPSO and utilizes nearby Lawit
facilities. Hess operates the field and holds 50 percent interest.
PETRONAS Carigali holds the remaining 50 percent interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  35.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.2  deg. C.

concentration (0.03 wt percent) condensate. It is produced from the
Kangan gas and condensate field which is located onshore in western
Iran. The fields hold 27.084 tcf initial gas reserves and 12.284 tcf
remaining reserves. Kangan condensate production averages 15,000 boe/d.
NIOC owns and operates the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  76.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   140.5  deg. C.

Name: Kapal Field EP5 (SGS) Jan '14
Comments:
The Kapal field is part of the Kapal, Banang and Meranti (KBM) Cluster,
located in the western central portion of the Malay Basin, off the east
coast of Peninsular Malaysia. Kapal, the first and only field that is
currently in production, achieved first oil on Dec 16, 2013 and is
producing 9,000 b/d (2014). Banang is expected to start up in July 2014
and Meranti will start up in 2019. The KBM cluster holds 24 million
barrels of recoverable oil. Output is tied back to the KBM FPSO which
can store up to 600,000 boe. Kapal is a light (41.5 degrees API), low
sulfur (0.03 wt percent) crude oil with a high pour point (75.2 degrees
F) and a mercury concentration of 29 ppb. Partners are Cepsa, the
operator, with 70 percent interest and Peta Energy with 30 percent
interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  13.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   141.7  deg. C.

Name: Karachaganak (ENI) '10
Comments:
KARACHAGANAK CRUDE OIL 45.7 API – SAMPLED ON July 27, 2010 and assay by
and from ENI. Karachaganak is a light, low sulphur, intermediate
paraffinic crude with low acidity and a high content in mercaptan
compounds present in the whole boiling range, that require sweetening
in distillation fractions to meet sulphur specification in products.
Naphtha yields are high (C5-180 C full naphtha fraction yield 37.23
%m/m), 80-180 C heavy naphtha (N+2A = 62.6 % v/v) is a good feedstock
to catalytic reforming for gasoline production. Middle distillates have
good yields, with good combustion properties (smoke point and cetane
index) and cold properties. Vacuum distillates have low metal and
nitrogen content and good “K factor” result in excellent feedstock for
catalytic cracker or hydrocracker. Vacuum residue has Low yield and low
metal content. Karachaganak Field is an onshore gas condensate field in
West Kazakhstan. It is located about 150 km east from the city of Oral
(Uralsk) in the northwest of Kazakhstan. Nickel below detection limit
Hydrogen Sulphide below detection limit Vanadium below detection limit
*** The GC Analysis Covers  31.9 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.7  deg. C.

Name: Karachaganak (ENI) '11
Comments:
Karachaganak Condensate is a sour condensate (45.3 deg API and 0.9 wt.
percent Sulfur) that is produced from the Karachaganak onshore oil and
gas condensate field located about 150 km east from the city of Oral
(Uralsk) in northwest Kazakhstan near the Russian border. Karachaganak,
Kazakhstan largest producing oil fields, is a large, complex, pre-salt
carbonate massif that covers an area of 280 square km and has a
reservoir thickness of 1,700 m. Estimated reserves are 1.4 Tcm of gas,
5.2 billion barrels of condensate and 1.4 billion barrels of crude oil.
The average production for 2010 was 220,000 b/d. 40 percent of the
produced sour gas is re-injected into the reservoir to improve liquids
recovery and the rest of the gas is piped to Russia's Orenburg plant or
used domestically. Most of the produced liquids are exported as part of
the CPC Blend. The re-maining liquids are sent to Orenburg and small
volumes are exported through the Russian Transneft system to Primorsk,
Russia. Karachaganak was discovered in 1979 and started up in 1985
under Karachaganckgazprom, a subsidiary of the Russian Gas Company
Gazprom. In 1998, the KPO Consortium was awarded the rights to operate
the field under a 40-year production license. Members of the consortium
are joint operators BG and Eni, who each have a 32.5 percent share.
Other members are Chevron (20 percent) and Lukoil (15 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  31.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.1  deg. C.

Name: Karachaganak Condensate (ENI)'09
Comments:
2009 sample Karachaganak Field is an onshore gas condensate field in
West Kazakhstan. It is located about 150 km east from the city of Oral
(Uralsk) in the northwest of Kazakhstan. The field was once a massive
Permian and Carboniferous reef complex covering an area 30 km by 15 km.
At its largest point the reservoir contains a gas column 1450 m deep
with a 200 m deep oil rim below it. It is estimated to contain 1.2
trillion cubic meters 42.4 trillion cubic feet (tcf) of gas and 1
billion tonnes of liquid condensate and oil. Discovered in 1979, it
began production under Karachaganckgazprom, a subsidiary of the Russian
Gas Company Gazprom. Kazakhgas took over operatorship after the
independence of Kazakhstan in 1992. in 1992 AGIP (now Eni) and the then
British Gas (now BG Group) were awarded the sole negotiating rights,
forming a partnership company. In 1997 Texaco (now Chevron Corporation)
and Lukoil signed a production sharing agreement with the original two
companies and the Kazakhstan Government. This is a 40-year agreement to
develop the field to allow the production to reach world markets. This
is done under a partnership company known as Karachaganak Petroleum
Operating (KPO) where BG Group and ENI are joint operators with a 32.5%
stake each in the company, with Chevron and Lukoil owning 20% and 15%
respectively. with a hydrogen sulphide content of 3.5-5% and carbon
dioxide content of 5%. Karachaganckgazprom maintained a policy of full
gas voidage replacement to maintain pressure of the reservoir above the
dew point. The Karachaganak Field is one of the world's largest gas
condensate fields. It is located in the Pre-Caspian (or North Caspian)
Basin, which extends from the southeastern margin of the Russian
Platform down to the northern coast of the Caspian Sea, and includes
the offshore Caspian Sea north of about 44 N The field consists of a
heterogeneous carbonate massif with strata from three geologic periods
and numerous stages of deposition during these periods. The following
have been identified: Permian: Kungurian, Artinskian, Sakmarian,
Asselian Carboniferous: Serpukhovian, Visean, Tournaisian Devonian:
Famennian H2S DISSOLVED below detection limit
*** The GC Analysis Covers  31.8 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.8  deg. C.

Name: Karachaganak Q2 '12 (ENI) '12
Comments:
Karachaganak Condensate is a sour condensate (45.3 deg API and 0.9 wt.
percent Sulfur) that is produced from the Karachaganak onshore oil and
gas condensate field located about 150 km east from the city of Oral
(Uralsk) in northwest Kazakhstan near the Russian border. Karachaganak,
Kazakhstan largest producing oil fields, is a large, complex, pre-salt
carbonate massif that covers an area of 280 square km and has a
reservoir thickness of 1,700 m. Estimated reserves are 1.4 Tcm of gas,
5.2 billion barrels of condensate and 1.4 billion barrels of crude oil.
The average production for 2010 was 220,000 b/d. 40 percent of the
produced sour gas is re-injected into the reservoir to improve liquids
recovery and the rest of the gas is piped to Russia's Orenburg plant or
used domestically. Most of the produced liquids are exported as part of
the CPC Blend. The re-maining liquids are sent to Orenburg and small
volumes are exported through the Russian Transneft system to Primorsk,
Russia. Karachaganak was discovered in 1979 and started up in 1985
under Karachaganckgazprom, a subsidiary of the Russian Gas Company
Gazprom. In 1998, the KPO Consortium was awarded the rights to operate
the field under a 40-year production license. Members of the consortium
are joint operators BG and Eni, who each have a 32.5 percent share.
Other members are Chevron (20 percent) and Lukoil (15 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  31.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.5  deg. C.

Name: Kearl Blend (CVX) '13
Comments:
Kearl is a diluted bitumen (dlibit) produced from the ExxonMobil (29.04
percent) and Imperial Oil Resources (70.96 percent) jointly owned Kearl
Oil Sands Project located in the Athabasca region of northeastern
Alberta, Canada about 70 km north of Fort McMurray. The Kearl Oil Sands
Project will be the world's largest open-pit mining operations for
producing bitumen. It has an API that ranged from 21-22 degrees , a
high sulfur content (3.5-4 wt percent), and is acidic (1.5-2 mg KOG/g).
It is also predicted to produce a vacuum residuum with high nickel and
vanadium content (500 ppm). Production is expected to start at the end
of 2012 with an initial bitumen production rate of 110,000 b/d and
diluted bitumen production of 160,000 b/d. The Kearl oil sands area has
a resource of 4.6 billion barrels recoverable bitumen and the project
duration is expected to reach 30 years. Imperial Oil Resources operates
the project.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  21.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   140.7  deg. C.

Comments:

concentration of 2.23 wt percent. It is produced from the Khurmala Dome
located in the northern part of the Kirkuk field in the autonomous
Kurdistan region of Iraq. The Khurmala Dome covers 160 km2 and holds
initial recoverable reserves of 2.726 billion barrels of light oil.

began in 2009, averages 105,000 b/d (2015) of which, about 70,000 b/d

Name: Kidurng/Patricaw(Its)'03
Comments:
ITS CALEB BRETT ASSAY. JANUARY 2003 ASSAY LOCATED OFFSHORE
SARAWAK IN 130 FT. OF WATER IN BLOCK SK309. WEST PATRICIA FIELD
WILL BE MARKETED AS KIDURONG & IS MURPHY OIL'S FIRST PRODUCTION IN
MALAYSIA. IT IS ALMOST RESID-LESS.
CRUDE IS LIGHT AND AROMATIC,
0.09 WT% SULFUR, 0.20 MG KOH/G ACID, 2.6 PSI /17.8 KPA RVP,
<-60C POUR, 135 PPM N, <1 PPM V, <1 PPM NI, 3 PPM FE, 150 PPB AS,
2 PPB HG, <1 PPM PB, 4 PPM K. (S blends to 0.04%)
MISSING DHA, VGO NITROGEN, HVGO VISCOSITIES; V RESID N,
POUR, VISCOSITY; ITS revised some originally reported data.
It is the opinion of this ERTC that the resid cracked and the
hvgo contained entrainment which is supported by the high
asphaltenes, metals, and mcr levels in the hvgo. Cuts are very
narrow and given the discontinuity of the first distillation and
the high temp(700f) of the first distillation, the second distillation
appeared pre-disposed to crack. The cuts are very narrow and the
reported temperatures are not necessarily the achieved cutpts reported.
Without simdis on the fractions, this is difficult to document but the
separation is a remarkable echo of the simdis data. ERTC/this author has
adjusted the data to be consistent with TBP (not simdis) data. ITS also
non-monotonic gravities for an aromatic crude-- probably a function of
cracking.  Also some strangeness in the aniline data.
PTI REPORTS API AT 37.0.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  34.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   154.3  deg. C.

Name: Kraken (ITS) '15
Comments:
The Kraken area, which is comprised of the Kraken and Kraken North
fields is located in the East Shetland Basin, 78 miles east of the
Shetland Islands in the UK Northern North Sea. Kraken is an acidic (5.4
mg KOH/g), viscous (4220 cSt at20 degrees C), heavy (13.4 degrees ),
low sulfur (0.68 wt percent) crude oil with high measured Ca (461 ppm)
and As (159 ppb) concentrations. It is expected to produce high VGO (54
vol percent) and ARES (71.9 vol percent) yields. Initial recoverable
reserves are 137 million boe. Kraken and Kraken North are expected to
startup in Jun 2017 and early 2018, respectively, at an initial rate of
20,000 b/d. Production is expected to peak at 49,000 b/d in 2019.
Output will be tied back to the Kraken FPSO which can process 80,000
b/d and store 600,000 boe. Enquest operates the field and holds 70.5
percent interest. Partner Cairn Energy holds the remaining 29.5 percent
interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers    .1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.0  deg. C.

Name: Kuito Exp Bld (CVX) Feb '12
Comments:
Kuito, located in Angola's deepwater Block 14, was discovered in 1997
and came on-steam in December 1999. The field produces medium gravity,
low sulfur crude oil (27.7 degrees API, 0.7 wt percent sulfur crude
oil) with a measured total acid number of 1.4 mg KOH/g and arsenic
content (165 ppb). Kuito is also expected to produce vacuum gas oil and
vacuum residuum with high nitrogen content (3020 ppm and 12800 ppm,
respectively). Initial recoverable reserves were estimated at 244
million boe. As of year-end 2011, 61 million boe remain. In 2011,
production fell to an average of 16,000 b/d from 25,000 b/d in 2009 due
to the recertification and upgrade of the Kuito FPSO. Production is
expected to rebound in 2012. Chevron operates the field and has 31
percent share. Joint venture partners include Eni, Sonangol, and Total,
each holding 20 percent share, and Galp Energia with 9 percent interest.

Name: Kupe Cond (ITS) Mar '11
Comments:
Kupe is an offshore oil and gas field in PML 38146 located off the west
coast of New Zealand's North Island in the Taranaki Basin. Initial
recoverable are estimated are 10 million barrels of LPG, 18 million
barrels of condensate and 281 bcf gas. Remaining reserves are 8 million
barrels LPG, 13 million barrels of condensate and 233 bcf sales gas
(2012). Production in 2012 averaged 4,900 b/d of condensate, 1,700 b/d
of LPG and 43.5 mmcfd gas. Output is transported from the Kupe platform
to an onshore production station via a 30 m pipeline. From there the
condensate and LPG is stripped out and the gas is piped through the
Maui Gas pipeline to the Kapuni Gas Treatment Plant. Origin Energy
operates the field and holds 50 percent interest. Other partners are
Genesis Energy (31 percent), NZOG (15 percent), and Mitsui and Co (4
percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  47.5 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   141.5  deg. C.

Name: Kutubu - OSL Export Blend (ITS)
Comments:
Kutubu blend is a light (49.1 degrees API, sweet (0.03 wt percent)
crude oil produced from three primary developments (Kutubu, Gobe, and
Moran fields) located in the Southern Highlands region of Papua New
Guinea. Initial recoverable reserve estimates for the Kutubu, Gobe, and
Moran fields are 372 million, 45.7 million, and 107.9 million,
respectively and remaining reserves (2014) are 37 million boe, 2.2
million boe and 28 million boe, respectively. In 2013, production
averaged 14,000 b/d at Kutubu, 1,500 b/d at Gobe and 11,300 b/d at
Moran. In June 2014, production from the PNG LNG was added to the
Kutubu blend. Output from the fields are transported via pipeline to
the Kumul Marine Terminal and marketed as Kutubu Blend. Oil Search
(PNG) Limited operates the Kutubu blend and holds 60.05 percent
interest. Other partners are Merlin Petroleum (18.68 percent),
ExxonMobil (14.52 percent), and Petroleum Resources (6.75 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  29.5 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.2  deg. C.

Name: Kutubu (ITS) '13
Comments:
Kutubu blend is a light, sweet crude (API of 44.9 degrees and 0.04 wt
percent sulfur) produced from three primary developments (Kutubu, Gobe,
and Moran fields) located in the Southern Highlands region of Papua New
Guinea. Initial recoverable reserve estimates for the Kutubu, Gobe, and
Moran fields are 372 million, 45.7 million, and 107.9 million,
respectively and remaining reserves (2014) are 37 million boe, 2.2
million boe and 28 million boe, respectively. In 2013, production
averaged 14,000 b/d at Kutubu, 1,500 b/d at Gobe and 11,300 b/d at
Moran. Output from the fields are trasported via pipeline to the Kumul
Marine Terminal and marketed as Kutubu Blend. Oil Search (PNG) Limited
is the largest partner and also operates the Kotubu field, as well as
parts of the Moran and Gobe fields. Exxon Mobil operates parts of Moran
 and Santos operates parts of Gobe. Other Joint Venture partners
include  Exxon, Nippon Oil, Eda Oil, MRDC, Southern Highlands
Petroleum, Santos  and Cue Energy.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  38.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.0  deg. C.

Name: Kutubu (ITS) Aug 28 '15
Comments:
Kutubu blend is a light gravity (50.4 degrees API), low sulfur (0.03 wt
percent sulfur) crude oil that is produced primarily from the Kutubu,
Gobe, South East (SE) Gobe, Moran, and SE Mananda fields all located in
the Southern Highlands region of Papua New Guinea. Initial recoverable
reserve estimates for the Kutubu, Gobe, SE Gobe, Moran, and SE Mananda
are 372 million boe, 30.8 million boe, 45.7 million boe, 107.9 million,
and 2.9 million boe, respectively. Remaining reserves (2015) are 31
million boe, 1.6 million boe, 2.2 million boe, 28 million boe, and 0.1
million boe respectively. In 2014, production averaged 15,200 b/d at
Kutubu, 900 b/d at Gobe, 1,200 b/d at SE Gobe, 10,000 b/d at Moran and
30 b/d at SE Mananda. Output from the fields are transported via
pipeline to the Kumul Marine Terminal and marketed as Kutubu Blend. Oil
Search (PNG) Limited operates the Kutubu blend and holds 60.05 percent
interest. Other partners are Merlin Petroleum (18.68 percent),
ExxonMobil (14.52 percent), and Petroleum Resources (6.75 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  46.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.4  deg. C.

27.9 Wt% n-Paraffins/Wax(GC), 28.5 Wt% Wax on crude, 0.57 Wt% MCRT, 338
ppm KF Water, no detectable Mercaptan sulfur/RSH or H2S, Compatibility
Parameters of <92 Vol% CT, 0.33 Po, <0.03 ra. 62 C Wax Appearance Test
(WAT). Kutubu Light is produced in the Southern Highlands of Papua New
Guinea. Production is sourced from three developments: Kutubu, Gobe and
Moran.  The oil produced from each field is very similar in quality and
is excellent for the production of transportation fuels especially
motor gasoline. Field production is transported by pipeline to the
Kumul marine terminal for export. MERCAPTAN below detection limit H2S
DISSOLVED below detection limit MERCURY <15.00 CETANE TOLERANCE >92
SOLVENT REQUIREMENT <0.03, FLASH POINT <3
*** The GC Analysis Covers  32.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.3  deg. C.

Name: Kutubu Exp Bld (ITS) '10
Comments:
Kutubu blend is light, sweet crude (API of 44.8 deg and 0.03 weight
percent sulfur). It is suitable for the production of middle
distillates and motor gas and the atmospheric resid is suitable as a
feedstock for catalytic crackers. Kutubu is produced from three primary
developments (Kutubu, Gobe, and Moran fields) located in the Southern
Highlands region of Papua New Guinea. Initial recoverable reserves
estimates for the Kutubu, Gobe, and Moran fields are 357 million, 75
million, and 110 million, respectively. Cumulative production since
initial start up in 1992 to year end of 2009 was 447 million boe
(approximately 95 million boe remaining). Last year, production
contributions were about 50 percent Kutubu, 15 percent Gobe and 35
percent Moran and the average production rate for May 2010 was 40,000
b/d. The Kutubu blend s fields are in natural decline, with Moran and
Gobe dropping sharply. Despite the natural decline, production for the
Kutubu fields rose in 2009 because of eight new development wells. Oil
Search (PNG) Limited is the largest partner and also operates the

Guinea. Initial recoverable reserve estimates for the Kutubu, Gobe, and

the Kumul Marine Terminal and marketed as Kutubu Blend. Oil Search
(PNG) Limited operates the Kutubu blend and holds 60.05 percent

Name: Kuwait (CVX) '13
Comments:
Kuwait Export Blend is a composite of almost all of Kuwait's output.
The Greater Burgan field, which also includes the Burgan, Magwa and
Ahmadi structures, is largest contributor to the blend. Other
contributors are the Raudhatain, Sabriya, Abdali, Ratqa and Bahra
fields which are located in Northern Kuwait and Minagish and Umm Qudayr
which are located in the southwest region of the country. The Greater
Burgan field is a super-giant field with initial reserves of 44.5
billion boe, 956 million barrels of condensate, and 8.707 tcf gas.
Remaining reserves are 14.5 billion boe, 542 million barrels of
condensate, 127 million barrels of condensate and 5.212 tcf gas. The
fields in Northern Kuwait have initial reserves of 14.062 billion boe,
573 million bbl LPG, 692 million bbl Condensate, and 8.077 tcf Sales
Gas. Remaining reserves (2013) are 8. 471 billion bbl Oil, 371 million
bbl LPG, 618 million bbl Condensate, 6.078 tcf Sales Gas. Initial
reserves for Minagish was 2.774 billion barrels of oil, 29 million
barrels of condensate, 133 million barrels of LPG, and 772 bcf gas, of
which 1.559 billion boe, 10 million bbl condensate, 29 million bbl LPG
and 400 bcf gas remains. Umm Qudayr initial reserves were 2.611 billion
barrels of oil, 17 million barrels of condensate, 76 million barrels of
LPG, and 349 bcf gas, of which 1.491 billion boe, 6 million bbl
condensate, 16 million bbl LPG and 182 bcf gas remains. Kuwait's total
blend capacity is 3 million b/d. In 2011, production reached 2.8
million barrels. Kuwait Export Blend quality displays seasonal
variation. The API ranges from 31 degrees in the winter months to 29.5
degrees API in the summer. Kuwait Oil Co., the upstream arm of KPC,
owns and operates the fields. Kuwait export blend is light (30.1
degrees API) and high in sulfur (2.68 wt percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  17.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.6  deg. C.

Name: Kuwait Exp Bld (CVX) '08
Comments:
Oil-bearing geologic structure of Kuwait’s oil wells tap both shallow
low-pressure reservoirs and much deeper high-pressure reservoirs.
The shallow wells, which account for most of Kuwait’s wells (about 800),
make up approximately 50% of Kuwait’s national production, or about 1
million barrels per day. These shallow wells tap reservoirs at depths
ranging from 400 to 7,000 feet with formation pressures up to about
7,000psi.
 Kuwait’s 150 deep high-pressure wells collectively produce
about 1 million barrels of crude per day. Individually, they produce
between 7,000 and 10,000 barrels per day and tap the Marrat structure
at a depth of 12,000 to 14,000 feet. The Marrat structure runs
north-south and parallels the Kuwaiti coast. This structure has an
average formation pressure of 15,000 psi and yields crude oil with a
high hydrogen sulfide gas (H2S) content of 2 to 5% by weight (crude
oil containing high concentrations of H2S is commonly referred to as
"sour crude"
(5) 2 gallon cans of Kuwait Export Crude. Samples were
shipped via Air France AWB 057-1538-3012 by Al Manea Land Transport
Co. Kuwait City for Intertek.  Very little information on containers

Name: Lalang Exp Bld (CVX) Sep '11
Comments:
The Lalang onshore field is one of the oldest fields in the Malacca
Strait Production Sharing Contract area located in Central Sumatra.
Lalang was discovered in 1980 and began producing in 1984. The field
had initial recoverable reserves of 57.2 million boe, of which 2.9
million remain. In 2011, the production rate was 1,500 b/d. Lalang
crude oil is transported through two 8-inch diameter, 60,000 b/d
capacity pipelines from the LP platform to the Single Point Offshore
Loading System (SPOLS) located about 17 km to the north. From there it
is stored in the Ladinda storage tanker then offloaded to an ocean
going tanker for export. Lalang is a light (34.7 degrees API), low
sulfur crude oil (0.07 weight percent) with a high crude pour point
(89.5 degrees F) and high measured mercury content (50 ppb). Energi
Mega Persada, the operator, holds 34.46 percent, CNOOC Ltd holds 39.51
percent, and Imbang Tata Alam holds 26.03 percent).

Name: Laricina Bitumen P1c (CORE) Jan
Comments:
Larcina Bitumen and Diluted Bitumen are produced from Larcina's Saleski
project which uses SAGD to extract bitumen. Saleski is located in
Alberta s Grosmont Formation, Alberta s second-largest in situ oil
sands resource, and covers a total area of 17,152 gross hectares.
Production started up in March 2011. Bitumen production capacity is
currently at 10,700 b/d however production averages about 1,200 b/d
(2012). Diluent for the dilbit is also produced at the site using
recovered diluent produced during the solvent recovery step from.
Laricina operates the field and holds a 60 percent interest. Osum Oil
Sands Corp. holds the remaining 40 percent interest. Laricina bitumen
has an API of 6.5 - 6.9 degrees and a sulfur content of 3-4 wt percent.
It is highly acidic (4.4 mg KOH/g), viscous (1,710,000-2,930,000 cst at
20 degrees C) and has a high pour point (greater than 80 degrees F).
The naphtha and jet cuts are expected have high levels of mercaptans
(greater than 300 ppm) and the vacuum residuum (VRES) is predicted to
have high Ni content (greater than 500 ppm). The atmospheric and
vacuum residuum yields are also expected to be high (greater than 40
vol percent and greater than 80 vol percent, respectively).

Name: Lavan (Total) '11
Comments:
Lavan is a blend of crudes produced from Iranian offshore fields
Salman, Reshadat, Resalat, and Balal. Output from the fields are piped
and blended at the Lavan Island terminal for which the blend is named.
Lavan started production in 1993 and is producing about 120,000 b/d
(2011). Salman, the largest contributor to the blend (70,000 b/d in
2011), had initial recoverable reserves of 2 billion boe, of which 460
million remain. Resalat and Reshadat, with 211 million and 427 million
boe initial reserves, respectively, and 31 million and 273 million boe
remaining reserves, respectively, were severely damaged during the
Iran-Iraq war and has only contributed about 17,000 b/d (2011). The
remaining volume is from the Balal oil field, which has initial
reserves of 118 million boe and remaining reserves of 41 million boe.
Lavan is light gravity (36.2 deg API), sour (1.5 wt percent sulfur)
crude oil with high mercaptans in the naphtha (692 ppm) and jet (343
ppm) cuts. Iranian Offshore Oil Company operates all of the
contributing fields. Salman is owned by PetroIran Development Company
(55 percent) National Iranian Oil Company (45 percent). Reshadat,
Resalat, and Balal are owned by National Iranian Oil Company.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  22.5 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   139.7  deg. C.

export terminal at Lavan Island, where the crude is piped for blending
and export. The blend is relatively light but sour (ie rich in
mercaptan type sulfur) as well as high in total sulfur, similar in
quality to Iran Light. It is a high sulfur crude and has middle
distillate with good Cetane Index. The crude is good feedstock for
asphalt production. Salman which has estimated recoverable reserves of
430 million barrels in three producing reservoirs  Lower Arab, Buwaib
and upper Arab. Salman, the largest contributor to the blend, is
located on the median line with Abu Dhabi, where Abu Al Bukhoosh field
is its extension. Production at Salman began in 1968. The field

Name: Long Lake Syn PSC (MAX) Dec '10
Comments:
Long Lake Premium Synthetic Crude (PSC) is produced from the Nexen
operated Long Lake bitumen recovery and upgrading project located
Alberta, Canada. SAGD is used for bitumen extraction and proprietary
OrCrude technology along with hydrocracking and gasification is used to
upgrade the bitumen to synthetic crude oil. Production of Phase One,
known as Long lake Phase 1, began in 2008 and is currently producing
72,000 b/d of bitumen and after upgrading, produces about 58,500 b/d of
synthetic crude. Phase two, also known as Kinosis is expected to start
drilling by 2014 with production expected to start by 2015. Production
from Long Lake is transported through the Cheecham Terminal pipelines
to Hardisty where it is then shipped to North American markets where it
is used as diluent. The Long Lake area has initial recoverable bitumen
reserves of 1.375 billion barrel and remaining reserves of 1.349
billion barrels. Long Lake PSC is light gravity and low in sulfur (39
degrees API, 0.0003 wt percent sulfur). Nexen holds 65 percent interest
and CNOOC holds 35 percent interest, however CNOOC has just received
approval to acquire Nexen, Inc and once finalized will own 100 percent
of Long Lake.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  18.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   138.8  deg. C.

Name: Loreto  (CVX) Dec 27 '13
Comments:
Loreto Crude Oil is a viscous (1100 cSt at 20 degrees C) heavy gravity
(17.9 degrees API) crude oil with a sulfur content of 1.28 wt percent
and high measured lead (147 ppb) content. It is expected to produce a
vacuum residuum with a high MCRT (39 wt percent) concentration. Loreto
produced in Peru's northernmost region on Block 1- AB in the Maranon
Basin. Initial recoverable reserves are estimated at 764 million
barrels, of which 71 million boe remain. Block 1-AB came on stream in
1975 and in 2013 produced 14,600 b/d. Output from the field is
gathered, processed and stored at the Andoas Gathering Station. It is
then transported to the Bayovar export terminal through the Petroperu
owned Ramal Norte (North Branch) and Oleoducto Nor-Peruano (North Peru
Pipeline) pipeline system where it is marketed as Loreto Crude Oil.
Participants in Block 1-AB are the operator Pluspetrol Norte (55
percent), CNPC (22.5 percent) and PetroChina (22.5 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers   8.5 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.9  deg. C.

Comments:
The Lower Zakum field is the ADMA operated portion of the large Zakum
field located offshore Abu Dhabi midway between Das Island and Abu
Dhabi. The field was discovered in 1963 and came onstream in 1967. Oil
in place at Zakum Lower is estimated at 16 billion boe, of which 4.211
billion boe are recoverable and about 737 million boe (2012) remains.
In 2011, production averaged 300,000 b/d. The field is split into two
zones, Zakum West and Zakum Central, each of which have supercomplexes
where the crudes are processed. Zakum West and Zakum Central are linked
by a 175,000 b/d capacity, 10 km, 24-inch pipeline. The crude is then
transported via a 310,000 b/d capacity pipeline to ADMA's processing
and export terminal on Das Island. Lower Zakum is a light gravity ( 40
degrees API), low sulfur crude oil ( 1 wt percent). It is owned and
operated by the Abu Dhabi Marine Operating Company partners which
include Abu Dhabi National Oil Company (60 percent), BP (14.67
percent), Jodco (12 percent) and Total SA (13.33 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  24.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   138.3  deg. C.

Comments:

western canadian sedimentary basin.  The volumetrically largest light

predominantly southeastern Saskatchewan production (SES) and other

Kerrobert.  This sample is from Cromer.  Crude runs about 35ish*API
with 1.3ish %S but this sample ) cpnsistent with refinery receipts) is
running lighter.

Name: Lucina Blend (ITS) '09
Comments:
Lucina Blend is composed from the output of the Lucina, M'Bya and
M'Wengui fields, which are all located offshore in the South Gabon
sub-basin. Lucinda Blend came on stream in 1974, with production first
coming from the Lucina field. M'Bya started up in 1980 and M`Wengui was
blended to the M'Bya stream in 1997. All three fields have iniital
recoverable reserves of 177 million boe. About 23 million boe (2012)
remain. Production in 2011 averaged 6,000 b/d. Output from the three
fields is pipelined to the Banio storage and offloading facility then
sold as the Lucina blend. The crude is waxy (Pour Point 60.3 degrees
C), light gravity (33.5 degrees API), and has a low sulfur content
(0.07 wt percent). Parenco holds 90 percent interest and operates the
field. The Government of Gabon owns the remaining 10 percent interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  12.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.1  deg. C.

Name: Lula Crude Whole Crude only (SHE
Comments:
Lula, formerly known as Tupi, is a pre-salt oil and gas field located
in the in the Santos Basin offshore Brazil, about 250 km from the
southern coast of Rio de Janeiro. Lula crude oil is a light gravity
(29.5 degrees API), low sulfur (0.325 wt percent) crude oil. The field
lies directly under 2000 m thick salt layer at a depth of 5000-5200 m
below sea level. Production started in 2011 and output averaged
690,7000 b/d in February 2017. Production is expected to reach over 1
million b/d once the field is completely developed. With over 6.433
billion barrels of oil and 3.261 tcf gas recoverable reserves, Lula is
the largest oil discovery in the Americas in more than 30 years. At
year-end 2014, about 6.282 billion boe recoverable reserves remain.
Petrobras operates the field and holds 65 percent interest. Other
partners are BG with 25 percent interest and Galp Energia with 10
percent interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  14.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.3  deg. C.

Name: Lula TUPI P1 (INSP) Oct '11
Comments:
Tupi, now known as Lula, is a pre-salt oil and gas field located in the
in the Santos Basin offshore Brazil, about 250 km from the southern
coast of Rio de Janeiro. Tupi/Lula crude oil is a medium gravity, sweet
crude oil with an API of 29.3 degrees and a sulfur content of 0.34
weight percent. The field lies directly under a 2000 m thick salt layer
at a depth of 5000-5200 m below sea level. First oil was achieved in
May 2009 and the production rate reached a peak of 36,300 b/d in May
2011. Phase 1A of the full field start up is expected to begin on March
2015 and Phase 1B is anticipated to begin on 2019 and complete by 2021.
Production is expected to reach over 1 million b/d once the field is
completely developed. With over 6.914 billion barrels of oil and 4.1
tcf gas recoverable reserves, Lula is the largest oil discovery in the
Americas in more than 30 years. At year end 2011, about 6.892 billion
boe recoverable reserves remain. Petrobras operates the field and holds
65 percent interest. Other partners are BG with 25 percent interest and
Galp Energia with 10 percent interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  14.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.6  deg. C.

Name: M100 ex Kavkaz (ITS) Apr29 '15
Comments:
In the Former Soviet Union, M-100 is the nomenclature for the most
common brand of Fuel Oil. It is often bought by refiners as incremental
raw material and contains a significant portion of lighter components.
M-100 may be sourced from any crude in the region. For example, M-100
resid loaded from the Black Sea is from Siberian Light and M-100 resid
loaded from the Baltic Sea is derived from Urals. M-100 must meet
certain fuel oil specifications, therefor assumption about properties
(and corrosion properties, in particular) or refinability is not
necessarily transferable between cargoes unless from same base source
and refiner.

Name: Maari Fld Well#2 MTD (3rd) '03
Comments:
The Maari field, operated by OMV New Zealand, is situated in theTasman
Sea off the west coast of Taranaki, New Zealand. Field start up
production is expected to be 7,000 bbl/d rising to approximately 35,000
bbl/d with recoverable reserves estimated to be about 50 million
barrels of oil. Production started July 2008 and field lifetime is
expected to be 10+ years. Maari is high pour, waxy crude oil. OMTrading
Services will market Maari crude oil on behalf of OMV New Zealand and
Horizon Oil. Maari is a medium heavy crude oil with an API gravity of
34.6*API, sulfur of 0.09 wt%, wax content of 32 wt%. and pour point of
+ 27*C. It is a crude oil with a good yield of straight-run naphtha and
atmospheric gasoil distillation.  This assay was performed by Amdel
Petroleum services. products.  Situated in 100 meters of water, Maari
lies about 50 miles off the North Island, some 50 miles off the South
Taranaki coast, and about 25 miles south of the Maui field - offshore
New Zealand.  FSPO is called Rarona.  Life of Maari is expected to be

Name: MacKay Dilbit (Core) Dec '12
Comments:
The Southern Pacific McKay project is located about 45 km northwest of
Ft McMurray in Alberta, Canada. Phase 1, which started in July 2012,
extracts bitumen using the SAGD technique and is expected to reach a
production rate of 12,000 b/d bitumen by the end of 2013. Phase 1
expansion and Phase 2, which are expected to add an additional 6,000
b/d and 18,000 b/d bitumen, respectively, are still in the application
phase. Dilutoed Bitumen (Dilbit) is transported to terminals in
Natchez, MS by rail. Southern Pacific owns and operates the McKay
project. McKay Dilbit is medium gravity (22.1 degrees API), high sulfur
(3.72 wt percent) and acidic (2.54 mg KOH/g). It is also expected to
produce vacuum residuum with a high MCRT content (30.6 wt percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  21.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   144.8  deg. C.

Name: MacKay River Dilbit (Suncor) '12
Comments:
MacKay Heavy Blend (MKH) is a bitumen diluted with synthetic crude oil
(SynBit) produced from Suncor Energy Canada's MacKay River oil sands
facility located 37 miles NW of Fort McMurray in Alberta, Canada.
Mackay River holds initial recoverable reserves of 442 million barrels
of bitumen and remaining reserves are 346 million barrels of bitumen
(2015). It is medium gravity (20.9 degrees API), mid-level sulfur (2.53
wt percent), acidic (1.65 mg KOH/g) synbit that is expected to produce
a vacuum residuum with a high Ni concentration (1460 wt ppm).
Production started in 2002 and in 2014, the Mackay River
debottlenecking project was completed increasing the production
capacity from 30,000 b/d to 38,000 b/d. Suncor Energy is the sole owner
and operator.

barrels. Periodically, a shuttle tanker will carry the crude oil and
export it to certain locations. Other nearby production such as KE7-3
and others commingle into this segregation. Kodeco has a 50% stake in
licensed areas located in Poleng Field near the island of Madura.

Name: Manora (ITS) '15
Comments:
The Manora offshore oil field covers blocks G1/48 and G3/48 in the Gulf
of Thailand. Together the blocks hold 21 million barrels of recoverable
oil of which, 15 million barrels remain (2016). First oil was achieved
in 2014 and production averages 12,200 b/d (2016). Output is tied back
to an FSO that can store up to 650,000 boe. Manora is a waxy, light
gravity (27.8 degrees API), low sulfur (0.16 wt percent) crude oilwith
a high pour point (102.3 degrees F), high arsenic (544 ppm), and is
expected to produce high atmospheric yields (71.2 vol percent). The
field is owned by Mubadala Development (operator, 60 percent) and
Northern Gulf Petroleum (40 percent). TAP petroleum owns 75 percent
interest of Northern Gulf Petroleum which results in the company owning
30 percent of the Mubadala Development.

crude oil (20 degrees API, 0.7 wt percent sulfur, viscosity greater
than 300 cSt at 20 degrees C) that is expected to produce vacuum gas
oil and vacuum residuum that is high in nitrogen. The entire Marlim
area consists of three main fields that includes Marlim, Marlim Leste
(East) and Marlim Sul (South). The Marlim Area is located in the
central Campos Basin, offshore Rio de Janiero, Brazil. It was
discovered in 1985 and began production in 1991. Initial reserves were
2.736 billion boe, of which 574 million boe remain (2011). Production
in 2011 averaged 225,000 b/d. State owned Petrobras owns and operates
the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   6.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.5  deg. C.

Name: Masila Exp Bld (CVX) '07
Comments:
Yemen is a small, non-OPEC oil producer. According to Oil and Gas
Journal (OGJ), the country had proven crude oil reserves of 3 billion
barrels in 2007, down from 4 billion in 2006. The oil is concentrated
in five areas: Marib-Jawf - Block 18 (estimated 800 million barrels)
in the north; Masila - Block 14 (estimated 800+ million barrels) in
the south; East Shabwa - Block 10A (estimated 180 million barrels);
Jannah - Block 5 (estimated 345 million barrels) and Iyad - Block 4
(estimated 135 million barrels) in central Yemen.

Name: Maya  (CVX) Oct 30 '13
Comments:
Maya crude oil is produced from several offshore fields in the Bay of
Campeche and a few heavier onshore fields along the southern coast of
Mexico. Production at the Ku-Maloob-Zaap stream, located 90 km offshore
in the Bay of Campeche, averaged 895,000 b/d (2013), making it the
largest contributor to Maya grade. The next major contributing stream
is the Cantarell field, located 80 kilometers offshore in the Bay of
Campeche, southern Mexico. In 2010, Cantarall produced 467,800 b/d
(2013). Most, but not all, of the output from the Cantarell and
Ku-Maloob-Zaap stream is blended and exported as Maya Crude oil.
Ku-Maloob-Zaap and Cantarell have initial recoverable reserves of 6.98
billion and 11.756 billion barrels of heavy oil, respectively.
Remaining reserves (2013) are 3.897 billion and 2.07 billion barrels of
heavy oil (2011), respectively. In 2010, Maya production averaged 1.517
million b/d, of which 1.07 million b/d was exported. Maya is a heavy
gravity (20.7 degrees API), high sulfur (3.7 wt percent) crude oil with
a high measured arsenic content (144 ppb). It is expected to produce
sour naphtha and jet (653 ppm RSH and 525 ppm RSH, respectively) and a
vacuum residuum with high nickel and vanadium (Ni  Vequal to 971 ppm)
concentrations and high MCRT (31.8 wt percent) content. Pemex is the
sole owner and operator.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  11.9 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.2  deg. C.

Name: Mayna Exp Bld (CVX) Mar '12
Comments:
Mayna is produced from Peru's onshore Block 8 in Peru's Mara on Basin
located in northern Peru and consists of seven fields, Corrientes,
Capirona, Pavayacu, Yanayacu, Valencia, Nueva Esperanza and Chambira.
Production, which started up in 1974, average 10,000 b/d in 2011. Block
8 had initial recoverable reserves of 323 million boe, of which 22
million boe remain. Most of the crude from Block 8 is transported
through the Petroperu owned pipeline system, Oleoducto Nor-Peruano
(North Peru Pipeline), to the export terminal of Bayovar on the Pacific
coast where it is marketed as Mayna blend. The remaining crude is
barged to the Iquitos refinery. Mayna is medium gravity, low sulfur
crude oil with an API of 21.1 degrees and sulfur content of 0.7 wt
percent. The crude is also expected to produce a high atmospheric
residuum yield (74 vol percent). Mayna is operated by Pluspetrol Norte,
a joint venture where Pluspetrol holds 55 percent and China National
Petroleum Corporation holds 45 percent interest. Owners of the field
are Pluspetrol (33 percent), KNOC (20 percent), CNPC (13.5 percent),
PetroChina (13.5 percent), Daewoo International (11.67 percent), and SK
Energy (8.33 percent).

Name: Medanito (CVX) Dec 22 '16
Comments:
Medanito, a major component of the Rincon grade, is also known as
Neuquen Rio Negro crude. The crude is produced from several fields
located in La Pampa, Mendoza, Rio Negro and Neuquen. Medanito is a
mature, declining field therefor production is expected to steadily
decline. Output from the field is sent to the Allen terminal and then
pipelined through the Oldelval (Oleoductos del Valle) pipeline to Bahia
Blanca where it is marketed. Medanito crude oil is a light gravity
(36.7 degrees API), low sulfur (0.4 wt percent) crude oil with a high
measured As concentration (86.8 ppb). The fields that contribute to
Medanito are owned and operated by many companies including Chevron,
Petroqu mica Comodoro Rivadavia (PCR), and Petrobras Argentina.

Name: Medanito Exp Bld (CVX) '09
Comments:
2009 sample, Medanito aka Rio Negro) is  arelatively sweet and light
gravity crude oil with a good kerosene freeze point and good gas oil
Cetane index. It is produced from fields in the provinces of La Pampa,
Mendoza, Rio Negro, and Nequen.  The crude is split in to two nearly
identical streams whose names are determined by their destinations:
when directed towards the east, the Atlantic, the stream is called
Medanito, and when directed west toward the Pacific, it is called
Rincon. Medanito is Argentina’s primary crude oil steam and is mostly
refined domestically. It is pumped via pipelines operated by oleoductos
del Valle to the port of Rosales, situated close to the city of Bahia
Blanca in the province of Buenos Aries. Medanito is produced and sold
by Repsol YPF, which contributes the majority of volumes, Chevron and
local independents Pluspetrol and Pecom. Load port: Puerto Rosales.

Name: Melitah Exp Bld (CVX)'09
Comments:
Mellitah Export Blend is a light gravity (38.6 degree API), low sulfur
crude oil (0.14 weight percent) that is composed of the output of the
El-Feel (Elephant) oil field located on Block NC-174 in Libya's SW
desert and the Wafa gas and condensate field located on Block NC-169 in
western Libya. In 2009, output averaged just under 150,000 b/d with
Elephant contributing 110,000 b/d and Wafa contributing 37,290 b/d.
Both Elephant and Wafa came on stream on 2004, however Melitah was not
marketed until 2005 when the Elephant field was connected through a 727
km pipeline to the Mellitah terminal. Wafa output, once sold as a
separate grade, is sent to a storage facility, then transported to the
Mellitah Terminal through a 530 km pipeline where it is treated then
blended with Elephant. Recoverable reserves at Elephant are 660 million
boe and at Wafa are 250 million boe, 241 million bbl condensate, and
5.396 tcf of gas. Remaining reserves (2011) at Elephant are 417 million
boe and at Wafa are 172 million boe, 181 million bbl condensate, and
4.352 tcf of gas. Both fields and the terminal facility are operated
and owned by Mellitah Oil and Gas Company, a company owned by by
Libya's National Oil Corp. (50 percent), Eni (33.3 percent), Hyundai
(4.17 percent), KNOC (4.17 percent), SK Energy (4.17 percent), Majuko
Enterprise (2.50 percent), and Daesung (1.67 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  21.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.2  deg. C.

Comments:

offshore NC41 field together with the gas reserves of the
adjacent El Bouri field.  starting from Wafaa, pipelines link up with
the NC41/El Bouri fields. NC41 field, in the north-western part of
Libya's waters operated by Agip under a PSA, has >8 TCF of recoverable
gas. Wafaa field, an onshore structure in Ghadames Basin's Block
NC-169 near the Algerian border, has reserves est'd at >5TCF.
data blend back to over 60*API.

Name: Mesa 30 (PDVSA) April '05
Comments:
The Mesa-30 grade crude, also known as Furrial, is a medium to light
gravity (29.5 degrees API) crude oil with a sulfur content of 1 wt
percent. It is produced from the El Furrial field, located onshore
Venezuela in the Orinoco Belt. Furrial, a mature and declining field,
was discovered in February 1986 and started production in September
1986. In 2011, production averaged 183,000 b/d. El Furrial had initial
recoverable reserves of 3.053 billion boe and remaining reserves are at
625 million boe (2012). Future plans include blending production from
the first phase of Junin-5 Block which is expected to start up in late
2013/early 2014 for a duration of four to seven years. PDVSA owns and
operates the field.

Name: Morichal 16 Cerro Negro (CVX) Ma
Comments:
Morichal is the primary reservoir of the Cerro Negro-Petromonagas block
which consists of 16 producing zones, all located in the Easten
Venzuela's Orinoco Heavy Oil Belt. Morichal is made up of the six
deepest producing zones and resides at a depth between 640 and 915 m.
The field produces an extra heavy, sour crude (8.5 degrees API) that is
upgraded to produce a lighter SynCrude. There is an estimated 10
percent volume loss during the upgrading process. Morichal 16, also
known as Cerro Negro, is a heavy (16.7 degrees API), mid-level sulfur
(3.26 wt percent percent), acidic (2.11 mg KOH/g) synthetic crude oil
with a high As concentration (84.1 ppb). It is also expected to produce
WVGO and VRES with high N (3050 ppm and 12,000 ppm, respectively) and
VRES with high Ni (1130 ppm) concentrations. Cerro Negro, which is
also known as Petromonagas, holds about around 35 billion barrels of
extra heavy oil in place. Initial recoverable reserves are estimated at
1.637 billion barrels of extra heavy oil and 1.112 tcf gas. Remaining
reserves are 1.05 billion barrels of extra heavy oil and 711 bcf
(2017). Heavy oil production began in 1999 and SynCrude production
began in 2001. The Cerro Negro-Petromonagas block production rate for
July 2010 was reported at 110,000 b/d. PDVSA operates the Cerro
Negro-Petromonagas block and holds an 83.33 percent stake. TNK-BP holds
the remaining 16.67 percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   9.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.7  deg. C.

Name: Murban (ITS) Jan22 '15
Comments:
Murban is a light, sweet crude oil with an API of 40.5 deg and 0.77 wt
percent Sulfur. It is composed from the output of five different fields

Abu Dhabi. Although production capacity is 1.4 million b/d, output in
2009 was held to 1.2 million b/d due to cuts in OPEC production
targets. Bab and Assab, the oldest producing field, started up 1963 and
1970, respectively. Murban is owned and operated by ADCO, a consortium
made up of Abu Dhabi National Oil Co. (Adnoc; 60 percent), BP (9.5
percent), Royal Dutch Shell (9.5 percent), Total (9.5 percent), Exxon
Mobil (9.5 percent) and Partex (2 percent). ADCO plans to expand
production capacity of the Sahil, Assab, and Shah fields, also known as
SAS, from its 2010 production rate of 1.4 million b/d to 1.8 million
b/d by 2017. ADCO also plans to boost production for Bab field from
300,000 b/d (2010) to 380,000 b/d and Bu Hasa from 555,000 b/d (2009)
to 730,000 b/d by 2017.

Name: Mutineer Exeter (ITS) '14
Comments:
Mutineer, also referred to as Mutineer-Exeter crude because it includes
the nearby Exeter field, is located off the Western Australian coast.
It is a light (43.1 degrees ), low sulfur (0.03 wt percent) crude oil.
Together, the two fields have an estimated 61.1 million barrels of
initial recoverable reserves of which, 0.7 million boe remain (2016).
In 2016, production averaged 1,200 b/d. Mutineer started up in 1997 and
 Exeter production began in 2002. Production is expected to cease in
2018. Output from both fields are tied back to the Modec Venture II
FPSO which can process up to 100,000 b/d and store 930,000 boe. Santos
operates the field and holds 37.5 percent interest. Other partners are
KUFPEC (37.5 percent) and JX Nippon Oil and Energy Corp (25 percent).

Name: Myton PL Mix (CVX) '10
Comments:
2010 sample and CVX assay . Myton is a category of Black wax which was
recently inspected. It used to be equity before it was sold to
Newfield. Myton is a sibling to Altamont crude which is aka Yellow Wax
Crude. However, there is no field of this name. Myton is an oil city in
Utah. It is not a field itself. The name is derived from the location
of the terminal. The PL itself is operated by Chevron. Much of the
black wax is on Ute Indian reservation and refineries are opting for
the cheaper Canadian crude now available. The Uintah Basin accounts for
the largest percentage of oil production in Utah, with its heavy
paraffinic Black Wax Crude. Much of it is trucked. The oil from this
area of Utah is known as "Uinta Basin Black Wax Crude" and has to be
refined differently than most types of oil. Myton gets its name from
the Myton Petroleum Pipeline Pumping Station. Chevron Pipeline Company
operates the Myton petroleum pumping station. It receives crude oil
from the company owned fleet of transport trucks for delivery into the
heated and insulated pipeline that makes its way to Salt Lake City. The
Myton station serves as an entry point to pipeline operations. Giving
that the crude is trucked, variation can result from the differing
volumes from the local producers. Typically this stuff is 31-32API

Name: Nare (Magdalena) Exp Bld (UNK)
Comments:
Nare crude oil is a medium gravity oil with a 20.4 deg API and 1.6 wt
percent sulfur. It is produced from onshore oil fields located in the
Nare Association contract area which covers the "Magdalena Medio"
region near the city of Puerto Nare, in the Antioquia State of
Colombia. The Nare Association consists of the Nare B block, which
contains part of the Teca block as well as the Moriche and Girasol
discoveries, and Nare A block, which holds part of the Jazmin field and
the undeveloped Chicala discovery. The Teca fields, which also covers
the Cocorn Association and Cocorn Concession, holds about 590 million
bbl of 12 deg API oil. With the aid of enhanced oil recovery
techniques, about 16 percent of the reserves will be recoverable. Oil
in place estimates for the Jazmin field is 225 million boe, Moriche is
21 million boe, and Girasol is about 33 million boe. Remaining
recoverable reserves for Teca, Jazmin, Moriche, and Girasol are 6, 20,
17, and 29 million boe, respectively. Production rates in 2009 were
3,400 b/d, 12,900 b/d, 3,600 b/d, and 3,300 b/d, respectively. Teca is
owned and operated by Ecopetrol while Jazmin, Moriche, and Girasol
interests are split between Mansarover Energy Colombia (50 percent) and
Ecopetrol (50 percent). Mansarover is a 50/50 joint venture between
Sinopec and ONGC.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  13.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.3  deg. C.

Name: Nemba (CVX) '16
Comments:
Nemba is a light gravity (37.5 degrees API), low sulfur (0.3 wt
percent) crude oil. It is produced from several fields offshore Cabinda
Area B in the lower Congo Basin located adjacent to the Cabinda
coastline offshore Angola. In 2006, Benguela-Belize-Lobito-Tomboco
(BBLT) in Block 14 came on stream and started contributing to the grade
and in 2013, the heavier Benguela field, which was sent to the Kuito
stream, was rerouted to Nemba making it a heavier grade. BBLT volumes
will vary and can contribute 10-14 percent to the Nemba stream. Nemba
came on stream in 1996 and has initial recoverable reserves of 756
billion boe. Remaining reserves (2017) is about 146 million boe. BBLT
initial reserves were 471 million boe, of which 104 million barrels
remain (2017). In 2016, Cabinda Area B production averaged 40,000 b/d
and BBLT production averaged 54,000 b/d. Chevron operates both the
Nemba and BBLT areas and holds 39.2 percent and 31 percent interest,
respectively. Other Nemba partners are Sonangol (41 percent), Total (10
percent) and Eni (9.8 percent) and BBLT partners are Angola Block 14
B.V. (20 percent), Eni (20 percent), Sonangol PandP (20 percent), Galp
Energia (9 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  26.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.8  deg. C.

Name: Nemba with Benguela Intermd't 12
Comments:
New Nemba Blend assay contains just over 12 vol percent Benguela Inter
Nemba is a light gravity (37.5 degrees API), low sulfur (0.3 wt
percent) crude oil that is produced from several fields offshore
Cabinda Area B in the lower Congo Basin located adjacent to the Cabinda
coastline offshore Angola. In 2006, Benguela-Belize-Lobito-Tomboco
(BBLT) in Block 14 came on stream and started contributing to the grade
and in 2013, the heavier Benguela field, which was sent to the Kuito
stream, was rerouted to Nemba making it a heavier grade. BBLT volumes
will vary and can contribute 10-14 percent to the Nemba stream. Nemba
came on stream in 1996 and has initial recoverable reserves of 757
billion boe. Remaining reserves (2014) is about 189 million boe. BBLT
initial reserves were 474 million boe, of which 198 million barrels
remain (2014). In 2013, Cabinda Area B production averaged 41,000 b/d
and BBLT production averaged 71,000 b/d. Chevron operates both the
Nemba and BBLT areas and holds 39.2 percent and 31 percent interest,
respectively. Other Nemba partners are Sonangol (41 percent), Total (10
percent) and Eni (9.8 percent) and BBLT partners are Angola Block 14
B.V. (20 percent), Eni (20 percent), Sonangol PandP (20 percent), Galp
Energia (9 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  24.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.3  deg. C.

Name: Nile/Sudan Exp Bld (SGS)'02
Comments:
2009 assay on Nile blend-- this including bamboo field.  Heavy sweet
Nile Blend crude is exported to Asia, with Japan and China the two
largest buyers of the direct-burning grade. The return to full volumes
could add up to 40,000 bpd of heavy sweet crude to the Asian market.
production total about 240K/d.
Sudan had proved oil reserves of 6.614
billion barrels at the end of 2007 or 0.53 % of the world's reserves.
So far Sudanese oil exploration has been limited to the central and
south-central regions.  The majority of proven reserves are located in
the south in the Muglad and Melut basins. Due to civil conflict, oil
exploration has been concentrated in the central and south-central
regions of the country.
The Sudanese crude oil is waxy in character,
has an average API degree of 32 and possesses no sulphur. The
paraffinic nature of the crude makes it a good feed stock for
lubricating oils.
REID VAPOUR PRESSURE <0.1psi
FLASH POINT <30F
COPPER below detection limit
LEAD below detection limit

Name: Niobrara (ITK) Nov 2 '13
Comments:
The Niobrara Shale formation, located in the Denver-Julesburg Basin
covering 42,000 square miles primarily in Northeastern Colorado and
parts of Wyoming, Nebraska, and Kansas, produces a light, low sulfur
crude oil with an API of 36.9 degrees API and sulfur content of 0.3 wt
percent. The Niobrara Shale play is still in early stages and is seeing
significant land leasing and acquisition activity. The area is expected
to hold billions of barrels of shale oil which will require extraction
techniques such as horizontal drilling and hydraulic fracturing. There
are several producers in the area including Fidelity Exploration and
Production, Japanese owned Itochu, CNOOC, Chesapeake, Marathon,
Marbueni, Noble Energy and EnCana. Niobrara shale production averaged
240,000 b/d in 2013 and is expected to increase to over 500,000 boe/d
by 2016.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  25.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.4  deg. C.

Name: Njord Exp Bld (Statoil) '08
Comments:
The Njord field has been developed with a floating steel platform,
Njord A, which has an integrated deck with drilling and processing
facilities. During the first phase of the field’s lifetime, the oil was
recovered using 11 production wells, while four injection wells sent
the gas back down into the reservoir, to provide pressure support. From
December 2007, a new phase will begin where gas from the field will
also be recovered. The field produces around 20,000 barrels of oil per
24-hour period, while gas exports is average six million cubic meters
per 24-hour period. Operator: StatoilHydro Location: Blocks 6407/7 and
6407/10, around 130 km northwest of Kristiansund and 30 km west of the
Draugen field. Production start: September 1997 Production: Oil and gas
Partners: StatoilHydro 20.00 per cent           E.ON Ruhrgas Norge AS
30.00 per cent           Gaz de France 20.00 per cent
ExxonMobil 20.00 per cent           Petoro 7.50 per cent

TAN value (unlike many other crudes from West Africa) and is suitable

good lube crude.
 N'Kossa is located in the Haute Mer Block.
N'kossa is an offshore field located in 550 feet of water, 36 miles
off shore Djeno terminal in the Congo. M'Boundi and Kouakouala output
are blended into the N'kossa Blend, lowering the 43 API to 41.

Name: N'Kossa Export Blend (CVX) '13
Comments:
N'Kossa is located in the Haute Mer Zone A Production Sharing Contract
area located in the lower Congo Basin offshore Congo (Brazzaville). The
N'Kossa stream includes output from the N'Kossa field, which came
onstream in 1996, and the N'Kossa South stream, which came onstream in
2004. Together, the fields had initial recoverable reserves of 344
million boe and 71 million barrels of LPG. As of year-end 2012, the
fields had 92 million boe and 22 million barrels of LPG remaining
reserves. Production in 2013 averaged 20,000 b/d of oil and 5,000 b/d
of LPG. N'Kossa output, as well as output from the nearby Tchibeli
field, is commingled at a large processing barge then transported
through a 60 km, 12 inch diameter pipeline to the Djeno terminal where
it is blended with Kitina crude. N'Kossa crude oil is light gravity,
low sulfur crude oil (39.7 degrees API and 0.06 wt percent sulfur).
Participants include Total SA, the operator, with 53.5 percent
interest, Chevron with 31.5 percent interest, and Societe Nationale
Petroles du Congo with 15 percent interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  21.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.9  deg. C.

Comments:
Norne is a light (29.6 degrees API), low sulfur (0.3 wt percent) crude

and the Urd field, which includes the Svale and Staer satellite fields.

and was tied back to the Norne FPSO which can process 220,000 b/d and
store up to 700,000 barrels of oil. The Norne area is located in blocks
6608/10 and 6608/11, approximately 124 miles from the Norwegian coast

which 63 million boe remain (2015). Liquids production in 2015 averaged

(6.9 percent) and Petoro (54 percent).
