Comments:
2010 sample and XOM assay. Tapis crude is produced offshore in South
China Sea, East of Peninsular Malaysia. Production is currently
apprx.300kbd.  The crude is loaded at Terengganu Crude Oil Terminal,
Kerteh, Malaysia.  The producing reservoirs at Tapis are Miocene Age
Group J (Tapis formation 1) sandstones that contain rim-type oil
accumulations with associated gas caps. The three primary reservoirs,
J-20, J-25, and J-30, are shoreface/barrier bar deposits separated by
shale sequences. Both faulting and stratigraphic variations cause
localized discontinuities across the field. Tapis Blend is a high
quality, extra light, low sulfur crude. It has high quality clean
products and conversion feed. The Tapis field was discovered in 1969.
Nearly all of Malaysia's oil comes from offshore fields. The
continental shelf is divided into 3 producing basins: the Malay basin
in the west and the Sarawak and Sabah basins in the east. Most of the
country’s oil reserves are located in the Malay basin and tend to be of
high qua

Name: Te Giac Trang (ITS) Sep '11
Comments:
Te Giac Trang (TGT), also known as the White Rhinoceros field, is
located in Block 16-1 in the Cuu Long Basin offshore Vietnam. The field
produces a light (39.5 deg API), low sulfur (0.05 wt percent) crude
oil. TGT is expected to come onstream in August 2011 with an initial
production rate of 20,000-30,000 b/d. Peak production is forecasted to
reach 45,000-50,000 b/d. According to Hoang Vu Joint Operating Co,
recoverable reserves are estimated at 190 million. Output will be tied

while the gas will be sent to the Bach Ho infrastructure through a 25
km pipeline. TGT is operated by the Hoang Vu Joint Operating Co, a

Name: Thang Long (PVEP) Jul 2 '15
Reference: Lam Son JOC via CSAT Singapore
Comments:
Thang Long, also referred to as Thanh Long, includes production from
the nearby Dong Do field. Both fields are located in the shallow waters
of the Cuu Long Basin offshore Vietnam. Thang Long and Dong Do initial
recoverable reserves were 8 million and 29 million boe, respectively.
Remaining reserves are 6 million and 22 million boe (2015),
respectively. First oil was achieved in Jun 2014 and production
averaged 15,000 b/d in 2015. Output is tied back to the PTSC Lam Son
FPSO which has a storage capacity of 650,000 boe. Thang Long is a light
(31.3 degrees API), low sulfur (0.12 wt percent) crude oil with a high
crude pour point (80.4 degrees F). The Lam Son Joint Operating Company,
which is a 50-50 joint venture between PetroVietnam and Petronas
operates the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  12.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   133.7  deg. C.

Name: THUMS (ITS) Jan 14 '15
Comments:
THUMS, which is derived from the original partners' names (Texaco (now
Chevron), Humble (now ExxonMobil), Unocal (now Chevron), Mobil (now
ExxonMobil) and Shell), is a heavy (18.1 degrees API), mid-level sulfur
1.57 wt percent), acidic (1.8 mg KOH/g) crude oil that is expected to
produce VGO and VRES with high N concentrations (3,870 ppm and 15,200
ppm, respectively). The THUMS project is the offshore portion of the
Wilmington field located 1.5 miles off the coast of California in the
Long Beach Harbor. It consists of four man made islands each named
after astronauts that died in the line of duty (Freeman, Grissom, White
and Chaffee). Since 1965, THUMS has produced more than 1 billion
barrels of oil. THUMS is owned and operated by Oxy Petroleum.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   4.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.0  deg. C.

Name: Thunder Horse (CVX) Jun 13 '14
Comments:
Thunder Horse is a blend of the Thunder Horse North and South fields
located in Mississippi Canyon 778 and 779, respectively, in the US Gulf
of Mexico. Together the fields hold 1.025 billion barrels of initial
recoverable reserves of which, 817 million barrels of oil remain
(2013). Thunder Horse South came on stream in 2008, followed by Thunder
House North in 2009. Production has fallen from a high of 187,000 b/d
achieved in 2009 to an all-time low at 42,000 b/d in 2013 due to
intermittent shut-ins. Thunder Horse crude is transported to the
Louisiana Offshore Oil Port (LOOP) storage and offloading facilities
via a 70 mile Proteus Oil Pipeline that connects to the South Pass
Block 89 booster station platform. From there, the Endymion Oil
Pipeline transports the crude to a Thunder Horse dedicated storage
facility at LOOP that has a capacity of 1.8 million boe. Thunder House
is a light (31.9 degrees API), low sulfur (0.97 wt percent) crude. BP
operates the field and holds 75 percent interest. ExxonMobil holds the
remaining 25 percent interest.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  18.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.2  deg. C.

Comments:
2010 sample from Nido-operated Tindalo crude in East palawan.  This
sample is from well 1.  The export is from the Tove Knutsen FPSO.
Commercial startup at the Tindalo oil field began May 2010. This is the
second oil field in the Philippines (the first being Galoc(36.4 API /
1.64wt% Sul) - which started up in Oct 2008). With recoverable reserves
of 5.1 MM barrels, initial plateauproduction rate of 7-15 kBD is
anticipated for Tindalo. The field is operated by Nido Petroleum
(42.4%) in partnership with Kairiki Energy (30.1%), Trafigura Ventures
(15%) and TG World (BVI) Corp (12.5%). Crude is 25.7-26.4*API with
about 2.4% sulfur and form of the sulfur is in the mercaptan form.
Crude is wet and water production is an issue.  Asphaltenes and MCR are
high as are the aromatics.  Crude is heavy and immature. Aluminium
below detection limit Boron below detection limit Calcium below
detection limit Chromium below detection limit Copper below detection
limit Potassium below detection limit Magnesium below detection limit
Phosphorus below detection limit Lead below detection limit Pour Point
below detection limit Silicon below detection limit Zinc below
detection limit Iron below detection limit

Comments:
The Tormore oil field is located offshore in the UK North Sea in Block

field will be developed with the nearby Laggan field and both are
expected to start up on Oct 2014. Output will be tied back to a new
Shetland Gas Plant at Sullom Voe. From there production will be sent to
the new Shetland Island Regional Gas Export System (SIRGE) then sent to

21 million and 14 million barrels of condensate, respectively, and are
expected to produce 2,000 b/d and 1,700 b/d, respectively, in 2014.
Total operates both fields and holds 80 percent interest. Dong Energy
holds 20 percent interest.

Name: Troll (XOM) '13
Comments:
Troll Blend is a light, low sulfur crude oil (35.2 degrees API, 0.1 wt
percent sulfur) produced offshore Norway in the North Sea. The blend is
made up of crude oil from the Troll B, Troll C, Fram,and Kvitebj rn. At
the end of 2010, Gj a and Vega fields were added. The Troll field is
located 65 km west of Kollsnes, near Bergen and comprises the main
Troll East and Troll West structures in blocks 31/2, 31/3, 31/5 and
31/6. Inital recoverable reserves were 1.849 billion boe, 308 million
barrels of LPG, 19 million barrels of condensate and 49.8 tcf gas.
Remaining reserves at the start of 2013 were 425 millon barrels of oil,
237 million LPG, and 34.78 tcf gas. The fields currently produce
126,000 b/d crude and 35,000 b/d LNG. Statoil, the operator of all the
fields, has a 30.58 percent interest in the main Troll field and the
remaining participants are Norway State DFI (56 percent), Royal Dutch
Shell (8.1 percent), Total (3.7 percent), and ConocoPhillips (1.62
percent).

Comments:

Kvitebj rn fields. At the end of 2010, Gj a and Vega fields were added.
The addition of Gjoa and Vega fields has resulted in the crude oil
becoming lighter, (API has gone up to 35.9 deg from 33.4 beginning in
2009). The Troll field is located 65 km west of Kollsnes, near Bergen
and comprises the main Troll East and Troll West structures in blocks
31/2, 31/3, 31/5 and 31/6. It contains 40 percent of total gas reserves
on the Norwegian continental shelf. The fields originally contained 47
trillion cubic feet of reserves and through 2008 have produced 1.4
billion barrels of crude oil since it came on line in 1995. The fields
currently produce 131,000 b/d of medium density low sulfur crude.
Statoil, the operator of all the fields, has a 30.58 percent interest
in the main Troll field and the remaining participants are Petoro (56
percent), Royal Dutch Shell (8.1 percent), Total (3.7 percent), and
ConocoPhillips.

Name: Tupi Exp Bld (INSP) '10
Comments:
Tupi, now known as Lula, is a pre-salt oil and gas field located in the
in the Santos Basin offshore Brazil, about 250 km from the southern
coast of Rio de Janeiro. Lula crude oil is a medium gravity, sweet
crude oil with an API of 28.8 degrees and a sulfur content of 0.365
weight percent. The field lies directly unter 2000 m thick salt layer
at a depth of 5000-5200 m below sea level. First oil was achieved in
May 2009 and the production rate reached a peak of 36,300 b/d in May
2011. Phase 1A of the full field start up is expected to begin on March
2015 and Phase 1B is anticipated to begin on 2019 and complete by 2021.
Production is expected to reach over 1 million b/d once the field is
completely developed. With over 6.914 billion barrels of oil and 4.1
tcf gas recoverable reserves, Lula is the largest oil discovery in the
Americas in more than 30 years. At year and 2011, about 6.892 billion
barrels of oil recoverable reserves remain. Petrobras operates the
field and holds 65 percent interest. Other partners are BG with 25
percent interest and Galp Energia with 10 percent interest.

Name: Umm Shaif (Total) '10
Comments:
Umm Shaif is located north-west offshore Abu Dhabi in water depths of
about 18 m. It was discovered in 1958 and began producing in January
1962. Umm Shaif's initial reserves were estimated at 4.033 billion boe
of which about 756 million boe remain (2011). Although production
capacity is at 250,000 b/d, the production rate was held to 213,000 b/d
in 2010 because of OPEC cuts. Production capacity is expected to
increase to 300,000 b/d once the Umm Shaif gas injection project is
completed sometime in 2012. Umm Shaif is a light crude (36.9 degrees
API) with a sulfur content of 1.44 wt percent. Output is processed in
the Umm Shaif super complex then transported to the Das Island terminal
via two main oil lines that have a combined capacity of over 40,000
b/d. Abu Dhabi Marine Operating Co. (Adma-Opco), a joint operating
company comprised of Abu Dhabi National Oil Co. (Adnoc, 60 percent), BP
(14.67 percent), Total (13.33 percent) and Japan Oil Development Co.
(12 percent) owns and operates the field. In 2018, the concession is
set to expire and it is unclear if Adnoc will continue with the
existing partnership or open the contract area to new players through a
competitive bidding process.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  23.3 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.0  deg. C.

Name: Urals Ex Novorossiysk  (CVX) '09
Comments:
Urals crude oil, formerly known as REB28 (Russian Export Blend), is
Russia's main export blend. It is a light, medium sulfur crude with an
API of 32.7 degrees and sulfur content of 1.03 weight percent. The
blend is composed of the output of several Russian fields that are
transported through the Transneft pipeline, with the exception of YK
Blend, Vityaz Blend, Sokol, Espo Blend, and Siberian Light, which have
their own dedicated Transneft export routes. In 2009, Urals production
averaged 9.4 million b/d with exports totalling about 4.1 million b/d.
Urals is exported through the Primorsk, Novorossiysk, and Yuzhny
loading ports. Together, Rosneft, Lukoil, TNK-BP, and Surgutneftegas
hold 68 percent interest of all 2009 Russian oil production. Gazprom
Neft, Tatneft, Russneft and Bashneft account for about 18 percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  16.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   134.2  deg. C.

Name: Usan (XOM) '13
Comments:
The Usan oil field is in the OML 138 license, formerly OPL 222 license,
located 70 km offshore Nigeria in the eastern part of the deepwater
Nigeria. The field includes the Usan and Usan West fields which will be
developed together and tied back to the 180,000 b/d processing capacity
and 2 million boe storage capacity Usan FPSO. Future plans include
developing the Ukot field, located in OML 139 license, and tying back
the output to the Usan FPSO when it comes online in 2020. Usan came
online in February 2012 and Usan West is expected to startup in 2014.
Peak production from both fields is expected to reach 160,000 b/d by
2015. Usan and Usan West holds recoverable reserves of 525 million boe
and Ukot holds 60 million boe. Total is the operator of the field and
holds 20 percent interest with partners Chevron Corporation 30 percent,
ExxonMobil 30 percent, and Nexen Inc. 20 percent. Usan is a medium
gravity, low sulfur crude (31 degrees API and 0.2 wt percent sulfur)
that is predicted to have a high nitrogen concentration in the vacuum
residuum (13,800 ppm).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  19.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.8  deg. C.

Comments:
Varg is a  Talisman (Canadian Co)-operated, light, low sulfur North

contract and the expectation that the nearby fields will be tied backto
Varg beginning in late 2010.  Grevling is the largest of these
satellites—its quality is unknown as of this writing. HI- measured valu

Name: Waimea Exp Bld (ITS) '11
Comments:
Located in the in the BM-C-41 Block in Brazil s offshore Campos basin,
the Waimea field was discovered in February 2010 and production is
anticipated to start in June 2011 through an extended well test (EWT)
which is expected to register 20,000 b/d. Output will be tied back to
the OSX-1 FPSO. Full scale production is not expected to begin until
2013. Waimea holds an estimated 500 - 900 million boe reserves, however
since it is still early in the appraisal process and there is not much
production history in this area, Waimea's actual recoverable reserves
are uncertain. Waimea has three reservoir sections, all carbonates in
the Lower Cretaceous. The shallowest reservoir is the Albian and
contains 20 deg API oil. Waimea is a medium sulfur (1 weight percent
sulfur), heavy gravity (19.8 degree API) crude oil. OGX Petroleo e Gas
is the sole operator and owner of the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   8.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   130.6  deg. C.

Name: West Seno-Bangka Mix (LEMIGAS) '
Comments:
West Seno crude is a light (34.8 degrees API), low sulfur (0.1 wt
percent) crude oil that is produced in the Makassar Strait production
sharing contract (PSC) area, near East Kalimantan, Indonesia. Initial
reserves are 36 million barrels of oil and 514 bcf gas. Remaining
reserves are 3 million barrels of oil and 322 bcf gas (2015). The field
started up in 2003 and is currently producing 3,300 b/d (2015). Oil and
gas production is sent onshore to the Santan Oil Terminal via a 62 mile
pipeline. From there, most of the gas is sent to the Bontang LNG plant
and the remaining gas is used domestically. Owners include Chevron
(operator, 72 percent), Sinopec Group (18 percent), and Pertamina (10
percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  39.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   139.9  deg. C.

Districts 8, 8A and 10, and parts of eastern New Mexico and other
fields located in the Permian Basin. The crude streams are collected
and transported via pipelines to Midland, Texas then to Cushing,
Oklahoma for sale. WTI is a benchmark crude for pricing US crudes.

Name: Western Canadian Select (CVX) Ap
Comments:
Western Canadian Select (WCS), the benchmark for heavy, sour Canadian
crude oil, is a heavy sour dilbit (diluted bitumen) with an API of 21.9
degrees and sulfur content of 3.3 wt percent. It consists of
conventional and bitumen crude oils sourced from Mackay Heavy, Bow
River, Cold Lake, Western Canadian Blend (WCB) and/or Christina Lake
and blended with sweet synthetic and condensate diluents. WCS is
blended in at Hardisty, Alberta and then shipped to various locations
in Canada and the US. Since coming on stream on December 2004, WCS has
shown a consistent cyclic trend in API gravity ranging from a low of
19.2 degrees API to a high of 21.6 degrees API. Output in 2009 averaged
230,000 b/d. Producers to the blend include Canadian Natural Resources,
Cenovus Energy, Suncor Energy, and Talisman Energy.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  20.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   143.9  deg. C.

Comments:
White Rose is a light gravity (31.6 degrees API), low sulfur crude oil

White Rose consists of the main White Rose field and three satellite
fields, White Rose South, White Rose West and North Amethyst, which are
tied to the SeaRose FPSO which is moored in 115 m of water and has a
storage capacity of 940,000 boe. White Rose started up in November 2005
and North Amethyst came on stream in May 2010. Production in 2014
averaged 55,000 b/d. Initial recoverable reserves is 392 million boe,
of which 152 million remain (2015). Husky Energy operates both the main
White Rose field and the satellite fields and holds 72.5 percent and
68.9 percent interest, respectively. Other joint venture partners are
Suncor (27.5 percent White Rose field and 26.1 percent Satellite
fields) and Nalcor Energy (5 percent Satellite fields only).

Name: Willmar (MAX) Oct '13
Comments:
Bakken Formation, a large rock unit from the Late Devonian to Early
Mississippian age, is one of the largest continuous oil formations that
spans about 200,000 square miles (520,000 km2) of the subsurface of the
Williston Basin, covering northwestern South Dakota, and southern
Saskatchewan and Manitoba, Canada. Bakken contains 3 to 4.3 billion
barrels of technically recoverable oil. Production began in 1953 and
cumulative production through 2008 was 135 million boe. The development
and application of horizontal drilling and horizontal fracturing have
increased activity in the area. Production in 2011 reached 600,000 b/d.
Oil is transported through the North Dakota Pipeline System, a 161,000
bpd pipeline operated by Enbridge Energy Partners, LP. The 330-mile
crude oil gathering and 620-mile interstate transportation system
gathers crude oil from points near producing wells to Clearbrook, Minn.
From there, it is either connected to the Lakehead System, a 1,900 mile
pipeline system that transports crude oil from Western Canada to the
Gulf Coast, or to a third-party pipeline that transports crude oil to
refineries in the Minneapolis/St. Paul area. Other modes of
transportation include rail and truck. Several companies are operating
in the Bakken formation; most notable are Continental Resources, EOG,
Whiting, ConocoPhillips, Statoil, and Hess. Bakken, a light crude that
ranges from 39-46 degrees API, accounts for 10 percent of the US daily
production.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  28.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.7  deg. C.

Xan, located in Guatemala's North Peten sub-basin, is Guatemala's
largest oil field. Perenco is operator. load port is Santo Tomas Be
Castilla.  Coban is onshore oil. production from these fields is not
prolific. segregation is rich in H2s (800 ppm in oil), has about 20C
cloud. ACID, WHOLE CRUDE <0.01
*** The GC Analysis Covers   7.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   131.9  deg. C.

Name: Xijiang (CNOOC) '12
Comments:
Xijiang is a medium gravity (29 degrees API), low sulfur (0.107 wt
percent) crude oil with a high pour point (96.7 degrees F). The Xijiang
area, which includes the XJ 04, 15/11D and 15/22D blocks, is located in
the South China Sea in Block XJ04 in the Pearl River Mouth Basin.
Initial recoverable reserves are 540 million boe, of which 77 million
boe remain (2014). Production started in 1994 and the area is producing
35,000 b/d (2014). Output is tied back to the FPSO Hai Yang Shi You 115
which can process 40,000 b/d of oil and store 1 million boe. CNOOC owns
and operates the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers   1.7 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.0  deg. C.

Name: Xikomba Exp Bld (BP) '05
Comments:
This assay is in the public domain. Both BP and XOM have equity.  XOM
is operator.   Xikomba is deepwater development in Angola, West Africa,
is located in the northwest corner of Block 15, approximately 230 miles
(370km) northwest of Luanda in water depths of up to 4,850ft (1,480m).
The field was discovered in 1999. The recoverable reserves have been
put at around 100 million barrels of oil equivalent. The Xikomba
development is divided into two parts - Xikomba A and B. First oil from
Xikomba A was achieved in 2004, with a production plateau at around
80,000 barrels per day. Xikomba B first oil is expected in early 2006,
which will increase the combined recoverable resources to approximately
100,000 barrels per day Xikomba has been developed by subsea wells tied
back to a combined floating production and storage ship. The FPSO  is
Xikomba MERCURY <1.00
*** The GC Analysis Covers  18.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.1  deg. C.

and 11, contain 33 million bbl of 30-35deg -gravity crude and condensate
and 284 bcf of gas.

Name: Yetagun Condensate (ITS) '12
Comments:
Yetagun is an offshore gas and condensate field located in the southern
Gulf of Martaban, offshore Myanmar (Burma) in Blocks M-12, M-13, M-14
an M-15. Production started in May 2000. Condensate production averages
11,000 b/d (2015). Condensate produced in the field is tied back a FSO
then transferred to shuttle tankers for export. Yetagun holds 83
million barrels of condensate of which, 38 million barrels of
condensate remain (2015). Petronas Carigali (40.9 percent) operates the
field. Other partners are MOGE (20.46 percent), Nippon Oil Exp Myanmar
is METI (19.32 percent), and PTTEP (19.32 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  68.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.8  deg. C.

Name: YK Blend aka Varandey (INSP) Nov
Comments:
YK Blend, also known as Varandey or Arctic Light, is produced from the
onshore Yuzhno Khylchuyuskoye, also known as South Khylchuyuskoye,
Kharyaga fields located in the Arctic Nenets region in NW Siberia,
Russia and transported via the Kharyaginskoye - South Khylchuyuskoye -
Varandei pipeline to the Verandey Export Terminal. YK Blend is a light
(35.1 degrees API), low sulfur (0.6 wt percent) crude oil that is
expected to produce a high mercaptan naphtha (308 ppm). The fields
started up in 2008 and recoverable reserves have been downgraded from
505 million boe to 316 million boe due to the field's difficult
geological structure.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  15.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   142.3  deg. C.

Name: Yoho (XOM) '13
Comments:
Yoho (YOH401) is produced from the Yoho and Awawa reservoirs in the Oil
Mining Lease 104, located in shallow waters 25 miles offshore of
eastern Nigeria. Yoho is a light sweet crude with an API of 40.1
degrees and 0.095 wt percent sulfur. The crude is expected to produce
vacuum residuum that is high in Nitrogen (10,200 ppm). ExxonMobil has a
40 percent equity stake and operates the field through their affiliate,
Mobil Producing Nigeria Unlimited (MPN). Nigerian National Petroleum
Company owns the remaining 60 percent. Initial production began in
2002, however full field startup did not begin until 2006. It is
estimated that recoverable reserves are at 481 million bbl, of which
109 million boe remain (2012). Yoho s reported output in 2012 was
66,000 b/d.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  25.6 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   136.0  deg. C.

Name: Zaafarana Exp Bld (3rd) '07
Comments:
Zaafarana oil field is located 6.5 km offshore in the northern province
of Egypt’s Gulf of Suez region some 25 Km to the south of Ras Abu El
and 10 km north of Ras Zaafarana. In June 2005, the Zaafarana Field was
estimated to have original oil in place of some 294 MMbbls. The
ultimate proven reserves were set at 89.90 MMSTB. Production comes from
7 wells operated by ESP (electric submersible pumps) employing a unique
Cable Deployed Production System (CDPS). The extracted crude is
processed and stored on an FPSO with a capacity of 80,000 bbls. PICO
operates Amal, Zaafrana, and Gemsa fields.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  11.1 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   137.2  deg. C.

Name: Zafiro (Total) '12
Comments:
The Zafiro field, also referred to as New Zafiro due to the merging of
the crude with nearby Topacio field production during the mid-2005, is
located offshore of Bioko Island, Equitorial Guinea in Block B. It
covers a 5,000 square km area and includes production from several
other fields. Zafiro was the first field to go online in August 1996.
Topacio started up in 1997 and Opalo came onstream in 1999. In 2001,
Jade, Opalo East, Rubi and Serpentina fields started production. Zafiro
holds initial recoverable reserves of 1.163 billion boe of which, 263
million boe remain (2103). In 2013, production averaged 92,000 b/d.
Zafiro is a light gravity, low sulfur crude oil (30.6 degrees API and
0.27 wt percent sulfur) that is expected to produce a vacuum residuum
with a high Nitrogen content (12,900 ppm). In 2005, the Serpentina FPSO
replaced the Zafiro Producer FPSO. The field is operated by ExxonMobil
(71.25 percent). State-owned Compania Nacional de Petroleos de Guinea
Ecuatorial (GEPetrol) owns the remaining 23.75 percent.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  15.8 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.6  deg. C.

Name: Zafiro Exp Bld (XOM) '08
Comments:
The Zafiro fields, which include the Zafiro, Jade, Opalo, Sausage, and
Serpentina reservoirs, covers an area 5,000 square kilometers offshore
of Bioko Island, Equitorial Guinea in Block B. The field began
production in August 1996 and had initial recoverable reserves of 1.113
billion boe. Zafiro is also referred to as New Zafiro due to the
merging of the crude with nearby Topacio field production in mid-2005.
In 2010, the average production rate for New Zafiro, a medium gravity,
low sulfur crude oil (30.6 deg API and 0.27 wt percent sulfur), was
138,000 b/d. As of January 1, 2011 about 286 million barrels remain. In
2005, the Serpentina FPSO replaced the Zafiro Producer FPSO. The field
is operated by ExxonMobil who also has a 71.25 percent stake.
State-owned Compania Nacional de Petroleos de Guinea Ecuatorial
(GEPetrol) owns the remaining 23.75 percent stake.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  16.0 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   132.7  deg. C.

Name: Zakum Lower Exp Bld (ITS) Apr '1
Comments:
The Lower Zakum field is the ADMA operated portion of the large Zakum
field located offshore Abu Dhabi midway between Das Island and Abu
Dhabi. The field was discovered in 1963 and came onstream in 1967. Oil
in place at Zakum Lower is estimated at 16 billion boe, of which 4.211
billion boe are recoverable and about 737 million boe (2012) remains.
In 2011, production averaged 300,000 b/d. The field is split into two
zones, Zakum West and Zakum Central, each of which have super-complexes
where the crudes are processed. Zakum West and Zakum Central are linked
by a 175,000 b/d capacity, 10 km, 24-inch pipeline. The crude is then
transported via a 310,000 b/d capacity pipeline to ADMA's processing
and export terminal on Das Island. Lower Zazkum is a light gravity ( 40
degrees API), low sulfur crude oil ( 1 wt percent). It is owned and
operated by the Abu Dhabi Marine Operating Company partners which
include Abu Dhabi National Oil Company (60 percent), BP (14.67
percent), Jodco (12 percent) and Total SA (13.33 percent).
*** The GC Analysis Covers  23.2 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   135.7  deg. C.

Name: Zakum Upper (ITS) May 9 '14
Comments:
Zakum Upper is a light gravity, medium sulfur crude oil (33.9 degrees
API and 1.9 wt percent sulfur) produced from the Upper Zakum, Umm Al
Dalkh and Satah fields of the ZADCO Contract Area, offshore Abu Dhabi
in the Eastern Gulf Basin. The Zakum field, including the upper
reservoirs that is now known as the upper Zakum field, began producing
in 1967, however full production of the Upper Zakum grade did not start
until 1982. Umm Al Dalkh came on stream in 1985 and Satah started up in
1987. Initial recoverable reserves, including expired Arzanah field,
were 14.07 billion boe and about 9.63 billion boe remain (2014).
Production averaged 590,000 b/d in 2014. The oil and gas produced from
the three fields are piped to Zirku Island for processing, storage, and
export. Zakum Development Company (ZADCO), a consortium consisting of
Abu Dhabi National Oil Company (60 percent), ExxonMobil (28 percent)
and Japan Oil Development Company Limited (12 percent), owns and
operates the field.
*** The GC Analysis Covers  20.4 LV%  of crude up to a TBP of   138.4  deg. C.
